<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 0103EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Castro-Mexico     12-02 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Castro-Mexico,0836</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Castro's Old Haunts Gone, But Nostalgia Remains</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First available for Friday AMs</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Mexico, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of the bars, cafes and hotels where Fidel
Castro lived and plotted his successful invasion of Cuba three
decades ago are gone, but a few people still remember the bearded
revolutionary _ or think they do.
   Castro lived here for 18 months as an exile, but where he took
his meals and hung out are questions that only he, or maybe his
younger brother Raul, can say for certain.
   Castro returned to Mexico City on Wednesday for the first time in
32 years, this time for Thursday's inauguration of Carlos Salinas de
Gortari. It was clear he had fond memories as he strode off his
plane to a red-carpet welcome and saluted the crowd jovially.
   ``This is my second homeland, I'm thrilled to be back,'' said
Castro, 61.
   When he first arrived here on July 8, 1955, Castro was an almost
penniless young lawyer. His sister, Lidia, had to sell her
refrigerator to raise money for the trip from Havana.
   Fidel and his brother, Raul, had just spent almost two years in a
Cuban prison for leading an unsuccessful but now legendary attack on
the Moncada barracks in a first effort to overthrow dictator
Fulgencio Batista.
   The brothers quickly set to work organizing a network of Cuban
exiles into a secret invading force. They lived as inconspicuously
as possible, although the Cuban Embassy naval attache did take
notice and made several inquiries about them with Mexican
authorities.
   ``They weren't important people and there were a lot of exiles
here in those days. So there was no reason for anyone to take much
notice of them,'' said a retired military officer who worked in
security for a time. He asked to remain anonymous.
   One of the few who remembers Castro is Filiberto Clemente, the
cashier at the Bar Latino, a block from the Inter-American Regional
Labor Organization.
   ``They used to sit there,'' Clemente, 52, said in a recent
interview, pointing to a corner table. ``I was very young then, a
sort of waiter's helper.''
   ``Castro _ Fidel, I mean _ used to eat Spanish food. He drank
little, cognac sometimes. And also manzanilla, a (sherry-like)
Spanish drink,'' Clemente said. ``He used to live a few blocks from
here, at the Hotel Oxford.''
   At Hotel Oxford's seedy bar, a white-haired barkeeper in her
mid-60s also said she remembered Castro.
   ``He used to come here often because a lot of Cuban girls were
living here at the time. But he did not live here,'' said the woman,
who refused to give her name.
   ``He lived around the corner, at the Hotel Mariscala, which used
to be known before as La Casa de la Zorra,'' she added. The Hotel
Mariscala is gone.
   Castro is supposed to have had breakfast often at the Cafe
Habana, around the corner from a gym where the conspirators worked
out daily.
   The Habana still stands on the corner of Morelos Avenue and
Bucarelli Street, but the last owner and the old cook both died
recently.
   At the Labor Organization, Castro used to chat with other Latin
American exiles, among them Luis Alberto Monge, the organization's
general secretary, and Romulo Betancourt. Monge later became as
president of Costa Rica and Betancourt of Venezuela.
   As his movement grew to about 60 fighters, Castro split them into
secret cells of 10 each and moved them to separate safe-houses.
   Among those Castro enlisted was Alberto Bayo, a Cuban-born
officer who fought with the Republican army during the Spanish Civil
War.
   In his memoirs, Bravo wrote the Cubans trained by jogging along
Insurgentes Avenue, Mexico City's main north-south thoroughfare, and
by climbing Iztaccihuatl and Popocatepetl, two volcanoes to the
southeast.
   The Cubans moved to a rundown ranch near Chalco, a town 21 miles
southeast of the capital, and continued training while disguised as
workmen.
   On June 20, 1956, Castro and two of his men were arrested, and on
July 2 police raided the ranch and arrested a dozen fighters. They
were released with help from former Mexican President Lazaro
Cardenas, a leftist sympathizer and a power in Mexican politics.
   Cardenas was the father of Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the man Salinas
beat in a disputed election July 6. Many Mexican leftists feel
Castro is lending support to an illegitimate government by attending
the Salinas inauguration.
   Castro and his men ended up on the Yucatan Peninsula, 122 miles
from Cuba, where they bought a battered 38-foot yacht, the Granma,
from an American named Robert B. Erickson.
   The small band of Cubans repaired the boat and set off on a
stormy nine-day trip to Cuba and into history on Nov. 16, 1956. A
25-month guerrilla war followed, until Batista fled and Castro
seized power on Jan. 1, 1959.
</TEXT>
