<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Thousand-DollarTicket     12-02 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thousand-Dollar Ticket,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suburban Philadelphia Residents Say $1,000 Parking Tickets Are A
Crime</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HORSHAM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Ricci was incredulous when a
policeman slapped his son with a $1,000 parking ticket for illegal
parking in front of the family home.
   ``I flipped,'' Ricci, a retired policeman himself, said recently.
   But neither he nor others ticketed under a new ordinance are
getting sympathy from officials in this suburban Philadelphia
township, where an ordinance passed Sept. 13 specifies the fine _
and court costs of $23 _ in an effort to keep narrow cul-de-sacs
clear for emergency vehicles.
   ``If a fire engine cannot get in there because of the way cars
are parked, there is a danger to the lives of the people,'' said
township Solicitor Thomas Del Ricci. ``When you consider the value
of human life, I don't think $1,000 is unreasonable.''
   Ricci's 25-year-old son, Ken, was tightening battery cables under
the hood when an officer approached him Nov. 22. Moments later, he
was showing his father the citation.
   The elder Ricci, who retired to Horsham from Philadelphia
``because I wanted peace and tranquility,'' has company in his
disbelief.
   ``We were astounded,'' said Tom Cowgill, an insurance agent who
was ticketed that same night when he and his wife, Betty, were
visiting their grandchildren.``I thought it was ridiculous, but talk
to my wife and you'll hear a different story. They were scraping her
off the wall.''
   At least 11 car owners have received thousand-dollar tickets so
far.
   Del Ricci said judges have discretion to suspend part of the
fine. But District Justice Richard M. Price, who expects to be
hearing the cases, said the way the ordinance was written requires
him to assess the full $1,000.
   The first court hearings are scheduled for the end of December,
but Price said he expects the Township Council, which meets Tuesday,
to change the ordinance and give him some flexibility.
   ``I hope this comes out as funny as it seems,'' said Cowgill,
``because I'm not going to pay that $1,000. You might have to visit
me in jail at Christmas.''
</TEXT>
