<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bush-List     12-02 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-List,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Appointment Still On Hold</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush acknowledges his
selection of a defense secretary has been moving at a slower pace
than expected, saying apparent front-runner John Tower ``knows that
the process takes a while.''
   Last week, Bush's designated chief of staff, John Sununu,
indicated the president-elect would name his defense team this week.
   But the only appointment Bush has made in five days is that of
White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, who will keep the job he now
holds.
   Bush was also expected to move swiftly on his secretary of
commerce, with most bets on Robert Mosbacher, a Houston oilman who
is close to the vice president.
   Sources at the Bush transition office, speaking on condition they
not be named, said Mosbacher's appointment has been slowed because
of the background checks required for him and his numerous
businesses.
   In the case of Tower, the former Texas senator, there has
reportedly been infighting in the Bush camp over his appointment.
Speculation is that Bush wants to get his defense team in place
before he names Tower.
   ``We're trying to be prudent and do the proper work required to
back up appointments at all levels,'' Bush said Thursday.
   Bush was asked about the reports that Tower is a paid consultant
to several major defense contractors.
   ``Any time there seems to be stories that may be hurtful to
somebody it concerns me no matter who it is,'' he said. ``Senator
Tower's a friend of mine but he knows that the process takes a while
to go forward.''
   _ In other transition news, the name of former Wyoming House
Speaker Warren Morton has surfaced as a possible secretary of the
interior. Environmentalists object to Morton, whom they consider too
pro-development.
   Another possibility is Bob Broadbent, director of the Las Vegas,
Nev., airport and former commissioner of the bureau of reclamation.
Sen. Dan Evans of Washington has also been mentioned, as has
Michigan Gov. Bob Milliken.
   Some conservatives are also pushing Robert Teeter, the
co-director of the transition office, for the post at interior.
Teeter has been offered the position of deputy White House chief of
staff, but he hasn't accepted it yet.
   _ Evans is also mentioned for energy secretary, but former
Louisiana Rep. Henson Moore's name is heard more often.
   _ Mike Deland, the regional Environmental Protection Agency
administrator in Boston, is still the leading candidate. Francis
Blake, former agency general counsel, is also a possiblity.
   _ The Heritage Foundation, a conservative think tank, is pushing
former Transporation Secretary Elizabeth Dole to become the U.N.
ambassasdor. She is the wife of Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole,
R-Kan.
   _ Rep. Jack Kemp of New York, a failed GOP presidential
candidate, is reportedly eyeing the job as secretary of Housing and
Urban Development. Both Bush and President Reagan attended a
testimonial dinner for Kemp Thursday night.
   _ Rep. Bob Dornan, a hard-line conservative from California, has
let it be known that he'd like to be the new drug czar in the Bush
administration. A new name also surfaced for that post, former
baseball commissioner Peter Ueberroth. Ueberroth was once mentioned
for the job at Commerce, but that's apparently Mosbacher's for the
taking.
</TEXT>
