<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Fauntroy-Savage     12-02 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fauntroy-Savage,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Illinois Candidate Says D.C. Job was Stuffing Envelopes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressman's son who was running for office
in Illinois while on the payroll of the District of Columbia's
delegate to Congress says his House job consisted of little more
than stuffing envelopes on a part-time basis.
   Thomas John Savage's job came under scrutiny after The Associated
Press reported Tuesday that he claimed residency in Chicago and was
running for an Illinois House seat while on the payroll of Del.
Walter Fauntroy, the district's non-voting delegate to Congress.
   Savage, son of Rep. Gus Savage, D-Ill., earned $21,398 while on
Fauntroy's payroll between September 1987 and June 1988.
   In order to run for state representative in Illinois, he had
filed a sworn statement declaring that he had lived continuously for
two years in the district he sought to represent.
   House rules, meanwhile, say employees may work only in the
member's office or district _ in Fauntroy's case, the nation's
capital.
   When the issue was raised, Fauntroy said Savage worked diligently
on behalf of a bill that would have granted statehood to the
district. But on Thursday, Savage told The Washington Post that he
did no work on statehood, and only showed up for work on a part-time
basis.
   ``We didn't call out much (on statehood issues),'' Savage told
the Post. He said he spent most of his time at work ``putting
packages (of statehood material) together and getting them out.''
   The rest of the time, Savage said, he spent ``working around the
Hill,'' occasionally attending a hearing or dropping by the House
District of Columbia offices.
   Fauntroy was not immediately available to comment on the apparent
contradiction between his and Savage's assessment of Savage's job
duties.
   The latest disagreement followed statements by Savage that he had
lobbied congressmen on the statehood effort; Fauntroy had said
Savage had been working with grassroots organizers.
   Fauntroy also said Savage used House District of Columbia
Committee offices and phones to do his lobbying work, but Capitol
Hill staffers said Thursday that Savage did not use their offices.
City officials active in the statehood movement said they had never
met or heard of him.
   D.C. Council Chairman David Clarke and council members Hilda
Mason and Betty Ann Kane, all three of whom are active on statehood
issues, said they did not remember meeting Savage.
   Others have placed Savage in Chicago at the time he was on
Fauntroy's payroll and living in Washington.
   House rules require employees to regularly report to work in the
member's Capitol Hill or district offices. Illinois election laws
require candidates to live continuously for two years in the
district they intend to represent. Savage signed an affidavit three
months after he went to work for Fauntroy verifying his residency in
Illinois.
</TEXT>
