<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Suspect In Studio Gunbattle Wanted in Albuquerque Shopping Mall
Slayings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with man in Universal shootings is suspect
in bagel shootings in Albuquerque, i.d. of shot guards, other
details; no pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man wanted in a New Mexico
rampage that claimed three lives was arrested Thursday night after a
security guard at Universal Studios was shot to death and another
was wounded, authorities said.
   Nathan Nick Trupp, 42, the subject of a nationwide manhunt
following the shooting deaths Tuesday at a bagel shop in an
Albuquerque shopping mall, was shot and wounded Thursday by Los
Angeles County sheriff's deputies, said Deputy Roger Hom.
   The gunman walked up to a guard shack at an employees entrance to
Universal Studios shortly before 6 p.m. and opened fire, officials
said.
   Minutes later, deputies and a third guard spotted a man they
believed to be the gunman about a block away and ``engaged in a
gunbattle,'' wounding the man, said Van Mosley, a sheriff's
spokesman at the scene.
   What provoked the shooting was not immediately known. ``We have
absolutely no clues,'' said Dan Slusser, general manager of the
studio, a popular tourist attraction.
   Trupp was in critical condition at St. Joseph Medical Center in
nearby Burbank after surgery for gunshot wounds to his chest and
arm, said nursing supervisor Eric Chew.
   Home identified the dead guard as Jason Beeks, 27, of La
Crescenta. The wounded guard, 20-year-old Armando Torres, was in
critical condition with a gunshot wound to the head at St. Joseph's,
Chew said.
   Universal Studios, 10 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles, is
home to the Universal Studios amusement park, and movie and
television studios and offices.
</TEXT>
