   Only 41 tickets have been sold for the
wrestle-and-rock music extravaganza that soul singer James Brown was
required to produce as part of his probation, but the show will go
on Sunday, organizers say.
   The Augusta-Richmond Civic Center can hold up to 7,500 people for
an event like ``Wrestle-Rock '88.'' But by 5 p.m. Thursday only 41
of the $10 tickets, which went on sale Nov. 22, had been sold, said
the center's general manager, Larry Rogers.
   ``It's probably the worst advance ticket sales I've seen since
I've been in Augusta,'' Rogers said.
   Brown's lawyer, Buddy Dallas, said the show featuring his client
would go on despite the poor sales.
   Proceeds will go to the Aiken, S.C., Fraternal Order of Police,
which accepted the show to fulfill a condition of Brown's probation.
Money will also go to Helping Hands, a shelter for abused children,
and the Leukemia Society.
   Brown was placed on probation last summer and given a suspended
sentence of 2{ years after he pleaded guilty to carrying a pistol,
resisting arrest and possession of PCP in a May 18 incident near his
Beech Island, S.C., home.
