<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Shooting,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Shoot And Wound Gunman In Central London, Free Hostage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police shot and wounded a gunman in the busy
theater district today after he grabbed a bystander and held him
hostage 2{ hours, dragging him through streets lined with crowded
restaurants and pubs, Scotland Yard said.
   The hostage, who was seized in a scuffle after the gunman
apparently tried to mug someone else, was unharmed, police said.
They said the gunman was taken to a hospital with a chest wound. His
condition was not immediately known.
   More than 200 police, many carrying rifles, rushed to the
Trafalgar Square and St. Martin's lane area late Thursday where
crowds of theatergoers were either heading home or dining in
restaurants.
   Jane Chandler, a radio producer with the British Broadcasting
Corp., said she was in a pub and ran to a room upstairs to telephone
her office. She found herself sharing the room with two police
marksmen.
   ``I looked out of the window and I could see this skinhead
holding a dark-haired man around the neck and shoving a gun near his
head. The police were calling out: `Stop it, give it up.'
   ``The hostage was in a complete daze and the gunman kept dragging
him up and down the street from the Strand to Chandos Place and into
Maiden Lane...
   ``There were still people from the restaurants wandering about
and the police were trying to clear them but they were like helpless
chickens because they didn't know where he was going to go next.
   ``(Later) they (the police) had the man cornered in the alley and
I heard over the police radio an order to engage and saying they
should open fire if they had a clear shot. Then I heard the bang and
it was all over.''
   Neither the gunman nor the hostage was identified.
   Police trailed the gunman and his hostage through side roads
lined with theaters and restaurants as other officers sealed the
area, ordering pedestrians and traffic off the streets.
   An officer with a bullhorn appealed to the gunman to surrender
and release his hostage, a Scotland Yard statement said. The gunman
ignored the plea so the marksman shot him, the statement said.
   Police said the incident began at about 10.30 p.m. Thursday and
ended just after 1 a.m. on Maiden Lane, a narrow road near Trafalgar
Square in central London.
   Brian Last, manager of Rules restaurant on Maiden Lane, said
armed police told the 50 diners and staff there to stay inside with
the doors locked and keep away from the windows.
   Free-lance journalist Edmond Hall, said, ``We could see a man...
holding what looked like a small caliber revolver at a man lying
between his legs.''
   The British domestic news agency Press Association said the
gunman was thought to have tried to fire the gun several times but
that it misfired each time.
</TEXT>
