<HEAD>$24 Billion Buys A Lot Of Oreos, Triscuits, Del Monte Peaches</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-RJR Nabisco-Reax, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rivers of sliced peaches, mountains of cookies
and forests of filter-tipped cigarettes could be bought with the
more than $24 billion being spent to acquire RJR Nabisco Inc.
   If all the money were spent on Oreo cookies, they would overflow
every grain elevator in Toledo, Ohio; Buffalo, N.Y.; Chicago; and
Fort Worth, Texas.
   The $24 billion would buy enough Del Monte sliced peaches to keep
Niagara Falls going at full flow for more than half an hour.
   If every dime went into Winston cigarettes, there would be enough
so F. Ross Johnson, the chief executive of RJR Nabisco who lost the
bidding, could chain-smoke for 70,000 centuries.
   Viewed another way, the $22 billion in debt that RJR Nabisco will
carry under its new ownership is greater than the combined foreign
debts of Burma, the Congo, Cyprus, Honduras, Mali, Nepal, Niger and
Oman.
