<HEAD>Explosion Rocks Syrian-Policed West Beirut, At Least Two Injured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with details, quotes. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion rocked a Syrian-policed west
Beirut neighborhood today during the morning rush hour. At least two
people were wounded, police said.
   A police spokesman said the 8 a.m. bomb was planted under a car
only 50 yards from a Syrian army checkpoint in the Lower Mossaitbeh
district.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named in line with standing
regulations, said the explosion shattered glass in the neighborhood.
   A witness said a private car evacuated ``two wounded men from the
scene.'' Police could not say if the wounded were Syrian soldiers.
   Syrian troops, according to the witness, ``fired their automatic
rifles in the air to make way for the car carrying the wounded
men,'' then sealed off the area.
   The Moslem-run Voice of the Nation radio station, based in west
Beirut, said the explosion was caused by ``a small bomb planted
under a car parked in an empty lot near the Syrian checkpoint.''
   Syria, the main powerbroker in Lebanon, maintains about 40,000
troops in eastern and northern provinces as well as west and south
Beirut.
   The explosion may have been part of a campaign to discredit the
Syrians as peacekeepers. Scores of such attacks have been reported
since the Syrians moved into Beirut in 1986 to end militia rule.
   The blast came after a series of house raids mounted by the
Syrians to halt renewed violence between rival Shiite Moslem
factions.
   The pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, and the Syrian-backed
Amal, Arabic for hope, fought for six days late last month. By
police count, 40 people were killed and 87 wounded in the
confrontation.
</TEXT>
