<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Britain-Food     12-02 0126</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Britain-Food,0128</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Changing Global Weather Pattern Brings Threat of Famine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crop failures and famine will become more
widespread unless action is taken immediately to curb emission of
``greenhouse gases'' from burning fossil fuels and tropical rain
forests, a report said today.
   ``The delicate balance of gases in the atmosphere is changing,''
the Economist Intelligence Unit said in its annual report on food
and beverage trends. ``This is leading to significant changes in
global weather patterns and hence in crop yield patterns.''
   This year's drought in the United States, which reduced the
cushion of stocks against poor grain crops next year, was one of
several climatic anomalies in 1988, the report said.
   Another drought would reduce stocks to ``dangerously low''
levels, it said.
</TEXT>
