<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 0536EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shuttle-Photos     12-02 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Photos,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More News Organizations Protest Air Force Camera Order</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More news organizations have
protested a Defense Department demand that they surrender their film
of the launch of the space shuttle Atlantis in the event of an
accident.
   Some organizations removed their remote cameras from the area of
the launch pad, where the flight of the Atlantis was postponed
Thursday for at least 24 hours because of poor weather. Other news
organizations accepted the requirement, but under protest.
   After Air Force officers disclosed the new policy Wednesday, The
Associated Press, The New York Times and Newsweek magazine refused
to sign the agreement and were denied permission to place remote
cameras at the launch site. The AP described the arrangement as
``military censorship.''
   Later Wednesday, the Florida Times-Union withdrew its agreement
and its cameras. Gannett News Service did the same Thursday after
the launch was postponed.
   The remote cameras, focused on the base of the launch pad, are
1,500 to 2,500 feet away and are activated by the tremors and sounds
of liftoff. Photographers are kept about four miles from the launch
pad.
   The agreement gives the Defense Department the right to review
any film of an accident and to keep any it feels would disclose
classified information.
   Air Force Lt. Col. Ron Rand said the department needs to ensure
that no photos show the classified payload, which might be exposed
in an accident. Experts believe the payload to be a spy satellite.
   The Air Force agreement had not been required for other shuttle
missions with military payloads. Rand said it is linked to NASA's
signed agreement with news groups before the Discovery shuttle
launch Sept. 29, the first launch after the Jan. 28, 1986, explosion
of the Challenger.
   ``NASA had a written agreement, so we needed something in
writing,'' Rand said.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration agreement lets
news organizations process their own remote-camera film and give it
to investigators only after using what they need. NASA eventually
would return all film.
   ``We felt the agreement reached after the Challenger explosion
was sufficient. This one didn't sound definitive enough,'' said
Foster Marshall, Times-Union assistant managing editor for graphics.
   At least a dozen news organizations accepted the agreement.
Several said they would leave their cameras at the site while they
made formal protests and their lawyers studied the requirement.
   ``We will formally protest because it is an unreasonable and
silly attempt to impose censorship after the launch,'' said Sam
Terilli, general counsel for The Miami Herald.
   ``I thought it was a bad precedent,'' said Ron Cohen, executive
editor of Gannett News Service. ``...The demand that film be
confiscated was a clear case of a federal agency making an arbitrary
decision restricting First Amendment rights.''
   The Gannett cameras were put in place before the news service's
executives were aware of the new policy, and were removed at the
first opportunity, which was after Thursday's launch was scrubbed,
Cohen said.
</TEXT>
