<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     12-02 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Die In Bomb Attack On Presidential Campaign Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese militants fired guns and
threw bombs at a presidential campaign rally, killing five people
and wounding 25, authorities said today.
   Eleven gunmen staged the attack during a rally Thursday night in
suburban Colombo for Ossie Abeygoonsekera, candidate of the United
Socialist Alliance, authorities said.
   The victims included one of Abeygoonsekera's bodyguards and
Devabandara Senaratne, vice president of the Sri Lanka People's
Party, one of four parties that form the alliance, officials said.
   It was the second attack in less than a month on a campaign rally
for Abeygoonsekera. On Nov. 17, suspected Sinhalese militants threw
bombs at another campaign meeting, killing three people and injuring
50.
   All three candidates in the Dec. 19 presidential election have
received death threats from the People's Liberation Front, a radical
Sinhalese group demanding the government's resignation.
   But Abeygoonsekera has been the only candidate to criticize the
front, which has been blamed for more than 900 political murders in
the past 16 months.
   According to police, six gunmen hijacked a passenger bus and
drove to the rally site in Kadawatte, about 10 miles north of the
capital. Five other gunmen were waiting among the spectators, police
said.
   ``While the extremists opened fire from the bus, the others at
the meeting flung five bombs,'' said one police official, who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   They escaped in the bus and another car, the official said.
   Sinhalese militants are upset at the government's efforts to end
the 5-year-old insurgency by minority Tamils fighting for a separate
homeland.
   They contend a peace accord signed in July 1987 grants too many
concessions to the Tamils, who make up 18 percent of the island's 16
million people.
   The Sinhalese make up 75 percent of the island's population and
control the government and the military.
   Sinhalese militants have been demanding the resignation of
President Junius R. Jayewardene's government.
   Jayewardene, a Sinhalese, is not seeking re-election and has said
he will step down and dissolve Parliament after his successor is
chosen.
   Besides Abeygoonsekera, the other candidates are Prime Minister
Ramasinghe Premadasa of the United National Party, and Sirimavo
Bandaranaike, former prime minister and leader of the Sri Lanka
Freedom Party.
</TEXT>
