<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To punctuate or not to punctuate.
   That is the question about the 11-acre peninsula in this southern
Maine town owned by President-elect George Bush.
   The New York Times, Los Angeles Times and The Associated Press
spell Bush's summer estate, Walker's Point, with an apostrophe.
   USA Today and the local newspaper, the Journal Tribune, drop the
apostrophe, making it Walkers Point.
   A map by the Chamber of Commerce uses an apostrophe, but local
tax records do not.
   In his autobiography, ``Looking Forward,'' Bush spells the name
of the peninsula with an apostrophe.
   But the apostrophe may be wrong, said Don Orth, the executive
secretary of the U.S. Board on Geographic Names.
   In 1890, a group of professors and scholars ruled that most
proper names in place names are merely labels and do not require the
possessive apostrophe, Orth said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elvis Presley fans can add a touch of The
King to their holiday mail with a special Graceland postmark.
   The postmark, which will be hand-stamped on mail deposited in a
mailbox in the visitor center across from Graceland, shows
snow-covered Christmas trees next to the tourist attraction mansion,
with the Graceland logo in an old English typeface below.
   The postmark says ``Graceland Christmas Station, Memphis, Tenn.,
38116,'' and will be dated.
   Memphis artist Robbie Joyner drew the artwork for the postmark.
   Beth Benton, a communications specialist for the Postal Service,
said special cancellations draw a lot of attention, especially from
collectors.
   ``They've been around for a long time. They are real popular,
especially for something like Graceland. It was a lot of fun to do
this with them,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Bob Miller takes over as governor
in January, he'll qualify for three titles: governor, acting
governor and lieutenant governor.
   ``Call me Bob,'' Miller said Thursday.
   Miller, currently the lieutenant governor, will replace Gov. Dick
Bryan, who was elected Nov. 8 to the U.S. Senate, when Bryan takes
his seat in Washington.
   Common usage and protocol will dictate that Miller be given the
title governor during the next two years.
   There's no reference to ``acting governor'' in the Nevada
Constitution. So Miller's title technically remains lieutenant
governor.
   State Archivist Guy Rocha said he spotted just one reference to
the term ``acting governor'' in state law, dealing with the salary
of lieutenant governor when acting as governor.
</TEXT>
