<HEAD>Snowy Skies Over Ohio and Pennsylvania</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A foot of snow blanketed northeast Ohio and almost as much fell
on western Pennsylvania early this morning, but the weather was mild
in the central and western parts of the nation.
   Snow was scattered from northeast Ohio into western Pennsylvania,
and across the eastern portions of Pennsylvania and New York state.
   In Ohio, 10 to 12 inches of snow covered northern Ashtabula
County and 9 to 12 inches were recorded in Lake County.
   In Pennsylvania, 6 inches of snow were measured in many parts of
Erie County, and up to 10 inches fell on Crawford County.
   In the Pacific Northwest, rain spread over the Washington coast
and extreme northwest Oregon ahead of a cold front anchored off the
Pacific.
   Today's forecast called for widespread rain through western
Washington and western Oregon; foggy conditions during the morning
over valleys of northern California and southwest Oregon; and widely
scattered snow through the eastern shores of the lower Great Lakes.
   Highs were forecast to be in the 20s in northern Maine; in the
30s through the Great Lakes, the central and northern Appalachians,
northern New England, northern Utah and much of Idaho; in the 60s
over central California and Arizona, northern Texas, Oklahoma, the
central Plains, western South Dakota, the lower Mississippi Valley,
the central Gulf Coast and the northern two-thirds of Florida; in
the 70s in southern Florida, southern Texas, southern California and
parts of the desert Southwest; and in the 40s and 50s elsewhere.
   Temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 7 degrees at Idaho Falls,
Idaho, to 67 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
