<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 0833EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NATO 1stLd-Writethru   12-02 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0474,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Defense Ministers' Meeting Ends</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with meeting ending, communique. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO defense ministers tackled the
potentially divisive issue of how to fairly share the cost of
maintaining the alliance, officials said today at the conclusion to
a two-day meeting.
   The defense ministers agreed ``there are significant variations
in the scale and nature of their contributions,'' but the final
communique said Europe and the United States remained steadfast
partners.
   ``Once and for all it is clear this is not a matter of the United
States versus the rest of the alliance, this is a joint alliance
effort,'' NATO Secretary-General Manfred Woerner said.
   However, U.S. Secretary of Defense Frank Carlucci stressed the
report showed ``nations are not bearing a fair share of the common
defense burden,'' an issue that caused U.S. congressional critics to
raise the prospect of withdrawing some of the 326,000 U.S. troops
stationed in Europe.
   Carlucci said it was now NATO's task to create an ``effective
follow-up in a manner that serves to strengthen the cohesion of the
alliance and allied defense capabilities.''
   Woerner said the meeting achieved that. ``We did not only deliver
words but deeds,'' Woerner said. ``We did not only speak of
improving our defense effort and burden sharing but we took
decisions.''
   The ministers approved additional funds for transferring U.S.
F-16 fighter jets from Spain to Italy and cleared the way for a
study on a multinational European military unit in northern Central
Europe.
   A 79-page report approved Thursday has already produced a number
of specific commitments by members to improve their contributions,
Britain's secretary of state for defense, George Younger, said.
   The report asked Belgium, Norway, Denmark, the Netherlands, West
Germany, Canada, Portugal and Spain to make bigger budget
contributions.
   ``The differences between some individual national contributions
are glaring,'' said the report, which urged most European allies to
boost defense spending, upgrade military equipment and become more
active partners.
   The report offered a response to U.S. critics who claim Europe is
not doing enough to maintain NATO's strength, officials said.
   Guy Coeme, defense minister for Belgium, warned the report should
``not be used for mutual reproaches'' but to boost the ``collective
effort'' for common defense.
   The report went beyond analyzing the financial cost to highlight
the social cost of the European allies who provide facilities,
territory and troops to maintain a credible defense in Europe.
   Many European nations proposed additional efforts, officials
said, including a plan to introduce a multinational European
military unit in northern Central Europe.
   The project is only in the initial stage of study but Younger
urged NATO as a whole should profit from the intitiative.
   The report estimated the United States spent an average 5.98
percent of its economic output on defense from 1983 to 1987. Tops
was Greece, which spent 6.52 percent.
   Britain devoted 5.01 percent of its gross domestic product to
defense; Turkey 4 percent, and Germany 3.2 percent.
   Others were: Belgium, 3.26 percent; Canada, 2.17 percent;
Denmark, 2.2 percent; Italy, 2.16 percent; Luxembourg, 1.18 percent;
Netherlands, 3.32 percent; Norway, 2.93 percent; Portugal, 3.22
percent; and Spain, 2.37 percent. Iceland was not included in the
table.
</TEXT>
