<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kidnap 30 Children, Demand Plane To Leave Soviet Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hijack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed men commandeered a bus loaded with
schoolchildren and teachers and demanded a plane to leave the
country, an official said today.
   All the hostages are safe, and the hijackers were in control of a
plane that was provided for them, Albert Vlasov, head of the Soviet
news agency Novosti, said at a news conference.
   He spoke after airport officials in Israel and Cyprus said the
plane had left for Tel Aviv. But Vlasov would not say whether the
plane had taken off.
   He did not say who the hijackers were, or say how many there
were, but added that they wanted to go to Israel, South Africa or
Pakistan.
   ``A group of armed bandits hijacked a bus with 30 school children
and a teacher and demanded a plane to deliver them abroad,'' Vlasov
said.
   He said the incident began Thursday in the city of Ordzhonikidze
in southern Russia, just north of the Georigian republic.
   ``In order to save the children and the teacher a decision was
made to give a plane,'' Vlasov said. He said all the hostages were
now safe.
   ``The terrorists have the plane now,'' he said.
