<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChinaWhite     12-02 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China White,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Arrested In `Designer Drug' Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CASSANDRA BURRELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The arrests of seven people suspected of
manufacturing and distributing the synthetic drug ``China white,''
which has been linked to 13 deaths, has shut down one supplier of
the drug, police said.
   Authorities suspect as many as 60 people overdosed on the
``designer drug'' methylfentanyl, which was sold by itself or mixed
with heroin or cocaine, Allegheny County Coroner Joshua Perper said.
The drug also is suspected in seven other deaths, he said.
   The drug produces a euphoria similar to that of heroin but is
hundreds of times more powerful. The small quantities needed to be
effective makes it more difficult to detect.
   Police informants say the drug has disappeared from the street in
the last 10 days, Assistant Police Chief Chester Howard said.
   The arrests shut down one Pittsburgh source of the drug, but
there may be other sources, Police Chief Ralph Pampena said.
   Tom Schaefers, 48, a professional chemist, was arrested Thursday
night at his home in suburban Aspinwall, police said. Officers
confiscated eqiupment from a basement laboratory in the house, where
Schaefers lived with his elderly parents.
   ``We feel he's the one who put it together,'' said Detective
Barry Fox. ``All of our evidence points to that.''
   Arrested earlier Thursday in raids on five Pittsburgh-area homes
were Donald Sunkin, 39, of Springdale; Donald Hurley, 31, of
Bellevue; John Hricak, 42, of Bellevue; Richard Williams, 33, of
Harmarville; Mary Kathryn McNally, 38, of New Kensington,
Westmoreland County; and Brenda Ragland Smith, 40, of Bellevue.
   They were arraigned before U.S. Magistrate Robert C. Mitchell,
who ordered them held at Allegheny County Jail pending the bond
hearings today.
   All six were charged with conspiracy to manufacture and
distribute the drug. Smith, Sunkin, Williams and McNally also were
charged with distribution and with contributing to the death of Jay
Duschl, 38, of Verona, who died June 2 after taking the drug.
</TEXT>
