<1ST_LINE>u i PM-KALBombing 1stLd-Writethru a0490 12-02 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-KAL Bombing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0490,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Begin Questioning Woman In KAL Bombing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with testimony. CHANGES byline. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who claims to be a North Korean
agent said today she hates North Korean leaders for ordering her to
blow up a South Korean jetliner last year with 115 people aboard,
news reports said.
   Kim Hyon-hui, 26, made the comment when government prosecutors
questioned her behind closed doors to determine her role in the
destruction of a Korean Air (KAL) Boeing 707 that disappeared near
Burma Nov. 29, 1987.
   She has said she planted a bomb aboard the plane.
   Hundreds of students demanding a parliamentary probe into Miss
Kim's case battled riot police today at Seoul's Yonsei University.
Students hurled firebombs and rocks at riot police, who retaliated
with tear gas grenades, but there were no immediate reports of
injuries in the one-hour clash.
   Government prosecutors, who must determine whether to file formal
charges against Miss Kim, said she admitted most allegations against
her and aplogized for what she had done. They declined to elaborate
on their interrogation.
   Local newspapers said Miss Kim's voice cracked when she told
prosecutors she had killed many people and must be be punished.
   Miss Kim strongly denounced North Korea President Kim Il Sung and
his son and heir apparent Kim Jong Il, according to Yonhap, the
South Korean news agency. ``Now, I hate them most,'' she was quoted
as saying.
   It was Miss Kim's first public appearance since Jan. 15, when she
confessed in a televised news conference to being trained and
ordered by North Korean leaders to bomb the plane to disrupt this
year's Olympic Games in Seoul.
   North Korea and South Korea have been bitter rivals since their
land was divided in 1945. The North wanted to be a co-host of the
Olympics.
   Miss Kim has been in custody of the Agency for National Security
Planning, the main South Korean intelligence organization, since she
was extradited from Bahrain to Seoul last year.
   Tight security was in force hours before she arrived at the Seoul
District Prosecutor's office. Hundreds of plainclothes police were
posted on the streets and atop nearby buildings.
   Miss Kim arrived in a sedan, accompanied by two intelligence
officers. Unlike most suspects, she was not wearing handcuffs.
   Yonhap, quoting unidentified prosecution sources, said the day's
questioning also centered on Miss Kim's family and educational
background in North Korea.
   Miss Kim and a male companion, traveling on forged Japanese
passports, were among passengers aboard the KAL flight from Baghdad,
Iraq to Seoul. The couple, posing as father and daughter, left the
plane during a stopover in Abu Dhabi.
   They took poison when police tried to question them at Bahrain
Airport. The man died.
   Under South Korean law, Miss Kim's appearance before the
prosecution was to determine whether formal charges should be filed
against her. If formal charges are filed, she will be put on trial.
   Miss Kim, if found guilty, could be sentenced to death under
South Korea's Criminal Code and national security and aviation laws.
</TEXT>
