<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BhopalAnniversary     12-02 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bhopal Anniversary,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Street Protests On Fourth Anniversary Of Carbide Gas Leak</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BHARAT DESAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actors decorated in dollar signs pranced in
the streets and posters called for boycotts of Union Carbide
products today on the eve of the fourth anniversary of the world's
worst industrial accident.
   The death toll from the Dec. 3, 1984, gas leak at the Union
Carbide pesticide plant has reached 3,329, according to the Madhra
Pradesh state government. In the last four months, at least 188
people have died of lingering effects of the methyl isocyanate gas
they inhaled, officials said.
   ``We are registering more than one death a day because of the
effects of the gas,'' Gas Relief Commissioner S. Sathyam said in an
interview.
   A year ago, the death toll recorded by Sathyam and his staff
stood at 2,850.
   Activist groups and opposition politicians have called for two
days of demonstrations to commemmorative the disaster and press for
relief for the victims. A $3 billion damage case filed by the Indian
government against Union Carbide, a Danbury, Conn.-based
multinational, has yet to be resolved.
   Police set up barricides around the derelict pesticide plant,
which was operated by Union Carbide's Indian subsidary, in an effort
to thwart any attempts to invade the deserted premises.
   The Communist Party of India has vowed that some of its followers
will force their way inside on Saturday.
   Local theater groups today sent actors into nearby streets
dressed as devils. Garbed in black costumes decorated with white
dollar signs, the actors denounced what they called the imperialism
of multinational corporations.
   Speaking in Hindi, they enacted skits in which doctors demanded
huge sums of money to treat gas victims and vote-hungry politicians
made unfulfilled promises of relief.
   Posters appeared around Bhopal, a city of 1 million, calling for
boycotts of batteries and other Union Carbide products manufactured
in India.
   Another opposition party, the Bharatiya Janata, pitched a tent
opposite the Union Carbide plant, recited Hindu scriptures and
prayed for the souls of the gas victims.
   The gas leak began when liquid methyl isocyanate leaked out of a
storage tank and turned into deadly vapor as it hit the air. Union
Carbide maintains that sabotage by a disgruntled employee caused the
leak.
   The Indian government claims it was the result of negligence.
</TEXT>
