<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Kidnap, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0470, 0460, 0414,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Letter From Kidnapped Swiss Urges Government to ``Save My Life''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Swiss urged to leave Lebanon,
letter authenticated, Shiites say U.S. hindering release of its
hostages. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A kidnapped Swiss Red Cross worker today
sent a letter urging Switzerland to cooperate with his captors to
``save my life.''
   The Swiss government said the hijacking and the letter, which was
authenticated by the International Committee of the Red Cross, is an
attempt to force the release of a Shiite Moslem hijacker held in
Switzerland.
   The government urged all Swiss people to leave Lebanon.
   In Beirut, the spiritual guide of pro-Iranian Shiite militants
charged that Washington has hindered the release of the nine
American hostages.
   ``I have information that the Americans are the ones who
complicated the issue of the hostages,'' Sheik Mohammed Hussein
Fadlallah said in an interview today in the weekly magazine
Ash-Shiraa.
   ``America is after resuming ties with Iran. But it wants ties
resumed without making any political concession.
   ``Iran rejects a resumption of ties unless America changes its
hostile policy toward Iran and works out some details related to
bilateral relations, including the frozen Iranian assets,'' said
Fadlallah.
   He was referring to assets frozen in the United States after
militants stormed the U.S. Embassy in Tehran in November 1979 and
held 52 Americans hostage for 444 days.
   In Bern, Foreign Ministry official Edouard Brunner said Peter
Winkler's letter said his abduction was intended to pressure the
Swiss government.
   ``I was not kidnapped as a Red Cross delegate but as a Swiss
citizen. My government knows what my kidnappers want from it and it
has to cooperate in order to save my life,'' said the letter.
   Swiss authorities say they have not received demands from the
kidnappers and nobody has claimed responsibility for Winkler's
abduction.
   But, ``it looks very much like blackmail,'' Brunner told a news
conference.
   The plane hijacker arrested in Geneva is Hussein Hariri, 22, a
Lebanese Shiite Moslem who commandeered an Air Afrique jetliner to
Geneva in July 1987. He killed a French passenger before being
overpowered and arrested.
   Hariri is to go on trial on various charges Feb. 20 in
Switzerland's supreme court. He could face life imprisonment.
   The letter was received earlier today by a Western news agency in
Beirut. It is the first news of Winkler, 32, since he was abducted
at gunpoint Nov. 17 in the southern Lebanese city of Sidon.
   Further abductions cannot be excluded, Brunner said. The
government urged the 150 to 200 Swiss citizens living in Lebanon to
leave and told all Swiss to avoid traveling there for non-essential
reasons such as tourism, he said.
   The all-Swiss Committee of the Red Cross suspended its operations
in Sidon after Winkler's abduction and withdrew five other delegates
based in the city.
   Brunner said Switzerland will ask Syria, Lebanon, Iran and the
Palestine Liberation Organization to help secure Winkler's freedom.
   ``We appeal for the help of all governments who might be able to
use their moral and political influence,'' he said.
   Winkler's committee said in a statement that his abduction is
``an unacceptable attack against its humanitarian mission'' and
appealed for ``absolute respect'' of its personnel.
</TEXT>
