<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PoliceComplaints     12-02 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Police Complaints,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Chief Ordered To Pay $170,000 To Man Whose Home Was Raided</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police Chief Daryl Gates was ordered by a jury
to personally pay $170,000 to a man whose nose was broken and whose
house was ransacked by anti-gang police officers searching for a
murder weapon.
   A U.S. District Court jury deliberated less than two hours before
reaching its verdict Thursday and making the award to the family of
Jessie Larez.
   Gates denounced the decision, saying it was based on faulty
evidence.
   Comments Gates made earlier this week to reporters, in which he
said that Larez was lucky that only his nose was broken, were
admitted into evidence during the trial.
   ``The integrity of the whole system of justice at the federal
level clearly mandated that these proceedings be declared a
mistrial,'' the chief said.
   Mayor Tom Bradley issued a statement urging that the verdict be
overturned.
   If the judgment is upheld, the City Council must decide whether
the city or Gates would have to pay the damages.
   The Larez family's attorney, Stephen Yagman, said the family will
only accept the punitive award if it comes out of Gates' pocket.
   ``We want to send a message to Daryl Gates and to City Hall that
this kind of lawless behavior among officers that he has ratified by
his own comments and behavior will no longer be tolerated by members
of this community,'' Yagman said.
   In October, the same jury awarded $90,000 to the Larez family
after family members testified that police conducting the 1986 raid
broke Larez's nose, pulled the hair of one of Larez's daughters,
intimidated other members of the family and broke personal property.
   That judgment, against the Police Department, involved six gang
detail officers. The department delayed a decision on appealing the
award pending Thursday's verdict.
   During the second portion of the trial, concluded Thursday, the
jury had to determine whether Gates was accountable for actions of
officers who raided the Larez home in search of a murder weapon used
in a gang slaying. The weapon was never found.
   Speaking to reporters Tuesday outside the courtroom of Judge
Robert M. Takasugi, Gates angrily denounced Yagman, Larez and the
jury. Yagman has brought several civil suits against various police
agencies over the years.
   ``How much is a broken nose worth?'' the chief asked. ``Given the
circumstances in this case ... I don't think it's worth anything.
Larez is probably lucky that's all he had broken.
   ``People keep asking me, `Chief, why don't you do something about
gang killings?' I tell my officers, `Why don't you do something
about gang killings?' And we do something, and then juries give
$90,000.''
   Deputy City Attorney Jeff Nelson, who defended the police
department in the case, called Takasugi's decision to allow Gates'
comments as evidence ``very, very damaging.''
   Nelson defended Gates' remarks, saying ``he is entitled to fair
comment just like anyone else.''
</TEXT>
