<2ND_LINE>PM-EEC Summit, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0471,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Argues With Belgian Leader Before EEC Meeting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with Thatcher, Martens squabble,
meeting opening, other detail; no pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RHODES, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain
told the Belgian premier today that his refusal to extradite a
pro-IRA priest has undermined confidence between their countries,
British officials said.
   A British spokesman, who demanded anonymity, told reporters:
``Mrs. Thatcher spoke to Premier Wilfried Martens of being mystified
and deeply wounded and of confidence being dented.''
   Martens told reporters he defended his position during the
private meeting with Mrs. Thatcher. His aides said her attitude was
``acerbic.''
   The confrontation came just before the start of a European
Economic Community summit during which the 12-nation west European
trade bloc will review progress in moves to create a borderless,
single-market Europe by 1992.
   Officials said the European leaders would seek to reassure the
United States and Japan, the EEC's main trading partners, that
efforts to boost trade within the European Economic Community will
not be at the expense of imports.
   A draft statement states that a single EEC market will also
benefit ``non-community countries. 1992 Europe will not close in on
itself ... will not be a fortress Europe but a partnership Europe.''
   Earlier today, a bomb damaged an EEC Commission office in Athens,
270 miles from the meeting site. It was one of four that exploded in
the Greek capital. Police said no one was injured.
   The left-wing Revolutionary Popular Struggle claimed
responsibility.
   The EEC leaders, accompanied by their foreign ministers, started
the meeting with a luncheon hosted by Greek Premier Andreas
Papandreou, the summit's chairman.
   The summit was being held at the Knights' Palace, a 14th century
castle. Greek commandos armed with automatic weapons stood guard on
the battlement of the castle gate as the leaders arrived.
   This morning, Mrs. Thatcher also met with West German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl, and officials said they agreed it would be useful to
have a summit meeting of the leaders of the 16 NATO nations in
London in May or June 1988.
   A meeting between Mrs. Thatcher and Charles Haughey, the Irish
prime minister, was canceled by Haughey, who was said to be upset
over Mrs. Thatcher's criticism of Ireland for failing to extradite
the pro-IRA priest.
   Last week Belgium turned down Britain's request to extradite the
priest, Patrick Ryan, and sent him instead to the Irish Republic,
where he has taken refuge with an undisclosed religious order.
   Ryan, 58, had been held in a Belgian jail since his arrest in
June.
   Belgium said the British extradition warrant, citing unspecified
charges of conspiracy to murder and to bomb, was flawed.
   In the meeting with Martens, Mrs. Thatcher attacked the Belgian
premier over the extradition of Ryan, whom British police suspect
was involved in a string of Irish Republican Army bombings and other
terrorist related offences.
   Martens said he told Mrs. Thatcher, ``this decision was taken
completely legally ... it was not a political decision.''
   The IRA, outlawed in Britain and Ireland, is fighting to end
British rule in Northern Ireland and unite the Protestant-dominated
province with the Irish republic under leftist rule.
</TEXT>
