<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shoreham     12-02 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shoreham,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislature Refuses To Deal With Shoreham Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Legislature has allowed Gov. Mario
Cuomo's deal to buy the $5.3 billion Shoreham nuclear plant for $1
to fall through, leaving the utility free to try to open the
generating station.
   State lawmakers wrapped up a special session Thursday without
taking action on a bill to approve the deal Cuomo worked out in June
with Shoreham's owners, the Long Island Lighting Co. By failing to
act, Cuomo and the utility said the Legislature missed a deadline
that bound both sides to the agreement.
   The governor predicted Thursday night that the deal was over and
that state lawmakers had effectively decided to open Shoreham.
   ``As far as I'm concerned, tomorrow, 12:01, Dec. 2, 1988, you
ought to think of it as Black Friday,'' said Cuomo, who added that
allowing the deadline to pass could prove to be one of the ``most
tragic blunders that this Legislature ever made.''
   But the utility offered no indication of its plans.
   LILCO scheduled a meeting of its board of directors today in
Hicksville to discuss ``our future course regarding the
settlement,'' according to utility spokesman James Lois. Lois would
not speculate about what options LILCO might consider.
   The deal called for the state to buy the $5.3 billion Shoreham
facility for $1 and dismantle it. In return, the utility would get
guaranteed rate hikes over the next decade totaling more than 60
percent.
   The state, under the auspices of the New York Power Authority,
would build non-nuclear power plants to provide LILCO with the
electricity it would lose if Shoreham doesn't open, the deal also
stipulates. Cuomo says Shoreham should not be allowed to open
because crowded Long Island couldn't be safely evacuated in the
event of a serious nuclear accident.
   The Legislature's refusal to act on a Shoreham bill this week was
due mainly to the determination by the nine state senators from Long
Island, all Republicans, that the agreement as now written would be
too generous to the utility and cause rates to go up higher than
they have to for the utility's customers.
   Most of the discussion at the Capitol Thursday night in the wake
of the Legislature's departure was over whether the passing of the
midnight deadline really meant the end of the deal.
   The pro-agreement Citizens to Settle Shoreham group said
legislators had ``for all practical purposes opened Shoreham.'' That
organization called Long Island legislators ``gutless'' for not
dealing with the issue.
   According to Lois, the Shoreham agreement stipulates only that
the parties involved are ``free to withdraw'' starting today, not
that the pact falls apart.
   But Cuomo argued by the time any new agreement is reached,
Shoreham could be on its way to winning a license to operate from
the federal Nuclear Regulatory Commission and LILCO would lose its
incentive to renegotiate the pact.
   The governor maintained that the plant could be licensed to
operate as early as Dec. 12.
</TEXT>
