<2ND_LINE>PM-Highway Killings, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0556,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fear Serial Killer Could Be Connected With Bodies Found Near
Highways</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with search resuming; picks up
12th graf pvs, `Officials undertook ...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of five bodies, four of
them confirmed to be women, have been found along two highways in
southeastern Massachusetts, prompting worry that a serial killer
might be behind the deaths.
   ``There are things that are not coincidence, that are in
common,'' Bristol County District Attorney Ronald A. Pina said after
the fifth body was found Thursday. ``It would appear ... they are
connected.''
   ``They are all in a geographic location which is very similar,''
he said of the bodies found a couple of exits from each other along
Interstate 195 and Route 140 in southeastern Massachusetts.
   Pina also said his office has turned up additional evidence that
it has not disclosed.
   State police using specially trained dogs resumed a search today
of the area near where the partially clothed skeleton was found
Thursday.
   The body was located by police dogs along Route 140 in Freetown,
less than three miles from where the first body was discovered in
July, officials said.
   Thomas Gibney, a spokesman for Pina, said police used
searchlights Thursday night but found no evidence to help the
investigation. An autospy was scheduled today, he said.
   ``We're hoping we found the last of them and we just have to put
some of the pieces together,'' Gibney said.
   Gibney said investigators believed the fifth victim also was a
woman because of the style of the clothing, dungarees and a light
shirt. He said the body was severely decomposed and may have been
there for up to a year.
   The district attorney has linked the bodies to the disappearance
of several women from New Bedford's Weld Square area, known by
police as a center for drug trading and prostitution.
   LouAnn Silva, a resident of Weld Square, said she worried about
her 15-year-old daughter. ``I'm scared to go to the store myself,''
she said.
   The four also may be connected with the deaths of two women from
Providence, R.I., whose bodies were found last spring in Seekonk
near Interstate 195 and about 10 miles away in Attleboro near
Interstate 95, Pina said.
   Pina said he believes the killer was familiar with the area.
   ``I personally don't believe it could have been someone traveling
through,'' he said. ``It looks like it was someone who was more
local, someone who knew the area, someone who felt confident enough
that they could go there and drop a body off by the road and leave.''
   Officials undertook the search after a body was found last month
along Interstate 195 in Dartmouth, not far from where two bodies
were discovered in July.
   Police dogs Tuesday found the skeletal remains of a fourth woman
along the interstate in Dartmouth. None of the women has been
positively identified.
   Dental records of five women reported missing here in recent
months were being checked to see if they match any of the bodies.
Three of the missing women were either last seen, lived near or
frequented the Weld Square area.
   Jimmy Giammalvo, whose family has run a grocery store on the
corner of Weld Square since 1922, said little has changed since the
first body was found.
   ``They (prostitutes) come in and out of here all the time. It's
business as usual,'' he said.
</TEXT>
