<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TooManySantas     12-02 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Too Many Santas,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Dozen Santas and Their Ho-Ho-Hos Too Much for Many Tots</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kids may love Santa, but when 25 of the jolly old
fellows show up en masse, the pleasure turns to terror and tears,
and children run for their mothers' skirts.
   So it was when a festive phalanx of red-suited, black-booted Kris
Kringles _ excited graduates of a Santa school _ invaded a downtown
hotel lobby to a chorus of ho-ho-hos.
   ``I really love kids, but I didn't realize they'd be so scared,''
Chris Davis, 19, of San Diego, said Wednesday. ``I reached out to
shake one's hand and she started crying.''
   Veteran Santa Leonard Utecht, 68, with 48 years behind the beard,
used the incident to teach the new dogs old tricks.
   ``Don't reach down to the little ones from above or they'll
retreat,'' Utecht counseled. ``If you stoop to their level, you can
win them over.''
   The basics? Know all the reindeers' names. Forgo alcohol, tobacco
and garlic. Don't make any specific promises. And gently hold the
child's hand _ it's soothing and keeps him from grabbing the beard.
   The St. Nick novices were enthralled with their duties, although
they found the outfit a bit stifling for climates south of the North
Pole.
   ``I'm working up a real sweat,'' Davis said.
   ``With a little practice, we'll get used to it,'' said Jaymes
Regualos, 18, of Battle Creek, Mich., of the pillow padding and
warm, silky beards. ``I love doing this. It's lots of fun.''
   The bravest youngster on hand was Nadia Sawtarie from Japan.
   The 3-year-old assessed the invaders from behind her mother's
skirts and then gathered the courage to venture out and offer a
tentative wave before scurrying back to safety.
   Santa is known in Japan, but not on such a scale, her mother said.
</TEXT>
