<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1111EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDS-Blood     12-02 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Blood,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blood Bank Held Responsible For Transfusion-Related AIDS Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury verdict that found a blood bank
negligent for allowing an infant to get AIDS through a transfusion
will affect hundreds of similar cases across the country, an
attorney says.
   Additionally, the nation's blood supply could be significantly
improved if blood banks raise their standards in light of Thursday's
decision, a key witness in the case said.
   In a verdict believed to be the first of its kind, a jury found
the Irwin Memorial Blood Bank of San Francisco was negligent in
failing to properly screen its blood supply for the virus that
causes AIDS.
   The jury also found that the blood bank, which supplies blood to
about 40 hospitals in eight counties in Northern California, erred
when it rejected requests by the boy's family and friends to donate
blood for the transfusions.
   ``It shows blood banks that they are indeed vulnerable to jury
verdicts,'' said plaintiff's attorney Michael Moriarty.
   The suit was filed on behalf of Michael Osborn, now 5{, who was
three weeks old when he received AIDS-contaminated blood in 1983
during surgery for a congenital heart defect. He tested positive for
the AIDS virus in September 1987.
   Michael now has a brain tumor and lymphoma. He has only a few
months to live, said Moriarty.
   The jury awarded Michael $550,000 in compensatory damages. His
parents were awarded $200,000 to pay for past and future medical and
nursing bills.
   Superior Court Judge Andrew Ertola did not allow the jury to
consider awarding punitive damages, nor was the jury allowed to give
the parents any damages for pain and suffering, said Moriarty.
   Moriarty said the financial cost may motivate blood banks to
``police themselves more than they are now.'' He said hundreds of
similar cases are pending across the country.
   The blood bank plans to appeal, said Irwin's attorney, Duncan
Barr.
   Barr defended Irwin's decisions in the case. ``In February of
1983, there was only one case of AIDS from a transfusion in the
world,'' he said. ``There was not evidence at that time that this
was a disease transmitted by blood.''
   But Dr. Thomas Asher, a key witness for the family, disputed
Barr's assertion that there was no evidence in 1983 that AIDS was
transmitted by blood. ``Everybody knew it,'' he said.
   Asher, founder and chairman of HemaCare Corp., a private,
for-profit blood bank in Sherman Oaks, called the verdict ``a
marvelous thing.''
   ``Any time more pressure is put on the blood bankers to improve
the quality of their product, the better it'll be for the members of
the public who receive it,'' he said.
   Both Barr and Asher said it was the first time a blood bank had
been found responsible for a transfusion-related AIDS case. Other
cases have gone to court, but have not resulted in verdicts.
   Asher said that although many blood banks have improved their
screening and recruiting in the past few years, others have not.
   ``Much of the blood industry is still dragging their feet,'' he
said. ``Rather than working harder and recruiting harder, they're
willing to let questionable blood and questionable donors go through
their system.''
   Mary Osborn, Michael's mother, said she and her husband were
thrilled by the jury's decision.
   ``We just feel this is a great moral victory,'' she said. ``I
think the blood industry, particularly in high-risk areas like San
Francisco, has got to shape up.''
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome destroys the body's immune
system, leaving victims vulnerable to infections. The virus is
spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared
by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant
women to their offspring.
   As of Dec. 1, 79,389 cases had been reported since June 1981, and
44,590, or 56 percent of all victims, had died.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881202-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1109EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-PLO 2ndLd-Writethru a0441 12-02 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-PLO, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0441, 0405,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arabs Introduce Measure To Move Assembly To Geneva</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with resolution could pass
tonight, Geneva session could cost half a million dollars. Pick up
8th graf pvs, ``A rally...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Arab diplomat said today that
member states will pass a resolution to move the General Assembly to
Geneva so PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat, barred from entering the
United States, can address the body.
   On Thursday night, the United States refused the assembly's
request to grant Arafat a visa. Arafat planned to speak about the
Palestinian situation.
   ``This reply from the United States is negative and will be
contained in a report by the secretary-general to come out tomorrow
morning,'' U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani said Thursday night.
   A diplomat who saw the United States' response said it was
``extremely negative.'' It replied to a General Assembly resolution
urging Washington to reverse its decision and respond within 24
hours. The resolution passed 151-2 Wednesday, with the United States
and Israel opposed.
   The State Department said it denied Arafat a visa because he
encourages and condones terrorism by the Palestine Liberation
Organization. Washington has said it does not object to the assembly
shifting to Geneva and would participate in a session held there.
   The senior Arab diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the resolution would be introduced to the General Assembly this
afternoon and would pass by tonight.
   U.N. comptroller Luis Maria Gomez confirmed the Arab nations
introduced their resolution before one of two budgetary committees
that must consider it before it goes before the whole Assembly.
   Arab and U.N. sources said the Geneva session would be held
sometime Dec. 12-16. Revised estimates put the cost of the session
at $500,000, said the Arab diplomat.
   Arafat has said he wants to explain the new position taken by the
PLO's Palestine National Council in its recent meeting in Algiers.
   The council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile, implicitly recognized
Israel's right to exist, accepting key U.N. resolutions on the
Middle East calling for negotiations with states in the region.
   A rally planned to welcome Arafat on Thursday turned into a
protest outside the United Nations. About 400 people including
Palestinians and a few dozen anti-Zionist Orthodox Jews denounced
the visa denial.
   Waving PLO flags and pictures of Arafat, the demonstrators
chanted ``Long Live the PLO.''
   Holding anti-Zionist banners were ultra-Orthodox Jewish men in
long black coats and wide-brimmed hats. Orthodox Jews Against
Zionism believe God has forbidden the Jewish people to have their
own state.
   Geneva is the European headquarters of the United Nations. The
General Assembly has never met outside New York since the U.N.
headquarters were built in the city in 1952.
   The resolution on moving to Geneva must be heard by a 16-member
budgetary advisory committee then go to the General Assembly's
finance committee, which would vote on it and send it to the General
Assembly for a vote.
   The PLO has had a U.N. mission in New York since 1975 and holds
non-voting observer status at the world body. It is considered the
sole, legitimate representative of the Palestinian people and is
invited to speak on all debates concerning Palestinians and the
Middle East.
</TEXT>
