<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AngolaRebel     12-02 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Angola Rebel,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNITA Chieftain Criticizes Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leader of Angola's anti-communist insurgency
today criticized the pending agreement that will provide for the
withdrawal of Cuban troops from Angola, contending that the accord
undercounts the Cuban presence by 10,000.
   Jeremias K. Chitunda, vice president of the UNITA forces since
1986, said the agreement being negotiated in U.S.-mediated talks
calls for the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban forces over a 27-month
period.
   Chitunda said in an interview that the removal of that number of
Cubans would still leave 10,000 at the disposal of Angola's leftist
government after the withdrawal timetable ends.
   In addition, he said, 20,000 other Cubans have been given Angolan
citizenship and are capable of providing assistance to the Angolan
Army.
   ``There is very little in it for us to rejoice about,'' Chitunda
said, alluding to the agreement being worked out by officials from
South Africa, Angola and Cuba.
   The State Department said it stands by its estimate that the
Cuban troop presence numbers about 50,000. It also disputed
Chitunda's claim that 20,000 Cubans have acquired Angolan
citizenship.
   Final details of the agreement were being negotiated this week in
the Congolese capital of Brazzaville. Chester Crocker, the State
Department's top official for African affairs, is serving as
mediator for the talks.
   In addition to the withdrawal of Cuban troops, the accord is also
aimed at bringing about independence and black majority rule in
Namibia, a colony of South Africa. A treaty implementing the
agreement is expected to be ready for signature in a few weeks.
   The Reagan administration has been providing assistance to UNITA
since 1985 but Chitunda's remarks reflect what has been an
undercurrent of uneasiness between the two allies.
   South Africa has been UNITA's main supplier but that role is
expected to end once South African forces depart Namibia as part of
the independence process in the territory.
   Chitunda said UNITA has become increasingly self-sufficient and
should be able to survive a South African aid suspension.
   Another shortcoming of the agreement, Chitunda said, is that it
does not provide for a process of national reconciliation in Angola,
which has been plagued by civil war since independence in 1975.
   He said that UNITA's main political objective is negotiations
with Angolan authorities leading to a process of national
reconciliation and multi-party democracy.
   ``We do not seek military superiority,'' he said. ``We do not
seek military victory.''
   Angolan officials have refused to hold national reconciliation
talks, calling instead on the UNITA rebels to take advantange of a
government amnesty offer.
</TEXT>
