<HEAD>Precede JOHANNESBURG</HEAD>
<HEAD>South African Ministers Arrive For Talks Amid Reports Of Snag</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Botha and Malan arriving.
Pickup 10th graf `UNITA receives...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two South African government ministers
joined U.S.-mediated talks today aimed at wrapping up an interim
agreement on a Cuban troop withdrawal from Angola and independence
for South-West Africa.
   But Defense Minister Magnus Malan, who flew to the Congolese
capital today with Foreign Minister Pik Botha, said there was a
``serious hitch'' in the talks, the independent South Africa Press
Association reported.
   ``This is the time when the pitfalls start appearing,'' Malan was
quoted as saying by the news agency. The report did not elaborate.
   One reported disagreement has involved South Africa's insistence
on a reliable system for verifying the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban
troops supporting Angola's Marxist government in fighting a rebel
war.
   A statement issued in Pretoria before their arrival in
Brazzaville said it was hoped the agreement would be signed today or
Saturday.
   In any case, further negotiations will be required after the
signing of what is to be called the Brazzaville Protocol, before a
formal treaty is signed. The formal agreement was to be signed in
New York, perhaps next month.
   Delegations from South Africa, Angola and Cuba arrived earlier
this week for what was expected to be a final round of negotiations
on the details of agreements ironed out in the past six months of
U.S.-mediated talks.
   Angola's government is fighting a 13-year-old war with the UNITA
rebel movement.
   UNITA receives assistance from South Africa and the United
States. UNITA, which has not been a party to the peace talks, has
vowed to continue fighting.
   The protocol also calls for South Africa to begin granting
independence to South-West Africa, also known as Namibia. South
Africa has administered the territory for 73 years.
   The Weekly Mail newspaper in Johannesburg reported that UNITA
forces have been moving from southern Angola into Namibia. However,
the South African military has denied UNITA has any guerrilla
fighters in Namibia.
</TEXT>
