<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolReform     12-02 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Reform,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago School Reform Bill Wins General Assembly Approval</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS CONRAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A school reform measure for Chicago that
calls for the creation of local school councils and a new central
Board of Education has overwhelmingly won the approval of the
Illinois General Assembly.
   Final approval came on a 98-8 vote in the House late Thursday.
The Senate approved it 56-1 earlier in the evening.
   ``I think that it is a good bill, well-balanced, well-founded,
and I am very hopeful that it will make significant change in the
Chicago school system,'' said House Speaker Michael Madigan.
   The bill represents the General Assembly's second effort on
school reform. A Democratic-drafted bill was approved in July but
was abandoned early in the fall session amid a partisan dispute over
changes proposed by Gov. James R. Thompson.
   Drafted by a bipartisan legislative group, the measure is
designed to shift the balance of power in the school system by
trimming the central school bureaucracy and creating local school
councils with authority to appoint principals at each of the city's
592 public schools.
   Principals will be given more authority over hiring and over
attempts to improve the work of teachers who are deemed
unsatisfactory.
   The current 11-member Chicago Board of Education will be replaced
with a seven-member interim board to be appointed by the mayor. A
school board nominating commission will make recommendations to the
mayor for a permanent 15-member board.
   The existing Chicago School Finance Authority will serve as a
watchdog over the reform effort, and can suspend or fire any school
board member or employee who doesn't comply with its directives.
   Lawmakers of both parties acknowledged the bill dealt primarily
with the management of the school system but did not address such
issues as overcrowding, dropouts and early childhood education that
require major funding increases.
</TEXT>
