<2ND_LINE>PM-Argentina, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0535,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unrest Spreads to 4th Military Base; Apparently Move To Oust Army
Chief</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with rebel officer saying move
against army chief, not civilian government; emergency Cabinet
meeting. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Infantry units mutinied today at a
large army base outside the capital, and a rebel officer said the
move was aimed at replacing the army chief and not civilian
President Raul Alfonsin.
   It was unclear how many soldiers were taking part in the
insurrection, and there were no reports of gunfire or injuries by
early afternoon. The Campo de Mayo base was the fourth military
outpost reporting unrest in two days.
   The army sent loyal troops to the base and reported other bases
nationwide were calm. Vice President Victor Martinez convened
emergency meetings to discuss the rebellion with Cabinet ministers
and military chiefs.
   Alfonsin is in New York to address the U.N. General Assembly.
   The rebel officer, who identified himself only as an aide to Col.
Mohamed Ali Seineldin, said the revolt was not against Alfonsin
government.
   ``Our posture is one of absolute respect for the Constitution,''
he said in a telephone interview with The Associated Press. He said
the rebellion was aimed at toppling the army chief, Gen. Jose Dante
Caridi.
   Seineldin ``is raising arms against the authorities of the force
in a definitive attempt to restore the honor of the army and its
historic role,'' the officer said from the base, 20 miles northeast
of Buenos Aires.
   The insurrection followed incidents Thursday in which 53 coast
guard men armed themselves and deserted their base and an captain
attempted to incite infantry troops at La Tablada, west of Buenos
Aires. The Defense Ministry said the captain was arrested.
   Government officials had believed those incidents, and another
failed uprising at an army communications facility in City Bell, 25
miles south of the capital, had been isolated.
   Today they were treating the Campo de Mayo revolt as part of the
same unrest and trying to make sure there were no other pockets of
dissent.
   The elite coast guard unit on Thursday deserted their base in
three trucks, into which they loaded four light machine guns, 200
rifles, 30 handguns and 100,000 rounds of ammunition, officials said.
   The Diario y Noticias news agency reported the coast guard unit
was inside the Campo de Mayo base today.
   At the base, no clashes were reported, but rebels in combat gear
put a heavy machine gun at the entrance to the military school and
took in weapons.
   The military action was denounced on all sides.
   ``No action of this type is capable of threatening democracy,''
said Eduardo Angeloz, presidential candidate of Alfonsin's Radical
Civic Union.
   Carlos Menem, the opposition Peronist Party candidate in the May
1988 elections, said: ``If it were necessary, I don't doubt the
Argentine people would mobilize in defense of democracy.''
   Elements within the army have complained about Caridi's
leadership, the selection of officers for promotion and retirement,
the military budget that under Alfonsin has shrunk by half, and pay
that has not kept pace with 332 percent inflation.
   Officers also are unhappy about the resumption of trials against
colleagues charged with human rights abuses in the crackdown on
leftist subversion during the 1976-83 dictatorship.
   The 1987 and 1988 uprisings led by Lt. Col. Aldo Rico, now
discharged and imprisoned, were motivated to support fellow officers
being prosecuted in civilian courts, and reflected the unwillingness
of colleagues who were called to testify.
   During the dictatorship, kidnappings, bombings and assassinations
by leftist groups were curtailed, but at least 9,000 Argentines
``disappeared'' and were presumed executed by security forces, a
government commission reported.
   In December 1985, five former junta members, including former
military presidents Jorge Videla and Roberto Viola, were convicted
in civilian court for crimes including kidnapping, torture and
murder.
</TEXT>
