<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InspectionFires     12-02 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Inspection Fires,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Blames Philadelphia Inspections Office For Six Fires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury has blamed mismanagement in the
city's Department of Licenses and Inspections for at least six fires
since 1984 that caused more than $23 million in damage and killed
two people.
   The agency is a ``bureaucracy that does not react to danger,''
said District Attorney Ronald Castille.
   The Philadelphia County grand jury condemned the city
department's exclusive enforcement of the fire code, but did not
accuse any official of wrongdoing. The grand jury said the system
was at fault rather than the people.
   ``The present system promotes inefficiency by permitting
decisions without accountability, ignoring advice from the fire
department, failing to follow up field inspector requests for action
and failing to coordinate and utilize the information in its
system,'' the grand jury said Thursday.
   Castille sent a letter to Mayor W. Wilson Goode urging him and
the City Council to strip the department of its fire code
enforcement power and put the fire department in charge. City
officials had no response today.
   William Wolfe, the assistant district attorney who handled the
grand jury investigation, said inspectors did their jobs on the six
buildings that later burned, but their reports ``went into the black
hole of L&I, where their supervisors did nothing.''
   The grand jury review of inspection and licensing agency
practices covered six fires between May 1984 and December 1987,
including the Nov. 7, 1984, explosion at the Publicker Distillery,
where two workers died, and a nine-alarm fire on May 3, 1984, that
caused an estimated $20 million in damage to 17 buildings.
   The panel also recommended that criminal charges be filed against
one building owner who allegedly ignored safety citations and the
owner of a company that installs fire alarm and sprinkler systems
for allegedly illegally obtaining an occupancy permit.
</TEXT>
