<1ST_LINE>u a PM-RJRNabisco-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0483 12-02 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-RJR Nabisco-Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0483,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Uncertainty Pervades Home of RJR Nabisco Tobacco Subsidiary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 18th graf, `Wade Spache ...,' with 1 graf to UPDATE with
RJR stock dropping 75 cents this morning.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By F. ALAN BOYCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ The record buyout of RJR Nabisco Inc.
has stirred dreams of big stock profits and hopes that the company's
corporate headquarters would return to this tobacco city, but it
also brought fears of layoffs.
   ``I think the general feeling is one of uncertainty,'' Fred
Nordenholz, president of the Winston-Salem Chamber of Commerce, said
Thursday. ``There are lots of mixed feelings about what's
happening.''
   The food and tobacco giant was auctioned off to buyout firm
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. late Wednesday in a $24.53 billion
deal valued at about $109 a share in cash and securities.
   That is virtually double the stock's price before management
started a bidding war six weeks ago and represents a big windfall
for this city. Analysts estimate that about 9,000 people in the area
plus local trusts, foundations and retirement plans own stock now
worth a little more than $2 billion.
   At Windsor Jewelers in downtown Winston-Salem, Lois Simon said
she has already noticed an influx of potential new customers who
appear to be looking for ways to spend the proceeds they will get
from the sale of their stock.
   ``These are definitely not typical of the clientele that would be
pricing our emeralds and diamonds,'' she said.
   However, Chamber of Commerce Chairman John Davis said stories of
production-line workers becoming millionaires were ``a bit
overstated.''
   ``There are some people who are suddenly quarter-millionaires, on
paper anyway,'' he said.
   Some local businessmen hope RJR will return its corporate
headquarters, which were shifted to Atlanta last year, to
Winston-Salem, bringing jobs and prestige back as well. The company
has kept its R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. subsidiary, the nation's
second largest cigarette maker, based here throughout.
   Expectations of any windfalls are tempered because Kohlberg
Kravis will use unprecedented amounts of borrowed money to acquire
RJR. Locals expect belt-tightening measures to enable the company to
pay off its massive debt which could include layoffs, even in the
hugely profitable tobacco business.
   ``Some people are going to have greater personal wealth than ever
before, and that's balanced by a certain amount of anxiety about
where the company's headed and what's going to happen to their
careers,'' Nordenholz said.
   Davis, who is also a managing partner of the investment firm
Alex. Brown and Sons, said the city could emerge in better shape
when the financial smoke clears.
   ``Tobacco is fairly recession-resistant, as is most of the food
business,'' he said. ``Things may be tight for a year, 18 months.
But profits have been in the 20 to 25 percent range. ... What are
you going to do, lay people off because you're making more money? It
doesn't work that way.''
   Rick Weddle, director of Winston-Salem Business Inc., said
layoffs could actually help his firm lure other industry to the
area. A local unemployment rate of about 3 percent has left the area
short of skilled labor, he said.
   ``I am probably one of the few people alive who sees opportunity
in employment reductions,'' he said.
   Many local shareholders may seek to spend some of their sudden
windfall, business owners said.
   Davis said other shareholders are looking to reinvest their
profits.
   Wade Spache, a maintenance technician at R.J. Reynolds, said he
sold some of his stock earlier at $84 a share, far below the
buyout's $109 value but way above the stock's price of roughly $56
before the bidding war began Oct. 20. The stock fell $1.25 Thursday
to close at $91.75 and dropped another 75 cents this morning to $91.
   ``I just wanted to be on the safe side,'' he said. ``I didn't
want everything I had in speculation.''
</TEXT>
