<DOCNO> AP881202-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1153EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RJRNabisco-Markets 1stLd-Writethru a0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-RJR Nabisco-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0496,0737</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wall Street Bracing For Other Big Takeovers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Some of ...,' with 1 graf to reflect this
morning's trading. A version also moving on the financial wire.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Nabisco-Reax, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recently sluggish Wall Street received a burst
of energy from the record bidding contest for RJR Nabisco Inc., and
it's bracing for even more takeover activity before Congress
reconvenes next year.
   ``The takeover activity has lent a real spark of life to a market
which otherwise would be in the doldrums,'' said A.C. Moore,
director of equity research at Argus Research.
   ``There's been a lot of things going on here, but there's nothing
nearly as big,'' said Eldon Grimm, a senior vice president at Birr,
Wilson & Co., who has been trading stock for nearly 60 years. ``It's
livened up the place.''
   Still reeling from the October 1987 stock market crash and
worried about higher interest rates, a sluggish economy and the
dollar, many investors had shied away from stocks in recent weeks.
   But their interest was revived when the RJR bidding war erupted
in late October, amid a wave of other multibillion-dollar takeover
attempts of big companies.
   Late Wednesday, buyout specialist Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.
emerged the apparent victor in the bidding war, when the company's
board of directors accepted its $24.53 billion offer over a slightly
larger proposal by RJR management.
   Some of the biggest winners so far are RJR stockholders, who have
seen their shares more than double in value from a year ago, from
$43 to $91 at mid-morning today. They stand to reap tens of billions
of dollars in profits once the $109-a-share merger is consummated.
   Then there are the investment bankers, such as Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. and Salomon Brothers Inc., whose business had slowed
since last year's stock market crash. They will receive substantial
fees for helping the RJR bidders put their proposals together.
   And there are lucrative fees for the commercial banks lending
money to finance the deal and for the battery of lawyers providing
contractual advice. The new owners and their investors also are
likely to reap big profits once the consumer products giant is
restructured.
   Among the losers have been holders of RJR's $5 billion in
corporate bonds, which slipped 20 percent in market value during
recent weeks. What troubles bondholders is that the buyout will be
financed primarily by borrowed money, mainly through new issues of
high-yield, high-risk ``junk bonds,'' that will give the company
higher levels of debt than traditionaly have been considered prudent.
   Many other outstanding corporate issues have been hurt by the
takeover frenzy, but more money has gone into less volatile Treasury
bonds, particularly short-term issues.
   Other recent big takeover offers include the $12.6 billion merger
of Kraft Inc. with Phillip Morris Cos., and British conglomerate
Grand Metropolitan PLC's $5 billion-plus takeover attempt of
Pillsbury Co. The stock of those target companies also has risen in
value.
   Michale Metz, a technical analyst with Oppenheimer & Co., and
other analysts predict more giant takeovers offers may surface
before Congress reconvenes next year and considers how to limit
buyouts, as many lawmakers have threatened to do.
   ``I think that there is mounting pressure from various circles to
curtail activity of this sort. All this money is changing hands ...
but in the end we're not becoming any more productive or creative,''
said Moore. ``Until Washington takes action, though, I imagine any
company is up for grabs.
   Under this scenario, share prices of these future targets and
others could be driven up even further.
   And as more and more companies are bought and taken private that
will mean less stock available to the public, which also could boost
prices.
   According to Federal Reserve figures, the amount of available
stock has shrunk by about $75 billion in each of the past two years.
Moore predicts that by the end of this year another $100 billion in
equity will be gone, or about 3 percent of the $3.3 trillion
outstanding.
   So, where will all this money be reinvested?
   Metz predicted, ``The old conservative investor will probably be
buying Treasury bills and CDs with it. They're still wary after the
1987 crash. Others will buy more stock and look for more profits.''
</TEXT>
