<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CDC--Flu     12-02 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CDC--Flu,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CDC Reports First Flu Of The '88-'89 Season</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal health officials have reported the first
confirmed influenza cases of the 1988-89 flu season, in Ohio,
Arizona, Hawaii, Michigan and Texas.
   The flu season in the United States occurs during the
cold-weather months, and the first official outbreak of the 1988-89
season was reported in Ohio, the national Centers for Disease
Control said Thursday.
   On Nov. 14, an outbreak of flu-like illness was reported to Ohio
health officials by two schools in the same district. Type B flu
virus _ one of three major influenza groups _ was found in tests on
a teacher and four students.
   The CDC also reported six sporadic cases of type B flu in
children in Texas, beginning with a child in Houston on Oct. 11.
Type B flu also has been found in children in Arizona and Michigan.
   Type A flu cases have been reported in cases in Maryland and
Hawaii; officials do not know which of the two major A types those
cases were.
</TEXT>
