<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Duarte     12-02 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Duarte,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salvadoran President Hospitalized in Poor Health</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte of El Salvador,
who is suffering from terminal liver cancer, was hospitalized in
stable condition in Mexico City today, Salvadoran officials said.
   Salvadoran Foreign Minsiter Ricardo Acevedo Peralta told The
Associated Press that Duarte was ``in a government hospital.''
   Embassy Minister Guillermo Rubio said that Duarte, in Mexico City
for the inauguration of President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, was
being treated for a high temperature. Duarte was in stable condition
and had not changed his plans to return to El Salvador on Saturday
as scheduled, Rubio said.
   Peralta said Duarte ``was somewhat ill, he has a temperature, but
in general terms he is all right.
   ``He only has a little temperature, but these are the normal
results of chemotherapy ... He's a bit tired and the altitude
probably affected him.''
   But government sources in El Salvador said the 63-year-old Duarte
was in ``very grave'' condition today.
   An operator at the Mexico City hotel where Duarte had been
staying said she was under orders not to transfer any press calls to
the Salvadoran delegation.
   Duarte attended Salinas' inauguration Thursday morning, but did
not attend a dinner the new president hosted for visiting Latin
American leaders.
   Duarte had until Thursday exhibited in the past two months what
doctors called remarkable improvement in his health. They said the
spread of the cancer in his liver had been arrested and that other
organs had not been affected.
   When he arrived in Mexico City on Wednesday, he went directly
from the airport to the Basilica of Guadalupe, the holiest shrine
for this country's predominant Roman Catholic population.
   He told reporters he had thanked the Virgen of Guadalupe, to whom
the basilica is dedicated, for a recent improvement in health.
   Since diagnosis of his cancer in early June, Duarte had undergone
two weeklong treatments of chemotherapy in Walter Reed Hospital in
Washington and follow-up applications in San Salvador.
   Doctors had said that, though the liver cancer had been arrested,
it will eventually kill Duarte. In June, they gave him six-18 months
to live.
   Duarte, one of the the United States' staunchest allies in
Central America, assumed power in June 1984. His presidential term
ends next year; elections are due in March 1989.
   He began his political career in 1960 and was a founder of the
Salvadoran Democratic Christian Party.
</TEXT>
