<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Blinder-Robinson     12-02 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Blinder-Robinson,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Penny-Stock Broker Implicated In Alleged Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The penny-stock brokerage firm Blinder, Robinson &
Co. and its founder have been implicated in an alleged stock fraud
and international money-laundering scheme, according to court
documents.
   The operation allegedly poured thousands of dollars into penny
stocks without reporting the source of the money to federal
authorities as required by law, Internal Revenue Service agents in
Las Vegas, Nev., have testified.
   The funds were funneled through phony investors and shell
companies with no assets to inside investors of penny-stock firms,
according to allegations in the documents.
   The operation reached across the United States to Switzerland and
other European countries, according to a court affidavit submitted
by IRS agent Bob Salisbury.
   The allegations were outlined in more than 300 pages of documents
made public Thursday. The documents, originally sealed by a court
order, were unsealed after The Denver Post filed suit in U.S.
District Court.
   Federal authorities agreed Thursday to release the documents.
Blinder, Robinson, which has offices nationwide, fought the release
and refused repeated requests to comment on the material.
   ``We wanted it sealed to give us a chance to review what is in
there,'' said Alan Jacobson, an attorney for Blinder, Robinson. ``If
there is to be a trial, it should be in a court of law and not in
the media.''
   The government's allegations were the basis of a four-day search
by federal agents beginning Nov. 19 in which virtually all of
Blinder, Robinson's books and records were seized from its
headquarters in Englewood.
   According to the court documents, the main targets of the IRS and
Securities and Exchange Commission investigation are Michael D.
Wright of Salt Lake City and Arnold Kimmes of Palm Springs, Calif.
   Beginning in 1985, the two formed ``shell companies,'' with no
known assets, and sold the stock to ``straw parties'' _ people who
allowed Wright and Kimmes to use their names in transactions
although they had no control over the stock, the documents alleged.
The proceeds from the sales were shipped to Switzerland and other
European countries.
   The affidavit states that Meyer Blinder, who founded Blinder,
Robinson, and his brother, Morris, are under investigation for
aiding and abetting securities fraud.
   Blinder, Robinson, whose revenues have dropped 50 percent this
year, has begun closing some of its 80 U.S. branches. Its parent
company, Blinder International Enterprises Inc., reported revenue of
$139 million last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
