<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     12-02 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roh Hits Snags in Efforts to Shake Up Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo's plan to restore
credibility in his administration by revamping his Cabinet and party
has snagged in the selection process, officials said Friday.
   In other developments, the opposition-controlled National
Assembly issued a subpoena Friday ordering former President Chun
Doo-hwan to testify for parliamentary inquiries into corruption and
irregularities. It was not known if Chun received it.
   Hundreds of protesters again took to the streets demanding
punishment of Chun, who apologized for corruption and repression
during his government and went into self-imposed internal exile.
   Officials in the governing Democratic Justice Party said Roh
plans to replace several dozen key leaders as quickly as possible in
what they say would be the most extensive shake-up since he took
office in February.
   Roh has promised to remove the vestiges of the Chun government to
help soothe public furor over his repressive rule.
   But one party source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Roh was having trouble finding ``fresh and competent faces'' without
military background or past service in the Chun government.
   The president has a limited pool of senior party officials able
to take on the responsibilities of a high ranking government job,
the sources said.
   Party infighting has also delayed the new appointments, which
originally were to be announced this week, sources said.
   Among the most significant Cabinet changes would be the
replacement of incumbent officials who have military backgrounds
with competent civilians.
   Past authoritarian governments have been dominated by former army
generals. Opposition parties have persistently demanded civilian
control of the government.
   Chun, who resigned in February, went into rural exile Nov. 23
after publicly apologizing for corruption, human rights violations
and other abuses during his seven years in office.
   Chun has denied any personal wrongdoing, but a dozen of his
associates and family members, including two brothers, have been
convicted or charged with taking bribes and embezzling government
funds.
   Roh has asked the nation to forgive Chun and promised speedy
democratic reforms, which include the govenment shake-up. But Roh's
proposals failed to satisfy dissidents and radical students who have
staged demonstrations demanding Chun's arrest and punishment.
   On Friday about 200 students armed with iron rods and firebombs
attacked a building of goverment prosecutors, demanding Chun's
arrest. The attack caused no injuries but shattered dozens of
windows.
   Clashes also broke out in Seoul at Yonsei and Seoul National
Universities between hundreds of students and riot police. Students
hurled scores of firebombs, shouting ``Arrest Chun Doo-hwan, Punish
Roh Tae-woo!'' No injuries were reported.
</TEXT>
