<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NATO     12-02 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Says Some Not Bearing a Fair Share of Defense Burden</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci
said Friday a new push to get NATO allies to shoulder more of the
defense burden should stall any efforts in Congress to withdraw
American troops from Western Europe.
   He praised defense ministers at a two-day meeting of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization for taking the ``remarkable step'' of
approving a report critical of some for not doing more for the
Western alliance.
   ``They unanimously approved a report that makes clear that some
of their nations are not bearing a fair share of the common defense
burden,'' Carlucci told a news conference.
   The 79-page report made public Thursday was NATO's effort to
defuse the potentially divisive issue of ``burden-sharing.''
   U.S. congressional critics contend the allies are not pulling
their weight in NATO. Some have raised the possibility the United
States might withdraw some of its 326,000 troops stationed in Europe.
   NATO Secretary-General Manfred Woerner, a former West German
defense minister, told reporters the study sent a signal that ``this
is not a matter of the United States versus the rest of the
alliance. This is a joint alliance effort.''
   Carlucci said the work must continue. ``As long as Cognress
perceives we are dealing with this issue fairly, there will not be
efforts per se to reduce our troop strength in Europe,'' he said.
   ``We must remember we are not in Europe as a philanthropic
gesture to the Europeans,'' he said. ``We are there because of our
collective security.''
   Carlucci also said his recommendation for a 2 percent increase,
after adjustment for inflation, in the 1990 U.S. defense budget
would allow for U.S. troops to remain in Europe.
   If Congress pressed for zero-growth budgets for the Pentagon, he
said, $116 billion would have to be sliced from spending over five
years.
   In a final statement, the ministers said they were encouraged by
signs of change in the Soviet Union since they could lead to
``improved and progressively more stable East-West relations.''
   But the ministers's statement added: ``We have, as yet, seen no
evidence of relaxation in the scale of the Soviet Union's military
effort.''
   Moscow, it said, earmarks about 15 percent to 17 percent of its
total economic output for defense spending, nearly three times the
U.S. level.
   The ministers also said they agreed to provide additional money
in the 1991 and 1992 NATO budgets to relocate the United States'
401st Tactical Fighter Wing from Spain to Italy. The move is
expected to cost about $800 million.
   Spain has said the 72 F-16 fighter jets must leave its territory
by 1991 as part of a drive to reduce the U.S. military presence
there.
   Ministers from 15 of NATO's 16 member nations met at headquarters
in Brussels as part of the Defense Planning Committee. France does
not belong to the committee.
   Foreign ministers from all 16 nations gather in Brussels late
next week for a regularly scheduled meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
