<HEAD>Dukakis in Washington, Wishes It Were ``In Another Capacity''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with fresh quotes, subbing 2 grafs for 2nd graf pvs
and subbing 3 grafs for grafs 10-11 pvs, He was ... their help.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, conceding he had hoped to be
``here in another capacity,'' today made his first trip to
Washington since losing the presidential election, visiting
Democratic leaders before meeting with President-elect George Bush.
   He said he felt no bitterness from the campaign, remarking before
his White House meeting with Bush, ``When it's all over, we don't
throw bombs at each other; we sit down with each other.''
   After arriving in Washington this morning, the Massachusetts
governor headed immediately to the Capitol for separate meetings
with House Speaker Jim Wright of Texas and new Senate Majority
Leader George Mitchell of Maine.
   Wright said the Democratic Party was proud of Dukakis. ``He
fought a good fight,'' the speaker said, adding that the party still
considered Dukakis among its leaders.
   ``He's young. He's vigorous. He has a lot to offer the country,''
Wright told reporters before a private meeting with Dukakis. ``His
future is not behind him, it is ahead of him.''
   The governor thanked Wright but added: ``I think in the long run
I'll probably emerge stronger but I'd be less than candid if I
didn't say I wish I was here in another capacity.''
   Mitchell, too, referred to Dukakis as ``a national leader of our
party.''
   Asked if he considered himself the party's national leader,
Dukakis smiled and said, ``We have a good, strong Democratic Party
with lots of leaders.''
   During his meeting with Bush, he said, he planned to raise most
of the issues that he spoke about during the campaign.
   ``Education is important; the environment is important; child
care is important, good health care is important. These are the
things we believe in very strongly,'' he said.
   Dukakis dodged a question about whether he would run for national
office again, saying only that he was busy catching up on
gubernatorial duties.
   He also met with Massachusetts Sens. Edward Kennedy and John
Kerry and had lunch with Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, who was the No. 2
man on the defeated Democratic ticket.
   Some leading Democrats have privately _ and occasionally publicly
_ criticized Dukakis and his campaign operation. But Bentsen said he
expected Dukakis to play ``a very major role'' in the party.
   Aides said Dukakis also would meet briefly with Washington-based
campaign aides to thank them for their help.
   Dukakis said he hoped to discuss a broad range of issues with
Bush in ``a spirit of partnership, cooperation.''
   The meeting of the former presidential rivals, which was
requested by Bush, came a day after the president-elect met with
Mitchell and two days after he had lunch with Jesse Jackson, one of
the men Dukakis bested to win the Democratic nomination.
   Dukakis, at a Thursday news conference in Boston, had little to
say about his meeting with Bush but did say he and other Democrats
stood ready to support any ``real efforts'' by Bush to reduce the
federal budget deficit.
   Since the election Dukakis has expressed concern over reports
quoting Bush transition aides as saying Medicare and other
entitlement programs could face spending cuts as part of a
deficit-reduction plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
