<DOCNO> AP881202-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1324EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     12-02 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Press Credits Walesa with Conciliatory Tone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party newspaper on Friday
gave Lech Walesa credit for being conciliatory during his TV debate
with an official union leader, but it said the Solidarity leader
usually takes a different tone.
   The 43-minute debate Wednesday night with official unions' chief
Alfred Miodowicz was the first time Walesa had appeared on Polish
television in five years, and the first time he was ever given such
a forum to discuss his views at length.
   Supporters believed Walesa took the offensive and won the debate
easily, but the official press continued to avoid any judgments on
who was the victor.
   Miodowicz, in an interview published Friday with the Flag of
Youth newspaper, said in answer to a question about why he did not
speak more aggressively that, ``The idea of this meeting was to get
closer, not confrontation. As the host, I felt obliged to make my
style of the debate conform to this.''
   ``We did not indulge in a verbal fight which would bring disgrace
on ourselves,'' he said. ``What matters in the end is the future of
Polish trade unions and not who won more points.''
   He also said he would support a proposal made by Walesa during
the debate for further televised debates between experts on various
problems from both the official unions and representatives of
opposing viewpoints.
   ``I propose twice a month discussions about the problems of
workers,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, the party newspaper Trybuna Ludu said the fact that
the debate could be televised in itself proved that authorities are
not ``marking time'' in making reforms.
   ``One should note with appreciation and even satisfaction that
Walesa's address contained several statements and theses in a
conciliatory tone,'' said a Trybuna Ludu political commentator.
   ``By rejecting anarchy or destruction and stating that the
territory of an enterprise should not be an arena for political
struggle, Lech Walesa presented himself in a different way that in
other times,'' said commentator Ryszard Drecki.
   ``Millions of Poles on Wednesday listened to a Lech Walesa who
was rather conciliatory, calm and leaning toward agreement. Not many
people know however the speech he delivered last Sunday, an address
unequivocally confrontational. Did some change occur in his views in
three days?''
   The official press had criticized hostile remarks attacking
Miodowicz allegedly made by Walesa on Sunday, but Walesa has denied
making the quoted statements. The official PAP news agency later
conceded some of its quotations of Walesa were erroneous, and issued
a retraction.
</TEXT>
