<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Bejerot     12-02 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Bejerot,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swedish Drug Policy Opponent Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nils Bejerot, an international authority
on drugs in society, has died at the age of 67.
   Bejerot, who died Tuesday, suffered for several months apparently
from tuberculosis.
   His health deteriorated following two arson attempts on his home
in Stockholm last summer, said Jonas Hertelius, an official at the
Swedish Carnegie Institute, a private group headed by Bejerot that
specialized in drug research.
   No one was injured in the attacks but Bejerot's large private
library and documents were destroyed and he was disturbed by the
incidents.
   Bejerot wrote books on drug abuse and criminal policy.
   He maintained that the West's drug problem was created by the
permissive drug policies in the 1960s. He attacked anti-drug
programs that he believed failed to force addicts and to take
responsibilities in society, lashing out at what he called ``lenient
psychologists.''
   Several governments sought his advice on drug issues. In 1974 he
was called as an expert in U.S. Senate hearings about hashish and
marijuana.
   He lectured earlier this year in the Soviet Union on drugs. He
was also was a main speaker at an Atlanta seminar arranged by the
Parent Institute for Drug Education.
   Services will be held Dec. 10 in Stockholm.
</TEXT>
