<HEAD>Report Cuts in Large West German Maneuvers Won't Affect NATO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Planned drastic cuts in West Germany's
large military maneuvers won't affect the country's battle
readiness, officials at a meeting of NATO defense ministers said
Friday.
   West Germany will abandon more than half its maneuvers involving
more than 2,000 troops, but increase smaller excercises to allay
environmental and public complaints, said West German Defense
Minister Rupert Scholz. The switch also would be more
cost-effective, he said.
   NATO Secretary-General Manfred Woerner said Scholz stressed the
impending reliance on smaller excercises ``was meant to increase the
effectiveness'' of West German forces.
   ``It was not described as a reduction in overall military
excercises,'' said Woerner.
   Scholz said allies had ``reacted positively'' when hee, won't be affected.
But observers said large disruptive
maneuvers by other NATO troops might be seen in an increasingly bad
light.
