<HEAD>Turkish Consulate Damaged in Arson Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROTTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A firebomb exploded at the Turkish
consulate in Rotterdam early Friday but only damaged the front door,
police said.
   Nobody was hurt in the attack by activists who left a banner
protesting alleged human rights abuses in Turkish prisons, according
to police spokesman Hans den Breejen.
   The protesters also sparked a bomb alert by leaving two empty
soda cans with wires protruding near the building in this port city.
   Army explosives experts evacuated several buildings but found the
cans were harmless, the policeman said.
   There were no arrests.
   The incident occurred as a group of Turkish and Dutch activists
go into the sixth day of a hunger strike to protest conditions in
Turkish jails, according to the Rev. Hans Visser, pastor of the
Dutch Reformed St. Paul's Church.
   None of the 25 to 30 people at the church was involved in the
arson, Visser said.
