<DOCNO> AP881202-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1354EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Forests-Marijuana     12-02 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forests-Marijuana,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agency Says It Destroyed 60 Percent of Marijuana in National
Forests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents eradicated roughly 60 percent of
the marijuana grown in national forests during 1988, while sharply
increasing the number of cultivation arrests and plant seizures, a
U.S. Forest Service official said Friday.
   At the same time, the number of physical assaults against agents
and members of the public in cases related to marijuana growing was
down, but the number of sites that were booby-trapped were up,
according to Forest Service figures.
   The statistics also indicate that growers now apparently are
concentrating their efforts on more potent forms of marijuana, such
as sinsemilla, and on hybrids that produce more pounds of saleable
marijuana per plant.
   The crackdown on drug growers in the forests has become one of
the agency's top priorities, and agents are armed with increased
enforcement powers and more money than in the past.
   ``In essence, 1988 is the first full year in which we have been
able to see the sucess of our efforts,'' said Ed Few, the Forest
Service's assistant branch chief for law enforcement. ``We now have
policies and strategies in operation to attack this problem.''
   Few said federal agents wiped out an estimated 60 percent of the
marijuana grown in national forests in 1988, compared with an
estimated 40 percent of the crop in 1987.
   He said agents and rangers seized more than 340,000 plants in
1988, compared with 255,000 plants in 1987.
   The estimated street value of the plants seized in 1988 was more
than $1.2 billion, said Few, adding that the Forest Service
considered that a ``conservative estimate.''
   Few said the agency was ``comfortable'' with it estimates, which
are based on intelligence from field agents and surveys of marijuana
plantations that were harvested before being detected.
   ``It would be nice to get 100 percent'' of the crop, Few said,
``but we would be foolish to predict that. The objective is to seize
enough so that is becomes apparent to the grower that it is not
cost-effective for them to use national forest lands.''
   Few said that while once agents used to find plantations with
4,000 or 5,000 plants in a forest clearing, most sites now contain
about 100 plants that are growing near other trees or brush.
   The number of marijuana-growing arrests made by the Forest
Service was up almost 400 percent, from 134 nationwide in 1987 to
527 this year, Few said.
   ``We've dealt with the problem to some extent over the past 10
years handling it as a misdemeanor crime and concentrating on
eradication,'' Few said. ``The 1986 drug act gave us the tools we
needed to do the job.''
   Drug growers now face felony charges and agents now are allowed
to pursue suspects even after they leave federal lands.
   This year also was the first year in which the Forest Service
received the funds for drug enforcement progams it had requested, a
total of $3.2 million, Few said.
   The number of physical assaults on agents or members of the
general public using national forests dropped from 19 in 1987 to 11
in 1988, while the number of sites found with ``potentially lethal''
booby-traps grew from 83 in 1987 to 116 in 1988.
   Few said there was a ``dramatic'' increase in the number of
marijuana plantations found that exclusively contained the more
potent sinsemilla plants, with 1,255 such sites found in 1987 and
2,268 such sites found this year.
   He said the street value of sinsemilla can be almost twice that
of less potent types.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
