<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NewOrleansFire 1stLd-Writethru a0516 12-02 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Orleans Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0516,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arson Blamed in Block-Long Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with arrest, comment from officials</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NU1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless man was arrested today for arson,
and police said he was a suspect in at least one of 10 fires that
broke out in an inner-city neighborhood overnight, destroying eight
buildings.
   Tips from witnesses led to the arrest of Booker T. Washington
Jr., 46, who was picked up in the neighborhood while attempting to
drink from a container of gasoline, said police spokeswoman Yvonne
Bechet.
   He was booked with simple arson and taken to Charity Hospital for
observation.
   ``He was one of the city's homeless, living in an abandoned
car,'' said Bechet.
   No one was injured in the fires, which occurred mainly in vacant
residences. A passer-by said he pulled two elderly women from what
was believed to be the only occupied building. Eight buildings were
destroyed, and at least six others were heavily damaged.
   Washington was booked for a one-alarm fire that broke out just
before 8 p.m. Thursday, about the same time most of the city's
firefighters were working on a six-alarm blaze that razed much of a
nearby city block, said Fire Department spokesman Bob Whitman.
   Police and fire officials said Washington may be linked to the
other fires also.
   Fire Superintendent William McCrossen said there was ``no doubt
in my mind'' that the blazes were arson.
   Police said a witness reported seeing a man running with a
gasoline can just as the flames started leaping from the first fire,
which swept through six houses on one street. Two more fires
engulfed an abandoned bar and a vacant house, respectively, and
seven more broke out over the next few hours, all but one within
three or four blocks of the first fires, Whitman said.
   Mark Dandey said he was in a nearby restaurant when some children
told him there were people in one of the burning buildings.
   ``I smelled smoke and I ran out and there were two young kids
saying, `Fire! Fire!' So then, we go over the house and tried to
kick the door down. After I kicked the door down, they had two old
ladies in the house and I pulled them out,'' Dandey said.
</TEXT>
