<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Giacobetti     12-02 0111</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Giacobetti,0116</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Founder of Italian Singing Quartet Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Giovanni ``Tata'' Giacobetti, a singer and musician
who founded one of Italy's most popular quartets in the 1950s and
1960s, died Friday at the age of 66.
   Giacobetti had been hospitalized a week ago after a heart attack
and died from a brain hemorrhage.
   He wrote hundreds of songs and was the founder in 1941 of
Quartetto Cetra, which launched such favorites as ``In the Old
Farm'' and ``Box at La Scala.''
   Other members of the quartet were Lucia Mannucci, Virgilio Savona
and Felice Chiusano.
   He is survived by his wife, Valeria Fabrizi, an actress; and a
daughter, Giorgia.
</TEXT>
