<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Bush 4thLd-Writethru a0572 12-02 0809</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0572,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Welcomes Dukakis, Robertson</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis-Bush meeting in top 4 grafs, picking up
in 4th graf pvs, He also</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush shook hands with defeated
Democratic rival Michael Dukakis today as the Massachusetts governor
arrived for a private fence-mending session that the president-elect
had suggested.
   Bush and Dukakis had no words for the throng of reporters on hand
before going into the vice president's residence at the Naval
Observatory. A minute later, Sen. Dan Quayle, the future occupant of
the house, emerged and left in his limousine, presumably after
greeting Dukakis inside.
   Earlier, Bush warmly greeted onetime Republican rival Pat
Robertson at the White House, hailing the way ex-political foes can
be post-election friends and accepting Robertson's praise for
Cabinet appointments so far.
   Bush turned aside questions about further appointments in a less
cheerful manner, criticizing ``early, premature needless
speculation.''
   He also met with John Swan, the premier of Bermuda, and was to
meet this evening with another foreign leader, Argentine President
Raul Alfonsin, in whose country military units were reported to have
mutinied today at a large army base outside the capital of Buenos
Aires.
   Swan and Alfonsin are the fourth and fifth heads of state meeting
with Bush since his election Nov. 8.
   At the White House, Robertson told reporters he gave Bush a
private message from the foreign minister of South Africa.
   ``The time has come to recognize that the South African
government needs a little encouragement,'' said Robertson, who
returned last week from South Africa. He is a longtime critic of
sanctions against that nation's white-ruled apartheid government.
   Robertson said Bush told him he would like to see Jesse Jackson
and other American black leaders visit South Africa ``and explore
firsthand what's happening because there have been some significant
changes over the last 10 years.''
   Robertson cited the government's movement of Nelson Mandela from
prison to a halfway house, the commutation of the death sentences of
the Sharpeville 6 and other steps. ``They have broken down a great
deal of institutionalized and social apartheid and I think it would
be nice to just say, `You're on the right track and we'd like to
encourage you a little bit,'' Robertson said.
   Bush, who was not available to reporters after the Robertson
meeting, also was hosting 20 evangelical leaders at his home Friday
night.
   Before the meeting with Robertson, Bush was asked if he had a
place in his Cabinet for the television evangelist. ``Just good
friend,'' Robertson interjected.
   ``Some people don't understand the campaign,'' Bush said. ``They
think that when you run against someone in a campaign that that
injures friendship. ... It's wonderful the way the American politcal
system works.''
   Robertson told Bush that in the transition period he had ``played
it as well as you possibly could. ... I think it's an
extraordinarily competent Cabinet so far.''
   Bush declined to say when he would appoint his defense secretary
or other top officials. ``The more I answer your questions on the
subject that needs to be treated in an orderly, procedural fashion,
the more I add to that which I don't like which is a lot of early,
premature, needless speculation, and so I'm not going to do it,''
Bush told reporters.
   ``We are way ahead of where other presidents-elect have been and
I'm going to stay ahead. And so all I say is stay tuned and please
don't press me,'' said Bush.
   He paid tribute to retiring Rep. Jack Kemp of New York, another
erstwhile rival, at a dinner Thursday night.
   Bush, who reviled Dukakis during the campaign as ``another
liberal governor coming out of nowhere who will take us back to the
bad old days,'' made clear immediately after the election that he
hoped to bury the hatchet as quickly as possible.
   Dukakis, for his part, had spoken during the campaign of sleaze
among top Reagan administration officials, drawing strong retorts
from Bush after saying, ``There's an old Greek saying ... `The fish
rots from the head first.'''
   Steve Crawford, a Dukakis spokesman, said the Massachusetts
governor planned to raise with Bush a number of the issues he
campaigned on.
   ``Education, health care, day care, drugs, housing and other
issues that he felt were important during the campaign and still
feels are important,'' Crawford said.
   In a meeting Thursday, Bush told Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell, D-Maine, that he will take the lead in proposing a
solution to the budget deficit, as Democrats have insisted.
   ``That is exactly what I intend to do'' after Jan. 20, Bush said.
   Bush also said he won't be rushed into making Cabinet
appointments despite persistent news media speculation that may be
troubling to prospects such as John Tower, the former Texas senator
keeping a long vigil for the Pentagon opening.
</TEXT>
