<1ST_LINE>r w BC-Economy-Glance     12-02 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Economy-Glance,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>November Unemployment, October Home Sales, Factory Orders All Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are economic reports Friday by the
government:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>UNEMPLOYMENT</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's civilian unemployment rate in November edged upward
from a 14-year low to 5.4 percent despite an increase of 463,000 new
jobs and a record percentage of the population at work. The 0.1
percentage point increase from October's rate of 5.3 percent was due
almost entirely to a 560,000 increase in the civilian labor force _
people holding jobs or looking for them.
   Despite the slight increase in the unemployment rate, 116 million
Americans held jobs last month, or 62.6 percent of the adult
population age 16 or over.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>HOME SALES</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of new, single-family homes rose 3.5 percent in October to
a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 733,000 units, the highest
level in more than 1{ years. It followed a drop of 1.4 percent in
September, revised up from a previous estimate of minus 7.8 percent
and a gain of 2.1 percent in August.
   Sales for the first 10 months of 1988 are 0.4 percent higher than
for the 1987 period, suprising analysts who were expecting a decline
this year.
   The average price fell 2.1 percent to $140,100 after an identical
increase a month earlier.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>FACTORY ORDERS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   New orders to U.S. factories for manufactured goods rose $3.5
billion, or 1.6 percent, in October to a seasonally adjusted $226.2
billion on the strength of big gains in orders for military ships
and tanks. Military orders shot up 42.5 percent to $10.6 billion
after falling 7.0 percent in September.
   The key category of non-defense capital goods, considered a good
barometer of industry investment plans, fell 3.0 percent to $33.8
billion, following a large 10.2 percent drop in September.
</TEXT>
