<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WorstPresents     12-02 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Worst Presents,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Better No Gift Than A Fruitcake</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Santa Woes, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   `Tis is better to give than to receive,
especially if what you give is a fruitcake.
   An American Express survey about Christmas gifts found that the
fruitcake was chosen most often from a list of ``worst'' holiday
gifts.
   It even finished ahead of ``no gift at all,'' the second choice.
Fruitcake was picked as the worst gift by 31 percent, ``no gift'' by
18 percent.
   Anything that has to be assembled was third on the list of bad
ideas, followed by damaged gifts, another tie or blouse, and a gift
that needs batteries but doesn't come with them.
   The same survey asked people what they would do with a bad gift.
Thirty percent said they would hide it in the closet, 21 percent
said they would return it, and 19 percent said they would give it
away.
   Nine percent specified they would give it to someone else as a
gift, suggesting the Christmas fruitcake might get recycled as a
gift for the host of a New Year's party.
   The survey was conducted this fall By R.H. Bruskin Associates,
which questioned 1,000 men and women nationwide, age 18 or older.
</TEXT>
