<DOCNO> AP881202-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1449EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hijack-History     12-02 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijack-History,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Reversed Practice By Letting Hijackers Go</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The decision by Soviet authorities to permit armed
hijackers to fly out of the country Friday marked a sharp reversal
from the two previous known air piracies, both of which ended in
fatal shootouts.
   But the Foreign Ministry's statement that the decision was made
``to save the children'' was consistent with Soviet tradition and
policy that focuses considerable official attention on the care and
upbringing of the nation's young.
   The five hijackers seized a busload of children in the city of
Ordzhonikidze in southern Russia, then traded the hostages for a
plane out of the country. They surrendered after landing in Israel
with a hostage crew of eight.
   Before Mikhail S. Gorbachev rose to power in March 1985,
incidents such as hijackings rarely were mentioned by the tightly
controlled official press.
   The labor newspaper Trud reported in July that there have been
more than 50 attempted hijackings in the Soviet Union in the past 15
years. Few of them were reported by the Soviet media.
   In March, an 11-member family musical troupe from Siberia seized
an Aeroflot jet in March with 76 passengers aboard over the Urals
and demanded to be flown to London. According to published reports,
authorities ordered the plane to land at a small airstrip near
Leningrad, tricking the hijackers into thinking they were landing in
nearby Finland.
   The hijackers shot a stewardess when they realized they had been
duped, the reports said, and after two hours of negotiations, a
police assault team stormed the plane, prompting the hijackers to
detonate a bomb that destroyed the aircraft.
   Nine people, including five of the hijackers, three passengers
and the stewardess, were killed. Nineteen people were seriously
wounded.
   The other reported incident took place Sept. 20, 1986, in the
Ural Mountains city of Ufa, when armed members of the internal
security forces hijacked an airliner. Media reports at the time said
five people, including two hijackers, were killed when authorities
stormed the plane. The other perpetrators were tried and sentenced,
the report said, but few details were provided.
   Air piracy is a capital offense in the Soviet Union.
   In one of the best known cases, Soviet authorities arrested 26
people in connection with an abortive attempt on June 17, 1970, by
11 Soviet Jews to board and hijack an aircraft in Leningrad to fly
to Sweden.
   Several of those arrested were refuseniks, or Jews who have been
refused permission to emigrate. The 26 were convicted in four
separate trials. Two were sentenced to death, with their sentences
later commuted, and the rest received lengthy prison terms.
   The same year two Soviet planes were hijacked to Turkey in
separate incidents. In 1977, two were commandeered and forced to fly
to Sweden.
   Four unsuccessful attempts to hijack Soviet airliners were
reported between 1961 and 1966.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881202-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1454EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WrongHouse     12-02 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wrong House,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police SWAT Team Surrounds Wrong House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police answering a report that a man was
holding his girlfriend hostage mistakenly surrounded the house next
door, then shooed the man away when he tried to surrender, police
and witnesses said.
   ``I didn't know what was coming down,'' said the man, Jessie
Cobb, 37. ``I came out and they started cussing me and told me to go
back inside. I thought they were going to pull a `Rambo' on me.''
   Both he and his girlfriend, Joyce Gaines, said later that the
incident was an argument that had been blown out of proportion. She
denied that she told police by telephone that Cobb had a knife, as
police said later.
   No arrests were made.
   Police were called to the house Wednesday by a neighbor who said
Cobb was holding Ms. Gaines there against her will.
   But because of a mixup, the police Special Operations Team
surrounded the house next door. When Cobb tried to surrender,
officers frantically waived him back inside, thinking he was just a
curious neighbor and telling him he was in danger.
   Police Sgt. John Bowman said the confusion intensified when Ms.
Gaines told hostage negotiators by telephone that she could hear
officers knocking on the door.
   ``She apparently was hearing the officers' rather heavy-handed
knocking on the house next door, but our negotiators didn't know
that,'' Bowman said.
   A witness, Johnny Walker, said he tried to tell police they were
at the wrong house, but officers told him they knew what they were
doing.
   ``This old boy in the meantime had come out two or three times to
give himself up, and the tactical squad ran him back in the house,
saying he could get hurt,'' Walker said.
   Bowman said officers were embarrassed by the incident, but
officers handled the situation the best way they could with the
information available.
   ``You can armchair quarterback this thing to death. It happened,
and the comic overtones are not unknown to us,'' Bowman said. At any
rate, he said, no one got hurt.
</TEXT>
