<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1455EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SouthAfrica Bjt   12-02 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa, Bjt,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Editor Banned from Journalism, Anti-Government Action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government released a black
newspaper editor Friday after two years of detention without charge,
but it banned him from journalistic or anti-government activity.
   Also on Friday, the government reportedly freed the head of a
banned black educational group, and an anti-apartheid newspaper was
back in print after a four-week ban.
   The newspaper editor, Zwelakhe Sisulu, was the best known of
South Africa's thousands of emergency detainees and there had been
an international campaign urging his release. He is editor of New
Nation, an outspoken anti-apartheid newspaper, and had been a Nieman
Fellow at Harvard.
   ``Amongst other things, I can't go back to the paper,'' were the
only words Sisulu uttered as newsmen swarmed around him outside
Johannesburg Prison in the black township of Diepkloof.
   Later, he appeared briefly at a packed news conference, but was
advised to leave by his attorney, because the restrictions placed on
him bar him from talking to the news media and attending a gathering
of more than 10 people.
   Late Friday, police banned a rally planned Sunday in a Soweto
church to celebrate the freedom of Zeph Mothopeng, the leader of the
outlawed Pan-Africanist Congress who was released from prison Nov.
26 on humanitarian grounds because of his illness. Major leaders
against apartheid, the government's system of racial separation, had
been scheduled to speak.
   Sisulu, 37, rejoins his wife and two young children in the black
township of Soweto outside Johannesburg. Sisulu's attorney,
Priscilla Jana, said he is barred from writing for any publication,
leaving the Johannesburg area, participating in any activity in
which the government is criticized, talking to the news media, or
going to any school.
   He is also required to report to police twice a day and be in his
home at night, Jana said.
   ``This is the harshest (restriction) order so far under the
emergency regulations,'' Jana said. ``It seems he can do virtually
nothing. He is imprisoned in his own house.''
   Lt. Peet Bothma of the Law and Order Ministry said several other
detainees were to be released Friday but gave no details.
   Eric Molobi, national coordinator for the banned National
Education Crisis Committee, was freed, according to his attorney,
Azhar Cachalia. The committee sought to increase black control over
curriculum and policies in black schools.
   Molobi, detained for a year, was placed under restrictions
similar to Sisulu's. He cannot leave his home from 6 p.m. to 6 a.m.,
must remain in Johannesburg and is prohibited from participating in
activities of major anti-apartheid organizations, Cachalia said.
   Sisulu's parents are among the country's best-known activists.
His father is Walter Sisulu, a jailed leader of the outlawed African
National Congress and a close colleague of ANC leader Nelson
Mandela, who has been moved from a jail to a hospital to recuperate
from tuberculosis.
   Sisulu's mother, Albertina, a co-president of the banned United
Democratic Front anti-apartheid coalition, is under government
restrictions that prevent her from being quoted or attending
gatherings.
   Sisulu, who will turn 38 on Dec. 17, was hospitalized in June for
treatment of depression.
   The Sisulu family has been awarded the Carter-Menil Human Rights
Prize, but it is expected that only Zwelakhe's exiled older brother
and sister will attend the award ceremony in Atlanta on Dec. 10. He
has another brother and sister in South Africa, and an adopted
brother in prison.
   Since he was detained in December 1986, Sisulu's newspaper,
published by the Southern African Catholic Bishop's Conference, was
banned for three months.
   Another anti-apartheid newspaper, The Weekly Mail, returned to
newsstands Friday after being banned for four weeks as an alleged
``threat to the public.'' It was the third paper that Home Affairs
Minister Stoffel Botha has suspended this year under powers granted
to him under the 29-month-old state of emergency.
   Censorship rules under the emergency ban or restrict reporting
about unrest, security force actions, treatment of detainees, many
forms of peaceful protest and a broad range of statements the
government considers subversive.
   A government official said Friday ``action will be instituted''
against a new Afrikaans-language anti-apartheid weekly, Vrye
Weekblad (Free Weekly), because the newspaper has published for a
month without registering.
   Gerrie van Zyl, director-general of the Department of Home
Affairs, said the action would be taken against the paper ``to
ensure good order.''
   The government had ordered the paper to pay a $13,000 deposit for
a registration certificate.
</TEXT>
