<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1519EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--BadSmog     12-02 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Bad Smog,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Southern California's 1988 Smog Ranked 3rd Worst Of Decade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern Californians just suffered through
one of the worst smog seasons of the decade, air quality officials
said.
   Ozone levels in the South Coast Air Basin surpassed federal
standards on 172 of the 184 days of this past smog season, which
runs from May 1 to Oct. 31. That number was exceeded only twice in
this decade.
   Ozone levels were above federal standards on 180 days in 1981 and
173 days in 1984.
   The smog season is the time of year when Southern California's
temperatures are the hottest and its air the most stagnant, factors
that contribute strongly in the creation of air pollution.
   Ozone is formed in sunlight by the reaction of nitrogen oxides, a
product of combustion, with certain hydrocarbon compounds such as
gasoline vapors and solvents.
   Ozone lowers resistance to infection, exacerbates chronic
respiratory illness and can cause permanent lung damage in people
exposed to high levels over a period of several years.
</TEXT>
