<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FactoryOrders     12-02 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Factory Orders,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Factory Orders Up 1.6 Percent in October</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY34</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for manufactured goods
increased 1.6 percent in October, driven by a surge in spending for
military equipment, the government said Friday.
   The Commerce Department said orders for durable and non-durable
goods climbed to a seasonally adjusted $226.2 billion, following a
1.9 percent decline in September.
   Defense spending shot up 42.5 percent to $10.6 billion, on the
strength of orders for ships and tanks, after falling 7.0 percent in
September.
   ``The military sector just went through the roof with the opening
of the new fiscal year,'' said David Wyss, an economist with Data
Resources Inc., a forecasting firm in Lexington, Mass. ``The
generals had money in their checking accounts again, so they were
busy writing checks.''
   However, Wyss said even excluding defense orders, manufacturing
remains strong. He pointed to the backlog of unfilled orders, which
jumped 0.8 percent in October, 0.3 percent in September and 1.2
percent in August.
   ``We're still getting more orders in than we're shipping goods
out,'' he said.
   New orders for the first 10 months of this year are up 9.3
percent from a year ago, compared with a 6.6 percent increase
between the same periods in 1987 and 1986.
   However, the key category of non-defense capital goods,
considered a good barometer of industry investment plans, fell 3.0
percent to $33.8 billion, following a large 10.2 percent drop in
September.
   Earlier in the year, this sector provided much of the momentum
for economic growth as industries geared up to meet an export boom
fueled by the lower value of the dollar abroad.
   ``It looks to me like the investment boom has gone past its peak,
and that's bad news. We really need new investment, and having it
fall off is a problem,'' said Robert Brusca, an economist with Nikko
Securities Co. International Inc.
   October orders followed a pattern set over the last several
months in which the presence or absence of big transportation and
military orders influenced overall performance.
   Transportation spending, bolstered by motor vehicle manufacturing
in addition to tank and shipbuilding, jumped 8.5 percent in October
to $34.3 billion after a decline of 8.9 percent in September.
   Excluding the transportation category, orders rose 0.4 percent in
October and fell 0.7 percent in September. Minus defense, orders
edged up 0.2 percent in October after dropping 1.7 percent in
September.
   Orders for all durable goods, ``big ticket'' items expected to
last three or more years, rose 2.3 percent in October to $122.1
billion after a 2.8 percent drop in September.
   Meanwhile, orders for non-durable goods climbed 0.8 percent in
October to $104.2 billion after an identical drop of 0.8 a month
earlier. Chemicals accounted for most of the increase, although most
industries were up.
   Wyss said the vigor in the non-durable industries, which were
having capacity problems early in the year, could signal renewed
price pressures.
   Shipments of manufactured goods were up by 0.5 percent in October
to $222.5 billion.
</TEXT>
