<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Duarte     12-02 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Duarte,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Duarte Hospitalized, Recovering Well from Intestinal Infection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvadoran President Jose Napoleon Duarte, who
is suffering from liver cancer, was hospitalized with an intestinal
infection, the Mexican foreign minister said Friday.
   ``He's doing very, very well,'' said Ricardo Acevedo Peralta, the
foreign minister. ``He had a minor intestinal infection but it's
been overcome.''
   Duarte, 63, attended the inauguration of President Carlos Salinas
de Gortari on Thursday.
   He was taken to the hospital with a temperature about 6 p.m.,
Acevedo Peralta said.
   ``He had an exhausting day'' meeting with Presidents Raul
Alfonsin of Argentina, Vinicio Cerezo of Guatemala and Daniel Ortega
of Nicaragua in addition to Salinas, Acevedo Peralta said.
   Asked if the problem was the the intestinal malady that afflicts
tourists in Mexico, he replied, ``That's it in part, the change in
diet and the work.''
   ``The president's condition is delicate,'' he said. ``It's better
to have him here (in the hospital) 48 hours. You know you have to
take care of any infection.''
   Duarte probably would return to his hotel Saturday, he said, and
is expected to return to El Salvador on Sunday or Monday.
   In San Salvador, Vice-President Rodolfo Castillo Claramount said
he had spoken to Duarte by telephone Friday and said the health
problem is principally the result of chemotherapy Duarte underwent
recently. The fever was due to an intestinal infection, inflammation
of the colon and slight dehydration, Castillo Claramount said.
   Doctors have said Duarte's health has improved remarkably in the
past two months. The spread of the cancer in his liver has been
arrested and other organs have not been affected, they say.
   He has been handling a nearly normal work load and has made
campaign appearances on behalf of his Christian Democratic Party's
presidential candidate, Fidel Chavez Mena.
   Party officials had counted on Duarte, whose five-year term ends
next year, being able to campaign to boost their prospects in March
19 presidential elections.
   When Duarte arrived in Mexico City on Wednesday, his first stop
was the Basilica of Guadalupe, the holiest shrine for this country's
predominantly Roman Catholic population. He said he had thanked the
Virgin of Guadalupe, to whom the basilica is dedicated, for his
improved health.
</TEXT>
