<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     12-02 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PUEBLO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deciding that free coffee was not much of a
threat to the public, the county health board has pulled the plug on
a brewing controversy by waiving a rule that even the city council
was violating.
   Few people knew it, but under the law, every business or
organization that gave out coffee or soft drinks to the public was
required to buy a $50 food-service permit.
   That meant all those doctors' offices, beauty shops, auto-repair
businesses and even the City Council, which handed coffee out free,
were in violation.
   This week, the Pueblo County Health Board voted to waive the
required license. Businesses that otherwise are not in the food
business are free to offer coffee, soft drinks or wrapped pastries
to their customers.
   ``We're trying to enforce the intent of the law, not necessarily
the letter of the law,'' said health division chief Roger Stasiak.
``The intent is to protect the public's health, and coffee has not
proven to be a significant problem.''
   ``It's such a burden off my mind,'' joked Merle Souder, manager
of a Meineke discount muffler shop, after the vote was take.
   Souder said he doesn't keep the coffee pot in a public area of
his store, ``but that's not to say some of our regular customers
don't head straight for the coffee pot.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty of Hong Kong's burliest policemen failed
Friday in an attempt to break the record set by their British
counterparts for pulling a jumbo jet 100 yards with a rope.
   The record of 57.7 seconds was set by a group of policemen at
London's Heathrow airport in May.
   Huffing and puffing, the policemen here took 1 minute, 11.4
seconds to pull the British Airways Boeing 747 the same distance at
the Hong Kong Airport.
   The event was staged by the Royal Hong Kong Police Force and
British Airways to raise about $25,000 for a home for the
handicapped in this British colony.
   Officer Karl Spencer said his men were disappointed at failing to
break the record, but he said they were at a disadvantage. The plane
together with the fuel weighed at least 185 tons, while the plane at
Heathrow in May was not carrying any fuel and weighed about 170 tons.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOVES PARK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Not even the U.S. Postal Service can
fight City Hall in this Rockford suburb _ not when Mayor Joseph
Sinkiawic's civic pride gets irritated.
   If the U.S. Postal Service had gotten its way, the silver
lettering on the outside of the new post office here would have said
``Rockford, Ill.'' After all, though it's in Loves Park, a town of
15,000, it's a branch of the Rockford office.
   ``That's a real slap in the face as far as we're concerned,''
Sinkiawic said Thursday. ``We're a proud city, and we want to have
an idenity.''
   Thanks to the complaints the mayor made to his congresswoman and
senators, the sign will say what the sign on the previous post
office building said for 40 years: ``Loves Park, Ill.''
   The mayor had called a news conference for Thursday to denounce
the proposed change. Two hours before it was scheduled to begin,
Sinkiawic received a call from Rockford Postmaster Don Brocher
saying the words ``Loves Park, Ill.'' would stay.
   The mayor credited calls Rep. Lynn Martin, and Illinois' two U.S.
senators, Alan Dixon and Paul Simon, with forestalling what would
have been a ``David and Goliath'' battle.
 
</TEXT>
