<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1617EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Korea     12-02 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Korea,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Says Officials Won't Testify Before Korean Committee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Friday it has
rejected a request from a South Korean legislative committee that
top U.S. diplomatic and military officials testify in person about
their knowledge of any U.S. role in a bloody 1980 uprising in that
country.
   Instead, the department will be willing to respond to written
questions from the committee, deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said.
   The National Assembly committee had asked that then-U.S.
Ambassador William Gleysteen and the commander of U.S. forces in
Korea, John Wickham, testify about their knowledge of the incidents
at Kwangju when hundreds _ perhaps thousands _ of people were killed
in clashes with the South Korean military.
   Mrs. Oakley said the views of Gleysteen and Wickham, both of whom
have since ended their service in Korea, will be incorporated in the
official responses to written questions.
   Allegations have been made that the United States acquiesced in
the transfer of Korean troops to Kwangju for the purpose of
violently suppressing the rebellion.
   Opposition leader Kim Dae-jung has said the United States did not
do enough to prevent the killings.
   Mrs. Oakley said that after careful consideration, the department
determined it would be ``inappropriate'' for Gleysteen and Wickham
to testify in person but written responses would be agreed to
because the incident at Kwangju is a matter of ``great concern'' in
Korea.
   In ruling out personal appearances by the two officials, Mrs.
Oakley said the department ``considered basic principles of
international comity and the manner in which foreign relations are
conducted.''
   ``We also considered principals of immunity of government
officials from providing testimony before foreign legislative
bodies,'' she said.
   She added that the department believes it can be fully responsive
to the committee's requirements through written answers.
</TEXT>
