<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan     12-02 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bhutto Takes Oath of Office; Promises `Peace, Liberty and Progress'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Benazir Bhutto took the oath of office
Friday as prime minister, assuming the job her father lost in a coup
11 years ago and promising to ``choose the path of law.''
   ``Our message is one of hope, peace, liberty and progress,'' Ms.
Bhutto told a nationwide televised address after the ceremony.
   About 300 Pakistani officials, lawmakers and foreign ambassadors
attended the 15-minute swearing-in ceremony in the presidency, a
flat, modern building between the Senate and National Assembly in
the federal capital.
   After reciting the oath, Ms. Bhutto received an extended round of
applause that was drowned out when members of her Pakistan People's
Party rose and cheered ``Bhutto lives!''
   The 35-year-old woman took the office once held by her father,
Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, who was deposed in a 1977 coup by Gen. Mohammed
Zia ul-Haq and hanged two years later.
   Zia ruled eight years under martial law and three years with a
limited civilian government before he died in an Aug. 17 plane
crash. A caretaker government resigned earlier Friday.
   In her television address, Ms. Bhutto promised her Pakistan's
People's Party ``will choose the path of law, eradicate hunger and
poverty, give shelter to the shelterless, employment to the
unemployed and we will educate the illiterate.''
   But she painted a bleak economic picture, saying ``our entire
fiscal system is nearing bankruptcy. We are faced with the prospect
of disaster, but a whole generation is ready to channel everything
in the direction of reconstruction.''
   Ms. Bhutto had pledged since her father's death to oust Zia and
restore democracy to Pakistan.
   ``Our struggle has now reached a successful culmination,'' she
said. ``The doors of Parliament that were shut are now open.''
   Before Zia's death, elections had been scheduled for Nov. 16.
   Ms. Bhutto's Pakistan People's Party won 105 seats in the
237-seat National Assembly, and she is said to have enough support
among minor parties and independents for a majority coalition.
   An eight-party grouping called the Islamic Democratic Alliance,
which includes Zia loyalists, won only 60 seats.
   Ms. Bhutto's father, the late Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, founded the
Pakistan People's Party that she now leads.
   ``I feel a mixture of happiness and sadness because I kept
thinking about my husband,'' said Bhutto's widow, Begum Nusrat
Bhutto, after she watched her daughter officially assume leadership.
   President Ghulam Ishaq Khan said he had received the resignations
of the caretaker government effective Friday.
   Ms. Bhutto, who studied at Radcliffe College in Cambridge, Mass.,
and at Oxford University in England, wed Karachi businessman Asif
Ali Zardari in a traditional Islamic arranged marriage a year ago.
She gave birth to a boy Sept. 21.
   Zia, U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel and 28 others died in the
August crash. Officials said sabotage was the probable cause, but
the probe is continuing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
