<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1653EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-EastGermany     12-02 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-East Germany,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador: East Germany Far From Diplomatic Ties With Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany has an ``extremely bad'' human rights
record and the Berlin Wall continues to bar better trade and
diplomatic ties with the United States, according to the departing
U.S. ambassador.
   Ambassador Francis J. Meehan called East Germany's claim it is
not responsible for Nazi crimes ``a bit ridiculous.''
   He predicted the communist nation will be slow to establish
diplomatic relations with Israel, despite recent wooing of Jewish
leaders.
   Meehan, 64, spoke in an interview Nov. 22 on condition his name
not be used until he left East Berlin on Dec. 1. He had been posted
there since 1985.
   On prospects for diplomatic ties with Israel, he said:
   ``I think they will be the slowest ship in the convoy to Tel
Aviv,'' although ``there is no question that East Germany now wants
to make an impact on the world Jewish community.''
   East Berlin and Tel Aviv have never had diplomatic relations.
   A procession of Jewish leaders have visited East Germany recently
and elaborate state-sponsored ceremonies in November marked the 50th
anniversary of the start of the Nazi pogrom.
   ``They know that they have lagged behind in this and that it is
important to get the world recognition they want,'' said Meehan.
   But he said the state's recent official treatment of Jewish
issues contrasts starkly to its refusal to accept moral
responsibility for the Holocaust.
   East Germany contends it is innocent of Nazi crimes because it
was founded in 1949 and because communists also were persecuted.
   ``This position is a bit ridiculous,'' Meehan said. ``It amounts
to saying the place was neutral territory during the war.''
   Meehan also noted that overtures to Jews are clouded by the
government's crackdown on the Lutheran Church because it has pushed
for dialogue inspired by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
policy of greater openness.
   ``This is where the tolerance ends,'' Meehan said. ``The party
leadership is pursuing a needlessly severe attitude.''
   Church publications have been censored or seized and human rights
activists allied with the church have been detained.
   ``In all, East Germany has an extremely bad record in human
rights,'' he said. This record and its refusal to pay U.S. claims
for seized property are main stumbling blocks to better relations
with Washington, he said.
   East Germany's desire for Most-Favored Nation trade status was
``out of the question.''
   ``It would be extremely difficult, if not impossible, to try and
argue in the Congress that there was a case for MFN for East Germany
so long as the wall is there and and so long as there are major
limitations on freedom of emigration,'' Meehan said.
   And there would be little growth in trade as long as U.S. claims
are unresolved.
   East Germany refuses to consider $80 million in claims filed by
U.S. companies and citizens for property lost after the nation was
founded. Interest has boosted the sum to $300 million.
   Meehan expected little change in East German leaders' resistance
to Soviet-style reforms.
   ``They don't quite know what's happening. They don't know where
it's leading and they're very unsure of the whole situation,'' he
said.
   But because East Germany's economy is strong compared with other
Warsaw Pact countries, it can afford to wait to gauge the outcome of
Gorbachev's reforms, he said.
</TEXT>
