<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Soviet     12-02 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Soviet,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet-Israel Contacts During Hijack May Spur Improved Ties</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hijacking of a jetliner by five armed
Soviets who surrendered here Friday comes at a time of increasing
contacts between Moscow and Israel.
   The cooperation between Israeli and Soviet officials and the fact
the hijacking ended without bloodshed could accelerate the process
of reconciliation.
   Some analysts were encouraged by the fact that Soviet authorities
asked Israel to let the Aeroflot jet land, maintained diplomatic
contacts throughout the day, and sent the head of their mission in
Israel to observe events at Ben-Gurion Airport near Tel Aviv.
   ``This can only be seen as an improvement in relations and an
important step forward for Israel's ... standing with the Soviets,''
said Ted Friedgut, a professor of Soviet politics at Hebrew
University.
   ``In the past, the Soviets would never have considered giving the
plane authority to come to Israel. Perhaps they wanted to signal
that they're ready to trust Israel with something serious ... It
could be a step toward normal relations,'' Friedgut said in an
interview.
   A Foreign Ministry official also welcomed the cooperation but was
more restrained in his optimism.
   ``Of course everybody will be very happy if this ends in good
cooperation between the two countries,'' the official said on
condition of anonymity.
   ``I wouldn't say it should be regarded as a breakthrough. But
yes, you may say it shows the Soviets at least have the minimum
confidence that things will be handled properly here,'' he said.
   The Foreign Ministry indicated Israel would react positively to a
Soviet request for extradition.
   ``The moment we get a request, we will examine it. I don't see
any reason why we would want to hold them,'' said spokesman Alon
Liel.
   The Soviets broke diplomatic ties with Israel after the 1967
Middle East war when the Jewish state seized the West Bank, Gaza
Strip, east Jerusalem and Golan Heights from Moscow's Arab allies.
   A gradual thaw in relations began in July 1987 when the Soviet
Union sent a quasi-permanent consular delegation to Tel Aviv. Israel
responded by sending a delegation to Moscow in April.
   This year the Soviet Union met a key Israeli demand by permitting
a growing number of Jews to leave the country. The year's exodus of
16,572 Jews through November is more than double last year's outflow
of 8,011. The 1988 emigration figure is expected to be the highest
in eight years.
   The warming of ties also has extended to the Soviet-allied
Eastern bloc, all of whose members severed ties with Israel in 1967
except Romania.
   In September, Hungary announced it was renewing full diplomatic
ties after a 21-year break. The announcement followed visits to
Budapest by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Foreign Minister
Shimon Peres.
   Cultural ties have also been improving. Moments after the
hijackers surrendered, Yevgeny Yevtushenko, a 55-year-old Soviet
poet, landed in Israel for a series of poetry readings in Jerusalem,
Tel Aviv and other Israeli towns.
   ``It is such an unhappy incident, but I am landing here
completely voluntarily,'' Yevtushenko joked on Israel televison.
</TEXT>
