<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Blind-Rescue     12-02 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Blind-Rescue,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mail Carrier Rescues Blind Woman From 9-Foot-Deep Hole</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BAENEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mail carrier making his rounds heard a
scream and rescued a blind woman and her guide dog who had fallen
into a 9-foot-deep hole.
   ``I feel he was really my angel for Christmas,'' Connie Kelley
said after her rescue Thursday. ``Probably he will have an extra
present under his Christmas tree this year.''
   Jack Grothe, 37, a four-year employee with the U.S. Postal
Service, said he was delivering mail when he heard Ms. Kelley
scream. He found her and her guide dog, Dazzle, trapped in a hole
which was dug by workers repairing a water line.
   ``I couldn't reach her,'' Grothe said. ``I had to jump in. ... I
picked her up, walked to the edge, pushed her out and her dog, then
got out myself.''
   ``Being a mailman, I'm a little cautious with dogs, and this dog
was really wonderful,'' Grothe said.
   Ms. Kelley, 29, said she was going shopping when she fell into
the hole _ and through no fault of the guide dog.
   ``My dog was hesitant at first, and I made her go forward,'' she
said. ``She saw the hole up ahead I didn't know was there.''
   As the dog tried to squeeze her between the hole and a ladder,
Ms. Kelley's foot slipped and she fell in, dragging Dazzle with her.
She said she was trapped in there three to five minutes before
Grothe found her.
   ``I think if I had been there any longer I wouldn't have had the
strength to get out of there with help,'' she said.
   Doug Michaud, chief inspector for utility connections for the
city of Minneapolis, said employees of Pete's Water and Sewer had
neglected to put guard rails around the hole and had left it
unattended.
   He said he had reprimanded the owner, Dennis Skjod, but lacked
the power to issue a citation.
   Skjod said his workers told him they had left the site to get
some parts and that they had put up a small barricade, enough to
warn away a sighted person.
   ``It's a lesson to be learned,'' he said. ``From now on, when we
do jobs we'll have sightless people in mind, and I thank God nothing
serious happened.'' He said he called Ms. Kelley and visited her
home after hearing about the accident.
</TEXT>
