<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0651 12-02 0835</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0651,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Visits Capital, Wishes Things Were Different</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis, Bush quotes in top 12 grafs, picking up
in 6th graf pvs, Dukakis had</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis visited Washington Friday for
the first time since losing the presidential election, sadly
conceding ``I wish I was here in another capacity.''
   Still, he received warm welcomes from Democratic Party leaders on
Capitol Hill during a morning full of meetings before going to the
home of the man who defeated him, President-elect George Bush, for a
private visit.
   ``When it's all over, we don't throw bombs at each other; we sit
down with each other,'' Dukakis said before his session with Bush.
   Afterward, Dukakis had few kind personal words for his bitter
election rival but promised to cooperate with the new
administration, provided Bush works to cut the federal deficit
without turning his back on health care, day care, education and
other issues that the Democrat focused on during his campaign.
   ``Do I look bitter?'' Dukakis asked in response to a question
after a 35-minute meeting with Bush. ``I feel pretty good actually.''
   Dukakis said the meeting did not include any talk about the tone
of the campaign, which Dukakis criticized at the time. ``That's over
now and our job is to meet some very formidable problems,'' he said.
But he managed to work in a swipe at Reagan administration deficit
spending and warned Bush against continuing such policies.
   Asked if he now considered himself a friend of the
president-elect, Dukakis at first laughed and then said: ``I'm
anxious to cooperate and play a constructive role.''
   Bush, in brief comments to reporters, said he looked forward to
working with Dukakis and other governors.
   ``To you and Kitty and that wonderful family, God bless you and
have a great Christmas,'' Bush told the departing Dukakis.
   Dukakis also had a brief encounter with Vice President-elect Dan
Quayle, who was at the Bush residence when Dukakis arrived.
   ``We shook hands and greeted each other,'' said Dukakis, who
during the campaign scornfully referred to the Indiana senator in
nearly every speech.
   The trip to the nation's capital was far different from the last
time Dukakis came, near the end of the campaign, when he still had
Secret Service protection and was accompanied by a phalanx of aides.
This time he took a commercial flight, accompanied by only two
aides, and traveled around town in a crowded rental car. He met with
Washington-based campaign workers before heading home to Boston.
   Dukakis had lunch Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, who was the
Democratic vice presidential nominee, and met separately with
congressional leaders including House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas,
and new Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine.
   Some party leaders have been highly critical of Dukakis and his
presidential campaign, but Bentsen, Wright and Mitchell said he
still had a part to play in party leadership.
   ``I think it's a very major role,'' Bentsen said.
   ``We're very proud of Mike Dukakis,'' Wright said at an earlier
meeting. ``He fought a good fight.''
   Dukakis dodged questions about whether he would consider running
for president again, saying he was too busy catching up on
gubernatorial duties to think about his political future.
   But Wright said, ``All of us look to him for leadership, for
ideas, for guidance, for cooperation. ... Governor Dukakis is young.
His future is not behind him. It is ahead of him. I think he has a
lot to give this country.''
   Dukakis thanked the speaker for his praise but did not hide his
disappointment in losing the election.
   ``I think in time I'll probably emerge stronger but I'd be less
than candid if I didn't say I wish I was here in another capacity,''
Dukakis said.
   Mitchell, after a separate meeting with his fellow New Englander,
also praised Dukakis as ``a national leader of our party.''
   Dukakis promised to maintain a party presence but did not claim
to be the Democrats' national leader.
   ``We have a good strong party, with lots of leaders,'' he said.
``I hope to make a contribution.''
   Just a week before the election Dukakis said he had no respect
for Bush because of the negative tone of the Republican campaign,
but on Friday he refused to be drawn into a new battle with his
election rival.
   ``I'm looking ahead; I assume he is,'' Dukakis said. ``The
election is over.''
   Dukakis also visited with Massachusetts Sens. Edward Kennedy and
John Kerry. Kennedy offered a question for Bush.
   ``The first thing we want to know is whether he still considers
Massachusetts a part of the union and we hope to get a positive
response,'' the senator said jokingly.
   Dukakis has been dealing with a state financial crisis at home
but plans to take a Florida vacation after next week. Spokesman
James Dorsey said Dukakis had no high-profile appearances planned
until February, when he is to return to Washington for the winter
meeting of the National Governors' Association.
</TEXT>
