<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hostages     12-02 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostages,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Letter Says Swiss Kidnapped To Swap For Hijacker; Cleric Blasts
U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A letter apparently signed by a kidnapped
Swiss Red Cross official and released Friday implied he was abducted
to be exchanged for a hijacker held in Geneva.
   A leading cleric, meanwhile, said the United States was
preventing the release of the nine American hostages held in Lebanon.
   No group has claimed responsibility for the abduction of Peter
Winkler, the 32-year-old Swiss Red Cross delegate seized by three
gunmen in the southern port of Sidon Nov. 17.
   ``I was not kidnapped as a Red Cross delegate but as a Swiss
citizen. My government knows what my kidnappers want from it and it
has to cooperate in order to save my life,'' said the letter,
delivered to a Western news agency.
   The 56-word letter in English did not include a picture of
Winkler, which is the usual method of proving its authenticity, nor
did it provide any indication of the kidnappers' identity.
   Lebanese police theorize Winkler was seized to swap him for
Shiite Moslem air pirate Hussein Hariri. He has been held in
Switzerland for more than 16 months and is scheduled to go on trial
Feb. 20.
   The Red Cross confirmed the signature was Winkler's and the Swiss
government warned its citizens to avoid all but essential travel to
Lebanon.
   ``It looks very much like blackmail,'' said Edouard Brunner, the
No. 2 man in the Swiss Foreign Ministry.
   Shiite Moslem cleric Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah charged
Friday that the United States has complicated the release of
Americans held by pro-Iranian factions in Lebanon.
   ``I have information that the Americans are the ones who
complicated the issue of the hostages,'' said Fadlallah, who has
close ties with Iran, in an interview with the weekly magazine
Ash-Shiraa.
   ``America is panting after a resumption of ties with Iran, but it
wants ties resumed in a way by which no political concession is
made,'' he said. ``Iran rejects a resumption of ties unless America
changed its hostile policy against Iran as well as some details
related to bilateral relations including the frozen Iranian assets
and others.''
   Fadlallah is the reputed spiritual guide of the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God. Hezbollah, made up of Shiite zealots
loyal to Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, is the umbrella group
for pro-Iranian underground factions holding most of the 14 Western
hostages.
   The hostage held longest is American Terry Anderson, chief Middle
East correspondent for The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March
16, 1985.
   The Red Cross suspended its Sidon operations _ including services
for the handicapped and visiting Palestinians detained in Israeli
prisons _ and withdrew the remaining five Swiss delegates.
   Harari, 22, a member of Hezbollah, hijacked an Air Afrique
jetliner while on flight from Rome to Paris and forced it to land at
Geneva airport July 24, 1987. He killed a French passenger before he
was overpowered and arrested.
   Also Friday, the mother of 32-year-old Belgian physician Jan
Cools pleaded in a videotaped message for help in finding her son,
missing in Lebanon for more than six months.
   No group has claimed to have kidnapped Cools, missing after
leaving his residence in south Lebanon's Palestinian refugee camp of
Rashidiyeh May 21.
</TEXT>
