<DOCNO> AP881202-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1806EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM_Boksburg     12-02 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM_Boksburg,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Few Blacks Sit-in at White Park, Council Vows Not to Yield</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOKSBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black leaders protested Friday in a
newly declared ``whites-only'' park, but the ultra-conservative town
council vowed to resist mounting pressure to abandon increased
segregation.
   ``We are going to carry out fearlessly the will of the white
people,'' Conservative Party official Koos van der Merwe said at an
emotional news conference in Boksburg. ``We will never surrender!
Never! Never! Never!''
   He said Conservatives are establishing a fund to support
councilors who become targets of economic sanctions aimed at forcing
them to reverse their decision.
   The Conservatives, who took control of Boksburg's town council in
nationwide local elections Oct. 26, called the conference to rebut
claims by the governing National Party that three Conservative
councilors planned to defect. That would tip the balance of power on
the 20-member council and enable the National Party faction to allow
blacks back to public facilities in the industrial town east of
Johannesburg.
   One by one, the 12 Conservative councilors stood up and pledged
their support for their party's policy.
   One of the resegegrated facilities is the town's 37-acre park,
Boksburg Lake, where 11 black leaders from neighboring townships
staged a peaceful protest.
   ``South Africa belongs to all of us,'' declared Tom Boya, head of
a national association of black local officials.
   The protest was billed as a mass sit-in, but the officials said
poor organization led to a low turnout. Dozens of reporters, but no
police, were on hand.
   ``Be warned, do not push the patience of the people too far,''
Boya said, asking, ``Where is this beautiful town being led? Is it
being pushed to the Stone Age where no black person was supposed to
be in town after certain times?''
   Boksburg was the first of several Conservative-controlled towns
to announce resegregation of facilities opened to all races in
recent years. The party won control of about 100 towns in October.
In some, councilors are considering curfews for blacks.
   Black residents are boycotting Boksburg's white-owned shops, and
sports federations and corporations have threatened to withdraw from
towns where resegregation takes place.
   The National Party, which enacted South Africa's apartheid laws
during 40 years in power, has denounced the Conservatives' moves,
but has been widely accused of hypocrisy.
   ``What we are doing is done by the National Party is every second
town,'' van der Merwe said. ``They should either stop criticizing us
or open all the water fountains, swimming pools, libraries and
beaches.''
   Early Friday, a bomb exploded outside a tax office in Boksburg.
Police said no one was injured in the blast, caused by a small
limpet mine. There was no indication whether it was connected to the
racial controversy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
