<DOCNO> AP881202-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1806EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Fission     12-02 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fission,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Germans Recall Fateful Discovery of Nuclear Fission 50 Years
Ago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Eberhard Diepgen extolled the discovery of
nuclear fission Friday, but said he cannot celebrate consequences
``from Hiroshima to Chernobyl'' as West Germans marked the 50th
anniversary of the breakthrough. Mixed with praise for the
scientific leap were words of caution about end results of the
revelation in a Berlin laboratory by German scientists Otto Hahn and
Fritz Strassmann in December 1938.
   ``We cannot simply pay respect to the enormous and unexpected
satisfaction of the human thirst for knowledge, without at the same
time also calling to mind the consequences _ from Hiroshima to
Chernobyl,'' the mayor told 1,100 guests at West Berlin's Congress
Hall.
   Other speakers also pointed to the bitter lessons of the U.S.
bombing of the Japanese cities of Hiroshima and Nagasaki in August
1945 and the April 1986 nuclear accident at Chernobyl in the Soviet
Union.
   ``This discovery changed the world like hardly any other one
before it, technically and spiritually as well as economically and
above all politically,'' Diepgen said.
   ``Today we recall this great scientific deed, without being able
to celebrate,'' said the mayor, a member of Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
conservative Christian Democratic party.
   Resistance to nuclear power remains strong among younger West
Germans, especially since Chernobyl. The disaster in the Soviet
Ukraine dumped radioactivity over large parts of West Germany,
causing widespread restrictions on sales of fresh meat and produce.
   West Germans, located at the front line of the East-West
struggle, also remain wary of nuclear weapons despite the current
removal of medium-range U.S. rockets from their soil.
   On Dec. 16, 1938, Hahn and Strassmann started their fateful
experiment in a laboratory in Berlin's Dahlem section. It showed
that bombarding the uranium atom with neutrons leads to its
splitting.
   At first the pair were unsure of the implications. Then, from her
exile in Sweden, their Jewish colleague Lise Meitner theorized that
such a splitting could lead to the release of huge amounts of energy
through chain reactions.
   Hahn won the 1944 Nobel Prize in chemistry for the work conducted
at the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute for Chemistry.
   Albert Speer, the Nazi arms minister, later implied Hahn was
among German scientists trying to develop the atomic bomb bu many
people say Hahn dissociated himself from such efforts.
   During Friday's ceremony, researcher Professor Peter Brix said
the Hahn and Strassmann discovery, besides leading to nuclear power,
also brought about advancements in nuclear medicine and even
astrophysics.
   ``On the other side of the coin'' were victims of Hiroshima and
Nagasaki, nuclear weapons stockpiles and distrust of nuclear power
since Chernobyl, he said.
   ``Many people now have a basic mistrust of science,'' added Brix,
who is from West Germany's prestigious Max-Planck Institute.
   It organized the formal ceremony with four other scientific
research organizations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
