<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Weinberger     12-02 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weinberger,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weinberger Hits Loans to Soviets as Strengthening Military</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Defense Secretary Caspar W. Weinberger
on Friday sharply attacked $7 billion in European loans to Moscow as
a potential aid to the Soviet military.
   ``These may be all going into production of better fertilizer,''
he said in a speech to business executives. ``The same chemicals,
however, are used for chemical warfare in many cases. The problem is
we don't know. I don't think we are at the stage where we can trust
unquestioningly their pretensions.''
   The loans are not linked to particular transactions and have been
made in the past two months, he said. He added that the bulk of them
are guaranteed by west European governments.
   In other remarks prepared in advance he called for immediate
high-level consultations by the United States and its allies on
issues of economic and financial security.
   ``I think NATO _ with full EC (European Economic Community) and
Japanese endorsement _ should incorporate these new issues into
plans to bolster alliance defense burden-sharing and ensure that the
West does not continue the gratuitous, undisciplined financing of
many Soviet activities around the world inimical to vital Western
security interests,'' he wrote.
   He defined burden-sharing as: ``They (America's allies) pay more
and we pay less.''
   A member of the audience commented that U.S. grain sales also
help the Soviet Union by freeing up its resources.
   ``We're guilty too,'' Weinberger replied.
   ``I'm not criticizing Europeans. I'm criticizing the rush to do
this on a rather broad basis and without any attempt to verify what
the proceeds are going to be used for.''
   In his prepared remarks he pointed to Soviet sales of bonds in
the West and the possibility that in time millions of Westerners
could wittingly or unwittingly hold such bonds in their own
portfolios or through pension funds.
   ``And, inevitably, soon thereafter, they would be told that that
was another reason to grant favors and help that `nice' Mr.
Gorbachev,'' Weinberger said.
   He noted reports that billions of Western dollars are on deposit
in banks owned by the Soviet bloc.
   Weinberger criticized what he called the growing romance between
the 12 governments of the community and the communist bloc. He said
businesses owned partly by west Europeans and partly by the Soviet
Union are a rapid way of putting Western know-how into Soviet hands.
   Weinberger, who stepped down as defense secretary in 1987, was
speaking at a business managers' conference on plans by the European
community governments to dismantle barriers to trade among them by
the year 1992.
   He said greater European unity could help Western defense, for
example by promoting standard weapons that could be used by all NATO
members.
</TEXT>
