<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0652 12-02 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0652,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Last North Motions; Secret Documents Remain Problem</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``The decisions ...'' to UPDATE with
hearings adjourned to Tuesday and CORRECTS figure of government
documents to 395 sted 350</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver L. North's remaining challenges to
Iran-Contra charges were rejected by a judge Friday, but the major
counts against him could still be scuttled by White House refusal to
release classified documents.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell rejected defense motions to
dismiss charges that the former National Security Council staff
member obstructed congressional investigations of reports he gave
covert military assistance to the Contra rebels in Nicaragua.
   The decisions were released as Gesell took the bench for a third
straight day of closed hearings on North's objections to censoring
395 government documents that independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh
wants to use as evidence against him. The secret hearings were
scheduled to resume Tuesday.
   Gesell's rulings disposed of the last of North's pre-trial
motions. His decisions have upheld 14 of the 16 charges originally
brought against North by Walsh.
   But the Reagan administration's decision not to allow North to
use any of the 40,000 pages of secret documents sought as defense
evidence poses a serious obstacle to going forward with the major
charges against the former presidential aide.
   About 90 percent of the classified material pertains to the broad
conspiracy charge that North and his three co-defendants illegally
diverted more than $14 million in profits from U.S. arms sales to
Iran to the Contras.
   The rest of the material involves 12 other counts, particularly
charges that North lied to Congress and destroyed NSC documents to
obstruct an inquiry of the Iran-Contra affair.
   Gesell has said repeatedly that North should be given wide
latitude to introduce secret documents relevant to defending the
conspiracy charge and a related count of theft of government
property.
   The judge has threatened to dismiss those charges if secret
documents he determines are necessary to North's defense are not
made available by the government for use at a public trial.
   On Thursday, President Reagan ruled out pardoning North but said
``duty requires'' him to withhold secret documents from the trial.
   Reagan denied the decision was a back-door maneuver to let North
off the hook on the major charges. ``The things we're blocking are
the things that duty requires we block,'' he said.
   Walsh contends that North does not need to disclose any secrets
to get a fair trial of the charges. He has asked Gesell to bar any
release by lawyers for the retired Marine lieutenant colonel.
   Gesell gave North until Dec. 19 to specify any other secrets he
considers important for his defense, including information that
might be elicited when high government officials are questioned on
the witness stand.
   The secrets that the administration won't release include the
existence of covert intelligence operations and the location of
American hostages in the Middle East.
   Disclosure of such information could expose ``people in very
difficult situations to torture and death,'' Walsh said in court
last spring at the outset of the case.
   But the information also includes the well-publicized names of
Central American countries that helped assist the Contras as well as
nations, such as Saudi Arabia and South Korea, that were asked to
donate money to the rebel cause.
   The countries were referred to by letter or number during
congressional hearings on the Iran-Contra affair, but their names
became widely known.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the names of
countries were ``one of the minor categories,'' indicating the
administration might be more flexible about revealing their identity.
   Gesell has repeatedly expressed impatience with the idea of
showing jurors documents stripped of references to information that
has already leaked into the public domain.
   In advance of this week's hearings, Gesell directed Walsh to
devise an alternative to referring to the foreign countries by
letter, saying ``this masking technique appears unduly cumbersome.''
   The defense contends that referring to countries by numbers or
letters would create confusion and make it impossible to question
witnesses.
   Defense lawyers also want to disclose secrets to support North's
contention that he destroyed documents to prevent disclosure of
covert operations by members of Congress or other government
officials.
   North and his co-defendants _ former national security adviser
John M. Poindexter and arms dealers Albert Hakin and Richard Secord
_ are to be tried separately.
</TEXT>
