<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SeniorSacrifice     12-02 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senior Sacrifice,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seniors Sacrifice Trip, Give $3,000 To Leukemia Victim</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ``Laatsch'' in 10th graf cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ALTAMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 60 seniors at Altamont High School are
skipping the annual class trip and donating their trip money to a
6-year-old leukemia victim, who needs $100,000 for a bone marrow
transplant.
   The seniors decided to give the $3,000 plus other funds they plan
to raise to Craig Grubaugh after hearing an emotional pitch from
Lynn Ingram, vice president of the local Jaycees, who went into the
classrooms to explain the youngster's plight.
   ``Her speech really got to you. There were a lot of tears,'' said
Johanna Smith, 17, secretary of the senior class in this central
Illinois town of 2,400 people. ``She told us that Christmas is a
time for giving and what better gift to give.''
   After Ms. Ingram's visit Tuesday, the subject turned to the
senior trip, said Matt Sager, 17, the senior class president.
   Donating money raised for the trip _ the destination had not been
decided _ provoked a ``lot of student discussion,'' Sager said, but
it was approved by a show of hands.
   ``There were one or two students who didn't like the idea, but
nobody spoke against it,'' he said.
   The seniors voted to give Craig all the proceeds from a spaghetti
supper planned to raise funds for the trip, plus other money set
aside for the traditional excursion.
   Principal Gene Logue praised the seniors, noting their action
ignited a flurry of fund-raising ideas.
   ``The school has exploded in the last two days,'' Logue said.
   Junior class president Doug Laatsch, 16, said his class decided
to donate money from a dance scheduled for Friday night. And all
four classes are competing in a ``Kiss The Pig'' contest _ the
teacher, community member and student who collect the most money for
the operation get the privilege of kissing a pig at an upcoming
basketball game.
   Craig's parents, Mike, 35, and Judy, 33, of Altamont, said their
insurer, Prudential Insurance Co., considers the bone marrow
transplant experimental and won't pay for it.
   The Grubaughs say they appreciate the seniors' sacrifice.
   ``I hate to see the students give up their class trip,'' said
Mrs. Grubaugh. ``We would like to see them hold the money out of the
fund until we get closer to the goal.''
   So far, the family has collected $16,000.
   Guidance counselor John Van Alst sent letters to parents seeking
their approval of the senior class' action.
   ``This is the kids' money (for the trip) but we wanted the
parents to be aware of what they had done,'' he said.
   About half of the parents have returned the letters; all favored
the seniors' decision.
   ``We are a poor community,'' Van Alst said, ``and if we pull it
off it will be a miracle. But then we all believe in miracles.''
</TEXT>
