<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FernaldAgreement Bjt   12-02 0791</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fernald Agreement, Bjt,0812</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ohio Announces Fernald Cleanup Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos CS3,4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A historic agreement announced Friday gives
Ohio power to regulate the Energy Department's cleanup of a uranium
processing plant that has pumped 300,000 pounds of radioactive waste
into the environment.
   Ohio Attorney General Anthony Celebrezze Jr. and Sen. John Glenn,
D-Ohio, said the decree, negotiated by federal and state attorneys,
gives the state a court-enforceable order to pressure the department
to clean up the plant at an estimated cost of $1 billion.
   The accord covers the Feed Materials Production Center in
Fernald, which state officials blame for contamination of air and
water at the 1,050-acre site 18 miles north of Cincinnati. The plant
enriches uranium for nuclear power plants and for the government's
nuclear research efforts.
   Jim Alexander, spokesman for the Energy Department's Oak Ridge,
Tenn., operations, which include Fernald, said the agreement is
evidence of intent to clean up the plant. He said it is not intended
as an admission of wrongdoing.
   Joe La Grone, the DOE manager at Oak Ridge, said this week the
government will have spent $355 million by the end of fiscal 1989 on
cleanup and safety at Fernald.
   The plant sits above the Great Miami River aquifer, a water
source for 2 million people. The Energy Department has admitted that
the plant emitted radioactive uranium dust into the atmosphere over
three decades.
   Glenn said he hopes the court decree will prompt Congress to give
high priority to cleanup of 17 Energy Department plants nationwide.
   Stanley Chesley, a lawyer for neighbors who have a $300 million
class-action lawsuit pending against the plant said the settlement
does not compensate victims, give Ohio authority over radioactive
wastes stored at the plant or indicate whether the DOE has committed
the whole $1 billion.
   Chesley said he also is concerned that in exchange for the
agreement, the state agreed not to bring additional civil or
criminal lawsuits against the department and past or present plant
contractors and officials.
   He said his group will proceed with its lawsuit at a Dec. 16
hearing here.
   Marvin Clawson, a neighbor represented in the lawsuit, said the
agreement falls short of what the Energy Department should do.
   ``It mainly addressed the hazardous-waste problem, not the
radioactive waste problem,'' said Clawson, who lives four miles from
the plant. ``They've hardly admitted to anything yet.''
   The 37-year-old plant processes and molds uranium metal ingots
for use elsewhere in the Energy Department's production of nuclear
weapons. There has been no production at the site since union
workers went on strike Oct. 7.
   Energy Department officials have said they expect production to
resume when the strike ends.
   U.S. District Judge S. Arthur Spiegel signed the agreement and
also is presiding over the neighbors' lawsuit.
   The agreement resulted from two years of negotiations prompted by
two lawsuits, filed by the state in 1986 and 1987, against the
Energy Department. The decree requires the department to pay the
state about $1 million for penalties and to reimburse Ohio for
overseeing the cleanup, Celebrezze said.
   He said the agreement requires Fernald's current operator,
Westinghouse Materials Co. of Ohio, to pay $60,000 in penalties for
two releases of radioactive radon gas from concrete silos containing
radium wastes. It also requires National Lead of Ohio Inc., which
operated the plant until the end of 1985, to pay $275,000 for past
environmental problems.
   ``The decree also extends Ohio's jurisdiction over Fernald to all
state and federal hazardous-waste law and regulations,'' Celebrezze
said.
   ``This doesn't take away the federal pre-eminence in things
nuclear,'' Glenn said. ``But it does set a first in what any (state)
attorney general in the United States has been able to work out.''
   The Energy Department is assessing the future of Fernald and
other plants nationwide in a secret study to be completed this month.
   Westinghouse Materials Co. announced Thursday it will lay off 350
of the plant's 1,500 employees soon because of declining demand for
processed uranium. Glenn opposes closing the plant because he thinks
the cleanup would get a higher priority if it remains active.
   Glenn said Fernald's problems date through 35 years of
administrations and predecessors to the Energy Department, including
the Atomic Energy Commission and the Energy Research and Development
Administration.
   Ohio officials on Nov. 22 announced agreement with the DOE on a
$50 million cleanup of hazardous waste at a uranium enrichment plant
near Piketon, Ohio. In that settlement, the department also agreed
to be subject to Ohio environmental regulation. Celebrezze said the
details of the Piketon agreement remain to be incorporated into a
federal court consent decree. The matter of fines to be paid for
pollution vilaations at Piketon also is not yet resolved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
