<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Commerce-Technology     12-02 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commerce-Technology,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ambler Chosen As Commerce Undersecretary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ernest Ambler, the longtime director of the
National Institute of Standards and Technology, was chosen Friday to
be the first Commerce undersecretary for technology.
   Ambler, who plans to retire next year after 35 years of
government service, said he would serve in the new post only through
March in order to give the Bush administration a chance to name its
own choice for the job.
   The job of undersecretary for technology was created by Congress
this fall in a reorganization sought by Commerce Secretary C.
William Verity.
   In announcing Ambler's selection, Verity said he believed the
federal government needed to do more to focus attention on the
important role technological breakthroughs play in keeping America
competitive in global markets.
   ``Today's global market realities demand not only the creation of
new technologies, atwhich America continues to excel, but rapid and
continuous transfer of these technologies to new products,'' Verity
said.
   Verity said Ambler's first role would be to decide which Commerce
Department agencies to include under the umbrella of a new
Technology Administration.
   ``Since I took office 14 months ago, one of the recurring
comments I have heard from business leaders is that they don't know
where to go or whom to talk to in government about technology
advances or technology needs,'' Verity said. ``Legislative approval
means we can for the first time bring together the remarkable
scientific and technological resources of the Commerce Department.''
</TEXT>
