<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Prince-Drugs 2ndLd-Writethru a0702 12-02 0869</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prince-Drugs, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0702,0891</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Princely Couple's Death Raises Questions about `High' Society</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB grafs 8-10 graf pvs, `After dining...family said' with
three grafs to CORRECT name of city to Gmunden, sted Gmuenden, and
CORRECT to Hapsburg, sted Habsburg; picks up 11th: Ever since...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen months ago they wed in a
fairy-tale ceremony at an Alpine castle. On Friday, one of Europe's
aristocratic young couples was buried _ the princess a victim of an
apparent drug overdose, her prince driven to suicide.
   Mourned by 150 noble relatives, Prince Ludwig Rudolf of Hanover,
a 33-year-old great-grandson of Germany's last emperor, and his
26-year-old bride, Isabelle, were laid to rest in a driving frozen
rain in the village of Gruenau, 120 miles west of Vienna.
   Among the mourners at a Mass in the whitewashed village church
were the prince's aunt, Princess Sophie of Greece, sister of Queen
Elizabeth II's husband, the Duke of Edinburgh, and four members of
Austria's deposed House of Hapsburg.
   The ceremony made no mention of how they died. With similar
restraint, none of the noble houses that sent about 40 wreaths to
the funeral signed their family names. At least two wreaths bore a
royal crown.
   The funeral came 14 months after a lavish five-day wedding in the
Alpine castle of Bleiburg in southern Austria, home of the bride,
Countess Isabelle von Thurn.
   Five months later, as the Austrian tabloid Kurier respectfully
phrased it, Isabelle ``made a gift'' of a son, Otto, to her husband.
   On Sunday night, the princely pair again made news. This time, it
was gruesome.
   After dining with an obscure West German pop group and an
unidentified American, Isabelle retired to her bedroom in the
couple's home, the so-called ``Queen's Villa'' in Gmunden, 150 miles
west of the capital.
   Several hours later, the prince found his wife dead on the bed
from what police said was apparently a drug overdose, probably
cocaine. The prince, who was ``in shock,'' drove from the house and
shot himself in a nearby forest of the Almtal valley, his family
said.
   The couple's grisly end has dented popular images of aristocrats
embodying the vanished glory of the still-beloved Hapsburg monarchy,
forced to abdicate in 1918 at the end of World War I.
   Ever since the deaths became known Monday, newspapers in Austria
and West Germany have painted a different picture of what Kurier on
Friday sardonically labeled ``high society.''
   Reporters trying to learn more about the dead couple got little
out of aristocrats at fashionable Vienna nightspots. Few admitted to
knowing the pair, and none discussed the use of what Germans often
call the ``noble drug'' _ cocaine, which is blamed here for a record
number of fatal overdoses this year.
   Such silence reportedly hampers police tracking well-born drug
offenders.
   ``There are barriers we simply can't cross,'' Salzburg narcotics
detective Karl Walder told Kurier.
   Police insisted on anonymity this week when revealing that old
needle marks were found on the arms of the royal couple and used
syringes were confiscated from their home.
   ``I don't want to burn my fingers,'' said one police official.
   A preliminary autopsy on the princess showed she died of heart
and lung edema, or swelling from an abnormal accumulation of fluid,
apparently caused by a cocaine overdose. Asked if more autopsy tests
would be made public, an official at a local state prosecutor's
office voiced relief no trial would be necessary.
   ``Death ends all punishment,'' he noted, demanding anonymity.
   Prince Ludwig Rudolf was no stranger to the courtroom. In 1981,
according to press reports reluctantly confirmed by Munich state
prosecutors, he testified at a drug trial that also involved Rainer
Werner Fassbinder, the West German film director who died after a
cocaine overdose in 1982.
   Asked why he transferred some $20,000 to the account of a
suspected cocaine dealer, the prince reportedly told the Munich
court the money was to pay for a car.
   Last week, state prosecutors in the West German city of Hanover
closed another drug trafficking investigation against the prince for
lack of evidence.
   Word that the investigation was dropped apparently had not
reached the prince when he shot himself, Hanover prosecutor's
spokesman Klaus Ramberger said.
   Newspapers have speculated this may have increased the panic the
prince felt when he found his wife dead at 2:45 a.m. Monday.
   Ludwig Rudolf quickly alerted the Red Cross, telling them in a
telephone call that his wife might have taken cocaine.
   Police later tested the other guests at the villa for drug abuse
and pronounced them clean.
   But the prince reportedly did not wait even for the emergency
doctor to arrive to examine his wife before leaving the villa,
taking a hunting gun.
   According to press reports based on police sources, he did call
his brother in London, Prince Ernst August of Hanover, telling him
of his suicide plans and asking him to take care of his baby son.
   The line to London then went dead. Police alerted to look for
Ludwig Rudolf failed to find him before a forest worker discovered
his body slumped across the steering wheel of his car, with a bullet
wound to the head.
</TEXT>
