<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChildrenSeized     12-02 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children Seized,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Children Seized From Woman Accused Of Trying To Trade Child For
Cocaine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police seized two children from a
courthouse while their mother was inside testifying before a grand
jury about allegations that she tried to sell one of them for
cocaine.
   ``I didn't know what was going on,'' said Rhonda Romero. ``I walk
outside and my kids are gone. They told me I'd sold him for 2 ounces
of cocaine. This is ridiculous.''
   Ms. Romero was testifying before the Nueces County Grand Jury on
Thursday when police took the children, 1 and 2 years old.
   Police did not have a court order to seize the boys, but the
Texas Family Code says a court order is not necessary if there is
``immediate danger to the physical health or safety of the child and
there is no time to obtain a temporary restraining order,'' said
District Attorney Grant Jones.
   Jones said the grand jury is investigating the ``sale or
attempted sale'' of a child.
   Ms. Romero said she is unemployed and could not care for the
children properly, so she was trying to find them decent homes. The
older boy was staying with another couple but that she did not trade
the child for drugs.
   The grand jury was to continue hearing testimony in the case.
   The children will be supervised by the Texas Department of Human
Services until a court hearing within 10 days determines who should
care for them.
