<HEAD>Car Bombing Suspect is Assassinated in Beirut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least one assassin with a silenced
pistol slipped into a guarded hospital room Friday and killed a
Moslem suspected in a fatal car bombing, police reported.
   They identified the dead man as Mahmoud Ahmed, a 25-year-old
Lebanese.
   Authorities arrested him after a car bomb exploded Sept. 28 at a
Syrian army checkpoint on the coastal highway south of Beirut. Five
people were killed and 21 wounded, included five Syrian soldiers.
   Ahmed was hit in the stomach by shrapnel and was undergoing
treatment at the American University Hospital in Moslem west Beirut,
police said. They said two plainclothes Syrian agents had guarded
him the 8th-floor room around the clock.
   ``We do not know how the assassin or assassins managed to slip
into the guarded room and shoot him,'' said a police spokesman who
spoke on condition of anonymity. ``We believe a silencer-equipped
pistol was used.''
   A hospital spokesman confirmed the killing but gave no details.
