<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LeadersSummit     12-02 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Leaders Summit,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conference Of Emerging U.S.-Soviet Leaders Seeks Common Ground</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and American delegates to an Emerging
Leaders Summit heard letters Friday from Mikhail Gorbachev and
President-elect George Bush, who said world peace could be developed
through better understanding.
   ``You are the leaders of tomorrow,'' Bush said in a letter read
during a plenary session that opened the week-long conference.
   The conference has 340 delegates, most of them in their 20s and
30s, from the two nations.
   Gorbachev, originally expected to attend the conference as part
of his visit to the U.S. next week to address the United Nations,
sent a letter that echoed Bush's.
   ``Your forum is a sign of real changes for the better in the
world,'' Gorbachev said. ``It's your mission to advance history, to
write its new pages and chapters. You are to carry the burden and
beauty of insuring conclusively that it will be no longer be written
by the sword and the yoke.''
   Viktor Mironenko, 35, first secretary of the Communist Youth
League, a member of the Supreme Soviet Presidium and head of the
Russian delegation, took up the theme.
   Referring to Philadelphia's role in U.S. history and the writing
of the Constitution, Mironenko said the challenges today's delegates
face are even tougher because they are more complex.
   ``Each generation of humans takes one or more steps toward making
the world free of wars and aggression. We are striving ahead (even
though) our world is far from perfect. But we have to live in this
world together,'' he said.
   Alluding to Gorbachev's current ``glasnost'' reforms, Mironenko
said: ``we have come to the conclusion that it is open-ness not
close-ness that makes society strong.''
   Sixteen delegate commissions will cover major topics affecting
the two world powers _ government and political affairs,
international business and trade, youth work and social service,
domestic and international law, military, media, religion, labor and
management, education, global environment, international finance,
science and technology, medicine and health care.
   Each commission has scheduled seven three-hour sessions during
the week.
   ``We must understand each other better because it will help world
peace,'' said Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., applauding Gorbachev's
efforts to democratize Soviet government. ``It is a very healthy
sign.
   ``As we view democracy in the changing Soviet Union we are more
impressed by the dissents than the agreements.''
   There will be daily updates on each commission's discussions,
which are closed to the public and to reporters. At the end of the
summit next week, delegates will compile ``The Final Appeal,'' a
document outlining strategies for improved relations between the
superpowers.
   Philip Hughes, assistant secretary of commerce in the Reagan
adminstration, told delegates there is world confusion ``on what
Gorbachev represents. Does he want to make the Soviet Union stronger
in the world community or is he really seeking change.
   ``Then there is skepticism. The alienation between the U.S. and
Soviet Union has existed for so long that many Americans are
skeptical whether any new leader can make any change permanent,''
Hughes said.
   American Rabbi Gary Zola, 32, of Cincinnati, said he expected the
religious sessions will touch on ``human rights, freedom of religion
and, of course, Soviet Jews.''
   ``That means bilateral relations, humanitarian issues, regional
conflicts,'' said Sergei Chelnokov.
   Chelnokov is head of the Soviet Committee of Youth Organizations,
which is co-sponsoring the meeting with the American Council of
International Leadership.
   In addition to the formal meetings, the delegates will have
sightseeing, lunches at various educational institutions and dinners
at homes, and on Saturday the Army-Navy football game.
</TEXT>
