<HEAD>China Accuses India of Border Violations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with India's response</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China claimed Friday that Indian planes had
intruded into its air space, but gave no details in a statement.
   India said it was not aware of any intrusions and indicated the
matter would not interfere with Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's plans
to visit Beijing this month, the first trip to China by an Indian
prime minister since 1954.
   China and India fought a brief border war in 1962 and relations
have remained tense. There have been intermittent accusations by
both sides of border violations.
   The Chinese Foreign Ministry statement Friday said, ``Recently
Indian planes have indeed intruded into China's air space. The
Chinese side has made representations to the Indian side.''
   The statement was issued in response to a question by the British
Broadcasting Corp., which said a Chinese source reported border
violations by India.
   A spokesman for the Indian Foreign Ministry in New Delhi said,
``We have checked with the Defense Ministry and are not aware of any
violations. Do not read too much into the matter. Preparations for
the prime minister's visit are ... going very well.''
