<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-Amerasians     12-02 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-Amerasians,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Embassy Says Details Remain Unsolved in Amerasian Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Vietnamese officials discussed
for opening an office to process Amerasians seeking to emigrate to
the United States, but did not reach agreement, a U.S. Embassy
official said Friday.
   Vietnamese government spokeswoman Ho The Lan reported that an
agreement resulted from the meeting Wednesday in Hanoi, but Bangkok
embassy spokesman Ross Petzing said: ``The discussions were useful
and constructive. No final agreement has been reached yet and some
details remain to be worked out.''
   Since a regular emigration program began in 1982, the United
States has taken about 5,000 Amerasians, children fathered by
Americans during the Vietnam War. U.S. forces withdrew from the
conflict in 1973.
   Officials estimate 8,000-12,000 Amerasians remain in Vietnam. The
Vietnamese have said a processing center in Ho Chi Minh City,
formerly Saigon, is needed to expedite their departure.
   Hanoi's official Vietnam News Agency said Foreign Ministry
representative Le Bang and Bruce Beardsley, head of the refugee
office of the U.S. Embassy in Bangkok, discussed the issue in the
Vietnamese capital.
   Its report quoted Mrs. Lan as telling a news conference Thursday
the two sides agreed to reach quick solutions to technical problems,
including air transportation.
   ``At the same time, they agreed to set up an Amerasian center in
Ho Chi Minh City and put it into operation soon,'' she said, without
giving details.
   The United States and Vietnam have no diplomatic relations
because of U.S. opposition to the decade-old Vietnamese occupation
of Cambodia. Hanoi has repeatedly pressed for establishing offices
to deal with Vietnamese-U.S. humanitarian issues.
   ``Vietnam has supplied the U.S. side with a list of Amerasians
and their relatives and urged the U.S. side to simplify the
procedures and quickly take them to the United States in a two-year
period beginning from March 1988,'' Mrs. Lan said.
   She said the two countries will conduct their third joint field
investigation in Vietnam from Dec. 5-15 to account for American
servicmen missing in action, or MIAs.
   The number of joint search teams will be increased from two to
four, she said. A total of 1,757 Americans still are listed as
missing in the Indochina war, which ended in April 1975.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
