<DOCNO> AP881202-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1900EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ContraArms 1stLd-Writethru a0693 12-02 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Arms, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0693,0819</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contra Supporters Argue U.S., Nicaragua Were In De Facto War</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with testimony from Adolfo
Calero, judge continuing hearing until January, picking up 7th graf
pvs, `The judge...; SUBS 10th graf pvs, `The group...', to delete
now-redundant first reference to Oliver North.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six Contra supporters accused of
attacking Nicaragua urged a judge Friday to dismiss their case on
the grounds the United States has been waging a de facto war against
the Sandinistas.
   They asked U.S. District Judge Norman C. Roettger to throw out an
indictment accusing them of violating the U.S. Neutrality Act by
recruiting mercenaries and launching operations against the
Sandinista government in Nicaragua from U.S. soil in 1985.
   ``This is a ludicrous thing,'' said defendant Mario Calero,
brother of top Contra leader Adolfo Calero. ``There has not been a
violation of the Neutrality Act. The executive branch was funding
and directing the war.''
   Adolfo Calero testified Friday that the rebels continued to
receive U.S. aid, such as private contributions funneled through
then-White House aide Oliver North, even during the time that
Congress cut off military funds.
   In testimony reminiscent of what he told the Iran-Contra
investigations, he said North and other government officials never
advised him to cease his activities because of the congressional
action.
   ``It was the opposite,'' said the Contra leader. ``We were told
not to give up, to continue the struggle.''
   After the day's testimony, Roettger continued the pretrial
hearing until Jan. 5 and said he would rule on the dismissal motion
shortly thereafter.
   The Neutrality Act forbids private citizens from launching
U.S.-based military operations against any nation with which the
nation is at peace.
   The defendants won a quick procedural victory when Roettger
brushed aside the U.S. attorney's efforts to delay arguments on the
issue until trial.
   Just before the noon recess, Roettger agreed to take more
testimony, and warned prosecutors that he expected to look broadly
at the war and peace issue.
   At one point, the judge also expressed impatience with the
prosecution's contention that the only purpose of U.S. aid to the
Nicaraguan Contras was to interdict arms to leftist rebels in nearby
El Salvador.
   Referring to President Reagan, the judge said: ``I remember a
badge that said `I'm a Contra too.' It didn't say anything about
interdicting arms.''
   The judge sharply questioned Assistant U.S. Attorney Eric
Dubelier on whether the government contends it was at peace with
Libya when U.S. Navy jets attacked Tripoli in 1986.
   Dubelier conceded the U.S. was not at peace with Libya in that
case, but asked in return, ``Where do you draw the line?''
   If the defense's line of reasoning was accepted, Dubelier said,
``then the Neutrality Act could not be used now against anyone
preparing to invade the Soviet Union.''
   The group was indicted in June after charges of Reagan
administration foot-dragging. Opponents of aid to the Contras
accused former Attorney General Edwin Meese III of stalling the case
because it threatened to uncover North's involvement.
   The indictment accused the Contra supporters of recruiting and
training mercenaries to fight with Contras, supplying them with
equipment, leading them on expeditions, including one aimed at
blowing up a Nicaraguan bridge, and violating firearms laws.
   The seven original defendants were Thomas Posey, head of the
Alabama-based Civilian Materiel Assistance group; Mario Calero, a
former supply manager for the rebels; Joe Adams, Adolfo's former
bodyguard; Jack Terrell, a former mercenary who turned against the
effort and went to authorities; Maco Stewart, a wealthy former Texas
businessman and state official who now lives in France; Jose Coutin,
a Civilian Materiel Assistance liaison in Florida; and Alex
Martinez, a conservative Cuban-American stockbroker.
   Stewart allegedly financed some of the activities.
   Some of the defendants, including Terrell and Posey, have
produced documents showing the FBI and other agencies were aware of
their activities in aiding the Contras, and have said knowledge of
their activities went all the way to the White House.
   But Adams decided to plead guilty and received a sentence of a
$50 fine and one day of probation. The other six defendants continue
to fight the charges.
   Terrell, who faces a possible 33-year jail sentence, was accused
of buying a Manlicher .308-caliber rifle to be used as a sniper
weapon in Nicaragua.
   Coutin faces 13 years if convicted because he allegedly gave his
passport to a mercenary, while the rest face up to eight years on
two Neutrality Act violations.
   A second Neutrality Act indictment returned by the same grand
jury accuses six more men of running a training camp for the
Contras, as well as supplying them with weapons that included a 20mm
cannon. That case is being heard by a different judge.
</TEXT>
