<1ST_LINE>r i AM-EEC-Summit 1stLd-Writethru a0706 12-02 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EEC-Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0706,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Priest Extradition Dispute Overshadows European Summit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 4th `Soon after...' to UPDATE with
later session, Thatcher, Dutch quotes; picks up 5th pvs `The
two-day...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RHODES, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
criticized Belgium's premier Friday for refusing to extradite a
pro-IRA priest, a dispute that overshadowed a European Economic
Community summit meeting.
   In the some of the angriest exchanges reported between leaders in
the trade bloc, Mrs. Thatcher told Premier Wilfried Martens of
Belgium that she was ``mystified and deeply wounded'' by his
government's refusal to extradite Patrick Ryan.
   British police suspect the Roman Catholic priest of involvement
in a series of Irish Republican Army bombings and other terrorist
offenses.
   Soon after the angry meeting in Mrs. Thatcher's hotel suite, she
and Martens sat side-by-side as the leaders of the 12-nation
community reviewed their ambitious program to dismantle all trade
barriers and create by 1992 a single market of 322 million people.
   Mrs. Thatcher, who has been criticized for being wary of the
trade agreement, argued during the afternoon meeting that some
border restrictions must remain in place to control terrorism, drug
dealing and arms smuggling, officials said.
   ``Insular thinking ... is a reality,'' Dutch Prime Minister Ruud
Lubbers said of Mrs. Thatcher. ``But I have never seen her more
relaxed. She sees this summit ... as the start of a debate,'' he
told reporters after the three-and-a-half hour session.
   The two-day meeting among the often-quarrelsome European leaders,
which began Friday, had been expected to produce few problems. Tough
decisions on closer union, including monetary cooperation and a
single tax system, are due at the next six-monthly summit in Spain.
   Central to the informal agenda was a draft statement aimed at
reassuring the United States and Japan that the community will not
shut out their trade in 1992.
   ``Europe will not close in on itself ... will not be a Fortress
Europe, but a partnership,'' the draft said.
   The leaders met in the 14th century Knights of St. John castle on
the island. A frigate patrolled offshore and commandos armed with
automatic weapons patrolled the beachfront.
   In the early hours Friday, four bombs exploded in Athens, 270
miles west of the meeting site, including one at an EEC building.
Police said no one was injured.
   The left-wing Revolutionary Popular Struggle, which has claimed
responsibility for more than 500 previous attacks in the past 15
years, said in a message to Greek newspapers that it planted the
devices.
   The priest was arrested in Belgium last summer. Last week,
Martens' government turned down the British extradition request and
sent him to Ireland. Ireland says it is considering the request,
though authorities no longer know where he is.
   Martens said after meeting Mrs. Thatcher that he told her the
extradition request was rejected because it was legally flawed.
   ``It was not a political decision,'' Martens said.
   A British spokesman said Mrs. Thatcher told Martens she was
``mystified and deeply wounded and (spoke) of confidence being
undermined.''
</TEXT>
