<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Philippines-CompanyPlea     12-02 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Company Plea,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Pleads Guilty To Assisting In Filing False Tax Return</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California company pleaded guilty Friday to
assisting in the filing of a false tax return by a businessman tied
to corruption in the Philippines under former President Ferdinand
Marcos.
   Ocean Applied Research Corp. of San Diego entered the plea in
U.S. District Court in Alexandria, Va., the Justice Department said.
   The company, which was fined $10,000 and paid $38,258 to settle
civil claims, aided Raymond M. Moreno in preparing and filing the
false tax return for Moreno's company, Amworld Inc., according to
the government.
   Moreno, who was closely associated with former Philippines Gen.
Fabian C. Ver, chief of the armed forces under Marcos, pleaded
guilty on Dec. 14, 1987, in an alleged $6.8 million kickback scheme
involving a Philippine military communications system.
   A U.S. arrest warrant was issued some time ago for Ver and still
is outstanding, a Justice Department official, Theodore Greenburg,
said in an interview.
   At the time Moreno pleaded guilty, the Justice Department said
that after Moreno's companies won three contracts totaling $28
million in 1983 to modernize the Philippine military communications
system, seven American firms were subcontractors to Moreno and paid
him $6.8 million in kickbacks. The modernization effort took place
under the Pentagon's foreign military program.
   Court papers filed in the OAR case say that the firm was a
subcontractor to Amworld in the Philippines communications system
modernization program. Moreno, said the court papers, awarded a
subcontract to OAR in 1983 when the company agreed to pay a kickback
which eventually totaled $658,093 to Moreno through a Hong Kong
shell company, Geomanagement Ltd., also owned by Moreno.
   OAR provided Amworld with an invoice reflecting twice the actual
sales price of goods. Moreno used the inflated invoice furnished by
OAR to fraudulently boost Amworld's business expenses on its 1983
corporate income tax return, the Justice Department papers said.
</TEXT>
