<2ND_LINE>AM-Arson Town,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arson Suspect Pleads Innocent; Lawyer Says Police Have `Wrong Man'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID TIRRELL-WYSOCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANCASTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former volunteer firefighter accused of
setting 14 blazes in a town that was terrorized by arson for several
months pleaded innocent Friday as his lawyer said authorities have
``the wrong man.''
   Lance Lalumiere, 23, stood silent during a brief hearing in the
Coos County Courthouse as his lawyer entered innocent pleas to 14
counts of arson and two of attempted arson.
   The series of 26 fires in and near Jefferson, a town of 850 near
here, began in May and continued through early October. No one was
killed, though there were close calls.
   Lalumiere was arrested Oct. 12 and has been held without bail
since them. He was first charged with setting a fire in his
brother's cabin in August, and then was later charged with 15 other
arsons or arson attempts.
   The attorney general's office has said that Lalumiere admitted
setting 16 fires. Court documents show that authorities found a
hand-drawn map of several arson sites in Lalumiere's trailer and a
propane-type torch in a car he owned.
   But after Friday's hearing, his lawyer, James Quay, said, ``The
police have arrested the wrong man.''
   ``Lance has appeared in court today and affirmed his innocence as
to each and every one of these charges,'' Quay said. ``We deny all
of the assertions contained in each of these charges.''
   In addition, he said, many townspeople quoted in news reports
since the arrest said Lalumiere couldn't have set the fires.
   Another man has been charged in connection with one of the 26
fires, and authorities say the other nine are still under
investigation.
</TEXT>
