<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PaloVerde     12-02 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Palo Verde,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Operators Won't Contest $250,000 in Penalties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINTERSBURG, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission on
Friday fined operators of the Palo Verde nuclear power plant
$250,000 for violations that included one worker's exposure to
radiation.
   The Arizona Nuclear Power Project, which operates the plant for a
consortium of utilities in Arizona, California, New Mexico and
Texas, said it would not contest the penalties by the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission.
   ``The violations resulted from problems we identified and
reported to the NRC. We take the infractions very seriously,'' said
Don Karner, ANPP executive vice president.
   The NRC's regional office in Walnut Creek, Calif., said the
violations included a worker exceeding his radiation exposure limit,
part of a reactor unit's air conditioning system being rendered
inoperable inadvertently ``and a radiation oversight committee not
fulfilling its reponsibilities.''
   Palo Verde operators recently announced they plan to spend
millions of dollars improving the plant, including hiring dozens of
additional engineers to act as troubleshooters, revamping the duties
of work crews and retaining consultants.
   Palo Verde, a three-reactor plant, is located about 50 miles west
of downtown Phoenix.
   The NRC previously has imposed several penalties against Palo
Verde, including $50,000 for deficiencies with a radiation sampling
system, $100,000 in May 1986 for security deficiencies and $100,000
in April for engineering and and operations problems.
   Other problems have included numerous unplanned shutdowns this
year for Palo Verde's Unit 1, which operated at 52.1 percent of
capacity this year. Units 2 and 3 operated at 56.3 percent and 90.5
percent, respectively.
</TEXT>
