<2ND_LINE>AM-Garbage House Body,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Body May Have Been In Garbage-Filled House For Two Weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 59-year-old man whose emaciated body was
found in a house filled with 5-foot piles of beer cans, excrement
and other debris died of dehydration, officials said Friday.
   The body of Robert Jorgensen was found Thursday. Health officials
said it may have been there at least two weeks.
   Jorgensen, who was 5-foot-7, weighed about 90 pounds when he
died. The cause of death was determined after an autopsy, said James
Essling, chief investigator for the Ramsey County medical examiner's
office.
   Police were called to the home Thursday after neighbors noticed
Jorgensen's prolonged absence.
   ``We had to clear a path through the beer cans to get the body
out,'' said police Lt. Russell Bovee. ``The house was
uninhabitable.''
   Inside, officers found 5-foot piles of cans and feces, rotting
furniture, grime-covered walls and cobweb-laced ceilings.
   The fully clothed victim was found lying on the floor inside the
doorway to a bedroom, Bovee said.
   Neighbors described Jorgensen as a pipe-smoking loner with a
fondness for beer.
   William Haller, who lives on the same street, said he was aware
of the squalid conditions inside the house.
   ``He invited me over a couple of times,'' he said. ``It was a
dump. The smell just about knocked me out.''
   Jorgensen worked as a dining room assistant at the St. Paul
Athletic Club from 1973 until he was fired last spring, said Alan
Guertin, the club's director of food and beverages.
   Jorgensen began to disappear from work for days and weeks at a
time, Guertin said, and he was replaced after a three-week
disappearance last spring.
</TEXT>
