<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chilly Weather In California And Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Record cold hit central California on Friday and unseasonably
cold air headed toward the Southeast, and there was relatively
little precipitation anywhere.
   The overnight low at Bakersfield, Calif., dipped to a record 33
degrees Friday, one degree colder than the city's previous record,
set in 1957.
   Some freezing temperatures were reported near Bakersfield in
outlying sections of the southern valley citrus district.
   Unseasonably low temperatures were forecast during the night in
the Southeast. Warnings for frost and freezing temperatures were
posted over inland southern Alabama, the northern section of the
Florida Panhandle and the coast of South Carolina.
   Snow showers were scattered over northeastern New York state.
Rain along the northern Pacific Coast changed to snow over
northwestern Montana.
   There were no reports of measurable snowfall or heavy rainfall
during the 6 hours up to 1 p.m. EST, the National Weather Service
said.
   Gale warnings were posted over lakes Erie, Huron and Ontario.
Wind gusted to 55 mph at Buffalo, N.Y., during the morning.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 2
degrees above zero at Jackson, Wyo., to 80 at Palm Springs, Calif.
Friday morning's official low temperature was 9 degrees below zero
at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Saturday, rain mixed with snow was forecast over northern
Lower Michigan, with high wind over much of the upper Mississippi
Valley.
   High in the 30s and 40s were predicted from New England across
the Great Lakes, the upper Mississippi Valley, the northern Plains
and the Rockies; in the 40s and low 50s along the northern half of
the Pacific Coast; near 70 over southern Florida, central through
southern Texas, and from the desert Southwest across the southern
coast of California; and generally in the 50s and 60s over the
remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
