<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 2125EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IranAir-Report     12-02 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran Air-Report,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Iranian Airliner Had Only 40 Seconds to React</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iranian airliner only had 40 seconds to react
to a warning before a U.S. warship shot it down on July 3, killing
all 290 people aboard, a U.N. aviation agency report was quoted as
saying on Friday.
   The report prepared by the International Civil Aviation
Organization also confirms the U.S. claim that several warnings were
given to the A-300 Airbus before it was shot down in the Persian
Gulf by the USS Vincennes, Canadian Press said.
   The report also says, however, that only a warning from another
American ship in the area, the USS Sides, was coded specifically for
Iran Air Flight 655, CP said.
   That warning came 40 seconds before the jet was destroyed by
surface-to-air missiles, CP quoted the report as saying.
   A warning coded for the civilian aircraft ``could have been
immediately recognizable to the flight crew but was given only in
the final challenge,'' the report said, according to CP. Other
warnings were sent on general military and civilian emergency radio
frequencies.
   Cmdr. Dave Thomas, a Defense Department spokesman in Washington,
said the Pentagon had not received the report and would have no
comment.
   Edmund Stohr, a U.S. representative at the aviation organization,
refused comment Friday but said in an interview Thursday the United
States considers the report fair.
   Airport officials in Iran were unaware a skirmish between the
Vincennes and Iranian gunboats in the gulf just before the airliner
left Bandar Abbas for a flight across the waterway, said the report,
which is to be presented to the agency's governing council Monday.
   ``No `red alert' status was in effect and the air traffic control
units in Tehran and Bandar Abbas were unaware of any activities at
sea,'' the report was quoted as saying.
   A Pentagon report blamed the downing of the airliner on human
error by the crew of the Vincennes, which mistook the commercial jet
for an Iranian F-14 fighter.
   According to the Pentagon report, the plane was warned 12 times
to change its course away from the battle zone.
   The International Civil Aviation Organization's report says the
sophisticated Aegis radar system on the Vincennes ``recorded a
flight profile consistent with a normal climb profile of an Airbus
A-300,'' CP said. The report says the plane was climbing normally
from Bandar Abbas airport and was well within the ``lateral''
boundaries of the flight corridor across the gulf.
   U.S. Navy investigators said September the Iranian aircraft had
been climbing until it was shot down.
   The International Civil Aviation Organization's report, prepared
at the request of a special meeting in July of the 33-nation ICAO
council, is highly technical and does not fix blame. It has been
widely circulated at the agency's Montreal headquarters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881202-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 2128EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissingBooks     12-02 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missing Books,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Author Pleads `No Contest' in Stolen Library Book Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN LUIS OBISPO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A novelist and Oscar nominee who
was charged with stealing thousands of books from more than 70
libraries pleaded no contest Friday to possessing stolen property.
   Gustav Jerry Hasford, who co-wrote the screenplay for the 1987
screenplay ``Full Metal Jacket,'' entered the plea in a bargain with
prosecutors, who dropped two criminal counts of grand theft.
   The plea was accepted by San Luis Obispo County Superior Court
Judge Harry Woolpert. Deputy District Attorney Terry
Estrada-Mullaney has recommended that Hasford serve six months in
jail.
   Hasford's defense attorney, Orlan Donley, did not immediately
return a telephone call to his office seeking comment.
   As part of the plea bargain, Hasford also was ordered to pay
restitution on all of the criminal counts. Sentencing was set for
Jan. 4.
   Hasford pleaded to possession of about 2,000 books, valued at
about $20,000, taken from public libraries in Los Angeles; Santa
Monica; Sacramento; St. Louis; Longview, Wash.; London and the city,
county and university libraries in the central California coastal
community of San Luis Obispo.
   The books were primarily Civil War research volumes, the
prosecutor said.
   The screenplay for the film ``Full Metal Jacket,'' which Hasford
co-wrote with director Stanley Kubrick and Michael Herr, was drawn
largely from Hasford's Vietnam War novel, ``The Short-Timers.''
   Although nominated for an Academy Award, the best screenplay
Oscar for 1987 was given to the authors of ``The Last Emperor.''
   The investigation began on March 17 when police at California
Polytechnic State University in San Luis Obispo served a search
warrant at a storage locker rented by Hasford. They were searching
for 87 overdue books that Hasford had checked out on his Cal Poly
library card.
   Among the estimated 10,000 books found in Hasford's possession
were at least 2,000 allegedly stolen from 77 libraries, Ms.
Estrada-Mullaney said. ``We had suspicions about some of the other
books, but we could only prove the 2,000,'' she said.
   Books found in the locker appeared to be from a city library in
Perth, Australia; Purdue University; the Foxburg Free Library in
Pennsylvania; the Coco Beach, Fla., public library and the Evanston,
Ill., Historical Society.
   Investigators also learned that a book theft warrant for Hasford
had been outstanding in Sacramento County for three years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
