<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FBI-Hispanics 1stLd-Writethru a0754 12-02 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FBI-Hispanics, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0754,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Finds FBI Agents Tried To Retailiate Against Hispanic
Agent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `In his ..., to clarify that ruling said
subpoena was not justified; SUBS last graf with 9 grafs to ADD
further comment from judge's ruling, background, response from
agent's lawyer.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Friday accused FBI agents
of misusing a federal grand jury subpoena to retaliate against a
Hispanic agent who filed a successful discrimination lawsuit against
the bureau.
   In a 17-page memorandum, U.S. District Judge Lucius Bunton ruled
that FBI agents requested a grand jury subpoena during an internal
investigation of agent Bernardo Perez after he and other Hispanic
agents sued the bureau. There was no legitimite purpose for the
subpoena, he said.
   The class-action lawsuit filed in January 1987 contended that the
FBI promoted Hispanic agents too slowly, assigned them
less-desirable jobs and gave them little recognition for their
successes. Bunton ruled in favor of the Hispanic agents in
September; damages have not been determined.
   In his 17-page opinion Friday, the judge said a subpoena issued
in February 1987, three weeks after the lawsuit was filed, was
requested without justification to gather telephone records on Perez.
   The allegation about the subpoena was brought up in August during
the trial on the lawsuit, but Bunton postponed consideration of the
issue because attorneys for the FBI said they were not prepared to
respond to it.
   When a hearing on the issue was held last month, the FBI denied
that the subpoena was requested in retaliation for the lawsuit.
   But in his ruling Friday, Bunton said the FBI did not state a
``legitimate, non-retaliatory reason for securing the subpoena ...
and that demonstrates that the securing of the grand jury subpoena
was not legitimate.''
   ``To deny that there was not a close causal relationship between
the grand jury subpoena and the filing of the Title VII
(discrimination) complaint is to fly in the face of reason,'' Bunton
concluded.
   Perez's attorney, Antonio Silva, said Bunton's ruling was ``a
significant finding in that it details retaliation against Mr.
Perez.''
   Tom McPoyle of the FBI's headquarters in Washington said Friday
that he couldn't comment on the judge's ruling ``because of the
ongoing litigation.''
   According to testimony at the hearing last month, FBI officials
began investigating Perez in 1986, after he filed an internal
discrimination complaint. The investigation concerned statements
Perez had made at the espionage trial of a former fellow agent,
Richard Miller.
   Perez had testified that while he was second-in-command of the
Los Angeles FBI office, he recommended that his boss, Richard
Bretzing, fire Miller for incompetence. Bretzing denied that Perez
ever made that recommendation.
   Miller was not fired at the time, and he was eventually convicted
of passing secrets to the Soviets.
   An FBI agent in Washington, Gary Hart, concluded that there was
no evidence to bring criminal perjury charges against Perez, but he
continued an administrative investigation into the agent.
   In February 1987, Hart asked a federal prosecutor in Alexandria,
Va., to secure a subpoena of telephone records related to Perez.
   Hart said he needed the subpoena to determine whether Perez was
telling the truth when he told Hart he had tried to call him from a
pay phone in Virginia while en route to Washington to meet with him
to discuss the Miller case.
   But thejudge ruled Friday that since the criminal investigation
was over at that point, the request for the subpoena was unjustified.
</TEXT>
