<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WildernessScouts     12-02 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wilderness Scouts,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wilderness Scouts Decline To End Flap By Joining Boy Or Girl Scouts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLAIRSVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite the threat of a lawsuit,
Georgia's Wilderness Scouts have decided to remain autonomous rather
than affiliate with the national Boy Scouts and Girl Scouts.
   The directors of the Wilderness Scouts of America Inc. voted
unanimously Thursday to keep both their name and mission, said
Harold Cornwell, founder of the organization for underprivileged
youngsters.
   The Boy Scouts of America had threatened to sue the Wilderness
Scouts over their use of the word ``scout,'' which the Boy Scouts
claim the rights to.
   But on Monday, Boy Scout officials offered to charter the
Wilderness Scouts as an affiliate of the national organization.
Under the plan, female Wilderness Scouts would have become Girl
Scouts and male Wilderness Scouts would become Boy Scouts.
   Cornwell said his 45-member group decided to remain separate, in
part because of a child molestation case involving one of his
scouts. The stepfather of the scout was sentenced Thursday to 20
years plus fines for aggravated sodomy.
   ``We were instrumental in bringing this case forward,'' Cornwell
said. ``We noticed he was distraught and crying in the meetings.
   ``That little boy would never have been able to join the Boy
Scouts,'' Cornwell said. ``He didn't even have a bed; he slept on
the floor. Who would have paid his dues? Some of our kids don't even
have a toothbrush. That's Third World poverty as far as I'm
concerned.''
   Cornwell said his group's volunteer attorney, who specializes in
patent and copyright law, ``says keep on with our mission.''
   Wayne Brock, executive director of the Boy Scouts' Northeast
Georgia Council, said Boy Scout officials had hoped the dispute
would be settled by chartering Cornwell's scouts. He said further
action will have to be determined by national Boy Scout officials.
   ``We're not opposed to their activities,'' Brock said. ``The only
issue is the use of the word `scout.'''
   Cornwell, a disabled Vietnam veteran, founded the group five
years ago to help children with backgrounds similar to his own. He
was raised in a one-parent home after his father was murdered, and
he could not afford a Boy Scout uniform or badges as a youth.
   Wilderness Scouts have no dues, uniforms or badges, but are
active in conservation and service in the community.
</TEXT>
