<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0722,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Powell Expects No-Surprises Summit Lunch</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th graf pvs, bgng: ``... And I ...''
and ADDS 1 graf to UPDATE with Soviet comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's national security adviser
said Friday that U.S. officials will advance no new proposals and
don't expect any surprises from Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev
at the superpower meeting next week on Governors Island, N.Y.
   Briefing reporters on the visit that Reagan, Gorbachev and
President-elect George Bush will have on Wednesday, Lt. Gen. Colin
D. Powell said Reagan looks forward to ``one final session with the
general secretary to note the stable relationship that exists now,
the improving relationship, and allow the vice president to continue
to build on that relationship.''
   He said the U.S. contingent is ready for, but he doesn't expect,
any repetition of Gorbachev's pattern of surprise at the hurried
summit in Reykjavik, Iceland, two years ago. It was there that the
Soviet leader caught the Americans off guard with sweeping proposals
that included the virtual elimination of strategic nuclear arsenals.
   Powell applauded the recent Soviet decision to stop jamming
broadcasts of the Voice of America and other Western programs, and
he said that U.S. officials were heartened by the Kremlin's decision
to release scores of refuseniks. But he said the United States still
wants to see the Soviet ``institutionalize'' human rights reforms.
   The three-star Army officer, who soon will be promoted to the
rank of general and will return to active duty with command
responsibility for all troops stationed in this country, was asked
what U.S. officials would do if Gorbachev sprang a surprise
reminiscent of Reykjavik.
   ``I don't know that we have to ensure against a surprise,'' he
replied. But Powell also said that ``We have seen them try to turn a
flank from time to time.''
   `` ... And I think we would be prepared to deal with any surprise
that they might come up with, take it under advisement, without
feeling that we're under any pressure during a ... two-and-a-half
lunch period, to necessarily respond in a substantive way to
something that had not been anticipated,'' he said.
   Deputy Soviet Foreign Minister Vladimir Petrovsky told a press
briefing in Moscow on Friday that Afghanistan, Central America and
the Middle East are among the items Gorbachev will discuss with
Reagan and Bush.
   Petrovsky said Gorbachev's speech next week at the United Nations
will detail ``the Soviet leadership's views on major issues of world
development.''
   U.S. officials were widely criticized in the wake of the summit
in Iceland, which collapsed when Reagan and Gorbachev disagreed over
the Soviet leader's demand that the U.S. president substantially
downgrade Reagan's Star Wars missile-defense program.
   Powell said that U.S. officials do not know why Gorbachev is
traveling on to Cuba after leaving this country.
   ``I really would hope that he would recognize that until
something is done with respect to the problem presented to us by
Cuba and Nicaragua, we will always have an irritant in our
relationship,'' the national security adviser said. `` ... We cannot
go as far as we would like to go with respect to the solution of
regional problems.''
   Petrovsky said all the meetings on Gorbachev's trip _ which
includes visits with Fidel Castro in Cuba and with Prime Minister
Minister Margaret Thatcher in London _ were related.
</TEXT>
