<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti 1stLd-Writethru a0755 12-02 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0755,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Ouster Army Officer was Poisoned</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout with police saying Paul was poisoned, NO PICKUP</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ A powerful army officer who had been
indicted in the United States on drug-smuggling charges was killed
earlier this month by poison, police said Friday.
   The ex-wife of Col. Jean-Claude Paul earlier said he suffered a
heart attack at his home on Nov. 6.
   Paul was indicted by a federal court in Miami earlier this year
on charges of drug smuggling. Haitian ruler Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril
forced him to give up his command of the powerful Dessalines
Barracks in October and to retire.
   He died moments after eating pumpkin soup, launching a wave of
speculation he had been murdered.
   Port-au-Prince Police Chief Col. Georges Valcin said Friday night
that Paul died after ``absorbing a toxic substance'' which he did
not identify.
   ``There was nothing in the leftover soup,'' he told The
Associated Press in a telephone interview. ``But be careful: it
could have been in the plate, which was washed immediately
afterwards.''
   Valcin said a sample of Paul's intestinal tract was analyzed at
Vidal Hospital in Paris. He said the chemical substance that was
found is under study.
   Police said nothing about who might have killed Paul or why.
   Paul's family and a medical source insisted immediately after his
death that he had been poisoned.
   However, his ex-wife, Mireille Delinois, said he died of a heart
attack.
   She was arrested the day after Paul's death, but authorities
released her Nov. 26 after a judge ruled her detention was illegal
because no charge was filed.
   Meanwhile, a Haitian official said Friday that he hopes the
United States will not ``make a political affair'' of last month's
arrest of a former-high ranking Haitian officer on drug charges.
   Retired Col. Gary Leon, former general secretary of the Haitian
Army High Command, was arrested on Nov. 18 in New York in possession
of about $200,000 worth of pure cocaine, the Drug Enforcement
Administration said.
   ``The Haitian government expects that justice will be done
according to the American laws in force with a sense of equity and
without any attempt to make a political affair of the case,''
Bernard Degraff, the government information director, said Friday.
   Leon was forced into retirement after rank-and-file soldiers
ousted former ruler Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy in a coup Sept. 17 and
installed Avril.
