<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HighwayKillings 2ndLd-Writethru a0750 12-02 0802</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Highway Killings, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0750,0824</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Search Near Highways After Fifth Body Found</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Seattle police looking for
possible links to Green River slayings, quotes, minor editing
throughout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least one of the five women whose
skeletons have been found along highways in southeastern
Massachusetts since July may have been involved with drugs or
prostitution in this port city, authorities said Friday.
   ``They're all murder victims. No doubt about it,'' said Bristol
County District Attorney Ronald A. Pina.
   Authorities suspect a serial killer may be responsible because
the skeletal remains were found in a six- to eight-mile radius, in
dense woods within 25 feet of Interstate 195 and Route 140, and all
are believed to be women.
   A Seattle detective spoke with New Bedford authorities by
telephone on Friday to determine if there are any links between the
Massachusetts slayings and the so-called ``Green River killer''
blamed for 48 deaths in Washington prior to 1984.
   The Green River killer, so called because many of the victims'
bodies were found near the Seattle-area river, preyed mostly on
prostitutes or transients.
   Bob Evans, commander of the Green River Task Force in Seattle,
said there was no evidence to link the cases, and that it was
routine for the task force to exchange information with other
jurisdictions investigating serial killings.
   Another body was discovered Friday in Dennis, about 50 miles east
of New Bedford on Cape Cod, but Bristol County officials said they
had no idea if it could be connected to the five bodies found in the
New Bedford area.
   The body, that of a 37-year-old man, was found next to a syringe
and needle.
   Investigators had to suspend a search of the highway area because
the trained dogs they were using were distracted by television
camera crews, Pina said.
   A woman whose skeleton was found Tuesday had been reported
missing in the summer and had been dead at least three months, Pina
said. He said her name was being withheld until relatives could be
notified.
   Three of the missing women were reported last seen in the Weld
Square area, known by police as a center for local drug trading and
prostitution in this fishing port of about 98,000 people about 50
miles south of Boston.
   ``Some of the missing people that possibly are going to be
identified were in the community at some point, in the drug
community or prostitution community,'' Pina said at a news
conference.
   ``I don't have a doubt that they are all related in one way or
another, as to the commonality of how they died, where they died,
the condition in which we found them and the locations in which we
found them,'' Pina said.
   Investigators have ``loose suspects in the case, including men
who had used prostitutes in New Bedford.
   ``We have some people we are looking at very seriously ... the
question is, who knew all these people,'' he said.
   Pina said one victim was strangled. The cause of death in some of
the others had been determined but he would not disclose those
results.
   The remains of all five women are be sent to the FBI for further
examination to more accurately determine the cause of death and
learn other details.
   Pina spokesman Thomas Gibney said police used searchlights
Thursday night but found no evidence to help the investigation. They
resumed searching Friday morning.
   ``We're hoping we found the last of them and we just have to put
some of the pieces together,'' Gibney said.
   He said investigators believe the fifth victim was a woman
because of the style of the clothing found, dungarees and a light
shirt. He said the body was severely decomposed and may have been
there a year.
   All of the bodies were so badly decomposed that none could be
identified as female on sight, Gibney said.
   The first three were spotted by motorists who pulled over on the
shoulders of the highways, authorities said.
   State police and the district attorney's office intensified their
investigation after the third body was discovered Nov. 8 off a ramp
from Interstate 195 in Dartmouth, not far from where the second body
was found July 30.
   A German shepherd owned by Connecticut State Police joined
Massachusetts State Police dogs in the search Tuesday and found the
fourth body near the same ramp. The ramp is about two miles west of
the Route 140 exit on the interstate.
   The dog turned up the fifth body less than three miles south of
where the first body was discovered July 3.
   Pina has said the five bodies might be linked to the deaths of
two suspected prostitutes from Providence, R.I., whose bodies were
found last spring near two interstate highways.
</TEXT>
