<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     12-02 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices soared to a record close on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange Saturday as the market expressed relief from the
threat of a interest rate hike, dealers said.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 133.25
points, or 0.45 percent, to close Saturday's half-day session at
29,665.50, its highest closing ever.
   The main economic barometer opened the week's trading with a
major setback of 380.27 points Monday, but soared in later trading
days to close 301.91 points, or 1.02 percent, above last week's
finish.
   ``Players were somewhat cautious until the release of U.S.
unemployment rate yesterday (Friday), and that seemed to have
prevented the upsurge of share prices even though the market
sentiment is still quite bullish,'' said a dealer at Nikko
Securities Co.
   He said Saturday's gain reflects the relief the market felt from
worry that the U.S. Federal Reserve Board may raise interest rates
to calm the heated economy and fear of inflation.
   ``But with the slight increase in the jobless rate, the anxiety
appeared to have been eased for the time being,'' he said.
   The U.S. Labor Department released a report Friday showing the
American jobless rate for November increased to 5.4 percent from
October's 5.3 percent.
   Volume on the first section of the exchange, where most major
shares are listed, was estimated at 600 million shares. The previous
Nikkei high was reached Wednesday when the index closed at 29,578.90
points.
   The foreign exchange market is closed on Saturdays.
</TEXT>
