<2ND_LINE>AM-LILCO-Shoreham, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0763,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LILCO Board Meets On Shoreham Fate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 5th, `The LILCO ..., with LILCO claiming
right to operate at higher power level; picks up 6th graf: `In
Albany, ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long Island Lighting Co.'s board of
directors said Friday it would consider a proposed agreement to sell
and close the Shoreham nuclear plant despite the Legislature's
failure to approve the deal.
   But the board reaffirmed that it would not renegotiate the
agreement and would ``vigorously'' continue to pursue a full-power
license from the Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
   The Legislature failed to meet a Thursday deadline on the
agreement, which calls for the state to buy the $5.3 billion plant
from LILCO for $1, then close it.
   In return, the utility would be granted yearly rate increases of
roughly 5 percent for the next 10 years. Legislators opposing the
settlement said it placed an unfair burden on ratepayers.
   The LILCO board said Friday that if the settlement is approved
before the NRC grants a 25 percent or full-power operating license,
the utility would stick to the agreement unless ``the passage of
time has materially disadvantaged LILCO's shareholders or
customers.''
   The utility said that because the Legislature missed the
deadline, it would ignore the part of the agreement restricting it
from operating the Shoreham plant above 5 percent power, if the NRC
authorizes higher operation.
   In Albany, Gov. Mario Cuomo said LILCO officials had exercised
every option open to them.
   ``What did they give the state and the Legislature? Nothing,''
Cuomo said. ``If I were their attorney, I would be very proud of
what I've done here today and I'd be saying to them, `Look, I got
you everything.' ''
   William J. Catacosinos, LILCO chairman and chief executive
officer, said the board was disappointed by the Legislature's
inaction.
   ``We believe it is important to end the controversy surrounding
Shoreham so that LILCO and state and local officials can work
together to resolve the energy shortages on Long Island,''
Catacosinos said.
   Legislators maintain that a settlement could still be approved
within the next few weeks.
   Cuomo said his administration would continue to oppose the NRC
licensing.
   The Shoreham plant was completed in 1985, a decade late and at
seven times the original estimated cost. It has been prevented from
operating at full power because the state and Suffolk county refuse
to join in emergency evacuation planning.
   The plant, located on the northshore of Long Island about 90
miles from New York City, is now licensed to run at up to 5 percent
of full power.
</TEXT>
