<2ND_LINE>AM-Interstate Shootings,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Freed Mental Patient Arrested in Two-State Shooting Spree</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fugitive mental patient sought in three New
Mexico killings demanded to see actor Michael Landon before fatally
shooting two Universal City movie studio guards, authorities said
Friday.
   Nathan Nick Trupp, 42, wounded in a shootout with deputies
Thursday near Universal City studios, told paramedics that God had
ordered him to kill someone.
   He had been freed from a psychiatric hospital by a court ruling
11 months ago, officials said Friday.
   ``Prior to the shooting, the suspect went on the Universal
Studios tour,'' said Sgt. Ernie Roop, a Los Angeles County sheriff's
spokesman. ``He asked several studio employees if he could talk to
Michael Landon, but was denied access.''
   Trupp asked the guards if he could use the telephone in their
guard shack to contact Landon, star of ``Highway to Heaven.'' Roop
said Trupp left when a guard told him to use a pay phone, then
returned and began shooting.
   One guard died instantly, and the other died Friday. Trupp was
wounded minutes later in a shootout with deputies near the 420-acre
Universal Studios production and entertainment complex near downtown.
   ``A paramedic said the suspect said he was told by God to shoot
somebody,'' said county fire Capt. Glenn Mutch. Trupp also was heard
to scream ``Help me! Kill me!'' as he was strapped onto a gurney.
   Landon could not immediately be reached for comment. A message
was left on an answering machine for the actor-producer's publicist.
   Trupp, who also is accused of killing three people in an
Albuquerque, N.M., bagel shop Tuesday, was involuntarily committed
to Trenton Psychiatric Hospital in New Jersey on Nov. 25, 1987.
   A court later ruled he posed no threat and ordered him released
to a supervised boarding house in February 1988, said Mary Kay Risi,
a spokeswoman for the New Jersey Department of Human Services.
   However, Trupp fled a Trenton-area boarding house on April 5, one
day after arriving, she said.
   He was listed in serious but stable condition Friday at Saint
Joseph Medical Center in Burbank with wounds to his chest and
abdomen, said spokeswoman Linda Roberts.
   ``One of the charges he will face will probably be murder,'' said
Deputy Roger Hom. ``As soon as he is able, he will probably be moved
to the jail ward at County-USC Medical Center.''
   Security guard Jeren Beeks, 27, of La Crescenta, Calif., died at
the scene. Officers said he was shot three times in the head. The
second guard, Armando Torres, 18, died Friday at St. Joseph Hospital
in nearby Burbank. Officers said he was shot once in the head and
twice in the body.
   Tom Lopez, an engineer at the entertainment complex, said he
heard the shots but assumed they were from the ``Miami Vice'' live
entertainment show for tourists. ``When you hear gunshots in a
studio, you don't associate them with murder,'' he said.
   Trupp was unemployed and lived off a $100,000 inheritance, said
Albuquerque police, who were looking for him in connection with
Tuesday's bagel shop slayings.
   Richard Wilt, 39, his wife, Jeanne Wilt, 37, both of Albuquerque,
and the woman's father, Joseph Famiglietta Sr., 63, of nearby Rio
Rancho, were killed when a man opened fire in the store.
   According to published reports, a cab driver told authorities
that Trupp had complained of the shop's ``lousy food,'' and
Famiglietta's wife, Joan, said her husband had received a
threatening call the Sunday before the slayings.
   The caller said he was ``short a bagel,'' and added, ``I'm going
to get you for this,'' the reports said.
   The cab driver who drove Trupp to the gunshop where he purchased
a .38-caliber handgun said Trupp had told him he had been instructed
by God to kill a Nazi SS officer.
</TEXT>
