<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   12-02 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0510</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A savings industry trade group is preparing to
call for abolition of the federal fund that insures deposits in
savings and loan institutions.
   The board of the National Council of Savings Institutions, the
smaller of two lobby groups representing the savings industry, said
Thursday it plans to meet Monday to consider recommendations for
solving the nation's S&L crisis.
   Among the proposals: allowing healthy S&Ls to transfer from the
Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp. to the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp., which insures commercial banks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an effort to capitalize on a string of
box office successes, Walt Disney Co. is forming a third movie
production arm called Hollywood Pictures.
   Disney, presently the nation's top producer of movies through its
Touchstone Films and Disney Films divisions, said Thursday the new
company would start up Feb. 1. Within three years, it is to be
making 12 movies a year, the company said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for G.D. Searle & Co. have asked a
judge for a new trial after a jury awarded $8.15 million to a woman
who said the company's Copper-7 intrauterine device left her
infertile.
   A new trial should be granted because jurors were prejudiced by
information taken into the jury room by the jury foreman and other
members of the jury, Paul Strain, attorney for the pharmaceutical
company, said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pressure to reduce deficits can be expected to
be a major factor as the Bush administration searches for new farm
program formulas, Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng says.
   ``You cannot avoid having the problems of trade deficit and
fiscal deficit intrude heavily on agricultural policy in the new
administration,'' the outgoing Cabinet member told a meeting
Thursday at the Agriculture Department.
   As much as $3 billion may have to be cut from farm programs by
lawmakers in 1989 to meet targets under the Gramm-Rudman deficit
reduction law, he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC has stunned CBS with a record bid of $401
million to win the U.S. television rights to the 1992 Summer
Olympics in Barcelona, Spain.
   NBC, which televised the Summer Olympics in Seoul, South Korea,
had been considered a longshot to get the Barcelona rights. CBS was
favored because it already owns the TV rights to the 1992 Winter
Games in Albertville, France.
   NBC President Robert Wright said Thursday that as part of the
agreement, NBC agreed to spend $10 million to promote the city of
Barcelona.
</TEXT>
