<1ST_LINE>r f PM-RJR-Nabisco-Local Bjt   12-02 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-RJR-Nabisco-Local, Bjt,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Uncertainty Surrounds RJR Nabisco Tobacco Subsidiary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F. ALAN BOYCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ Dreams of big stock profits and the
possible return of RJR Nabisco Inc.'s corporate headquarters are
being tempered by the specter of layoffs in this tobacco community,
following the company's record buyout agreement.
   ``I think the general feeling is one of uncertainty,'' said Fred
Nordenholz, president of the Winston-Salem Chamber of Commerce.
``There are lots of mixed feelings about what's happening.''
   RJR Nabisco's $24.53 billion buyout agreement with Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts & Co. means potentially big windfalls for the R.J.
Reynolds Tobacco Co. workers and others among the 9,000 area
residents and groups that own an estimated $2 billion in RJR Nabisco
stock.
   Some local businessmen also see the possibility that RJR will
move its corporate headquarters, which left Winston-Salem for
Atlanta less than two years ago, back home again, bringing jobs and
prestige.
   But at the same time, the company is being bought with
unprecedented amounts of borrowed money, and locals expect
subsequent belt-tightening in a number of RJR operations _ including
the tobacco business _ that could include layoffs or other cutbacks
affecting them.
   ``Some people are going to have greater personal wealth than ever
before, and that's balanced by a certain amount of anxiety about
where the company's headed and what's going to happen to their
careers,'' Nordenholz said.
   John Davis, chairman of the Chamber of Commerce, said stories of
production-line workers becoming millionaires as stock prices nearly
doubled in the past 50 days are ``a bit overstated.''
   ``There are some people who are suddenly quarter-millionaires, on
paper anyway,'' he said.
   But not many are packing up their bags for the Bahamas. Many
local shareholders will see their gains as a sudden windfall, but
others are looking to reinvest their profits, said Davis, a managing
partner of the investment firm Alex. Brown and Sons.
   Wade Spache, a maintenance technician at Reynolds Tobacco quoted
by the Winston-Salem Journal, said he had sold some stock earlier at
$84 a share, far below the expected $109 value of the buyout but way
above the $56 range the stock held before the bidding war began Oct.
20.
   ``I just wanted to be on the safe side,'' he said. ``I didn't
want everything I had in speculation.''
   Much of the impact on the community has been psychological.
   While many analysts have portrayed R.J. Reynolds Tobacco, the
nation's No. 2 cigarette maker, as the corporation's money-making
machine, few expect the Winston-Salem-based company to go unscathed.
   But Rick Weddle, director of Winston-Salem Business Inc., said
the impact of the buyout _ even with layoffs _ would be positive in
his firm's attempts to lure other industry to the area.
   ``I am probably one of the few people alive who sees opportunity
in employment reductions,'' he said. ``We have a fairly tight labor
market for certain types of industrial skills.''
   With local unemployment in the 3 percent range recently, it has
been difficult to benefit from expansion in the export and
manufacturing sectors, Weddle said.
   ``For us to share in that we must have all the available
ingredients,'' he said.
   When the financial smoke has cleared, Winston-Salem could be in
better shape than it was a year ago, Davis said.
   ``Tobacco is fairly recession resistant, as is most of the food
business,'' he said. ``Things may be tight for a year, 18 months.
But profits have been in the 20 to 25 percent range. ...What are you
going to do, lay people off because you're making more money? It
doesn't work that way.''
   Some employees could have lingering bitterness against F. Ross
Johnson, RJR's chief executive, Davis said. It was Johnson who moved
RJR corporate headquarters to Atlanta and who kicked off the buyout
war with his own offer to buy the company.
   ``If Ross Johnson hadn't moved headquarters to Atlanta, he'd have
had everybody rooting for management,'' Davis said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
