<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GeneralCinema     12-02 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-General Cinema,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pepsico Set To Buy General Cinema Bottling Operation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some analysts say Pepsico Inc.'s planned
acquisition of General Cinema Corp.'s soft drink bottling operation
will help increase efficiency in the business, putting downward
pressure on soda prices.
   Pepsico and General Cinema announced the proposed $1.5 billion
deal on Thursday.
   Analysts said the deal would bring General Cinema top dollar for
the bottling operation, relieving some of the earnings and cash flow
pressure the company has felt from a decline in its movie revenues
and heavy investment in retailing, confectionary and tobacco
companies.
   The move brings one of the nation's biggest independent bottlers
under Pepsi's control, allowing the soft drink giant to consolidate
bottling operations and reduce costs, industry analysts said.
   ``There are too many bottlers operating at inefficient levels. If
Pepsi can bring the production costs down, the competition in the
industry will drive the retail price down,'' said Roy D. Burry, a
senior vice president at the Wall Street brokerage house of Kidder,
Peabody Inc.
   The company, headquartered in the Boston suburb of Chestnut Hill,
owns and operates 1,359 movie screens at 318 locations throughout
the United States. Earnings from the movie operations declined about
5 percent despite a slight rise in box office revenues in the fiscal
year ended Oct. 31, Nardone said.
   General Cinema owns about 60 percent of the Neiman Marcus Group,
which consists of Neiman Marcus, Bergdorf Goodman and Contempo
Casuals stores. It has announced plans to open 10 to 12 new Neiman
Marcus stores by 1995.
   General Cinema also has bought about 18 percent of the stock in
Cadbury-Schweppes PLC since 1986, said company spokesman Philip
Nardone.
   General Cinema entered the bottling business in 1968 by acquiring
American Beverage Corp., which held Pepsi franchises in Miami and
northern Ohio. It subsequently purchased other franchises and now
has regional bottling facilities in Atlanta; Jacksonville, Fla.;
Winston-Salem, N.C.; Twinsburg, Ohio; and Charleston, W.Va.
   General Cinema Beverages had preliminary revenue of about $720
million for the fiscal year ended Oct. 31 and expects operating
earnings of about $93 million, the company said.
   For the quarter ended June 30, the company reported net earnings
of about $36 million on revenue of about $631 million, more than
double the profit from the year before.
   Pepsico, headquartered in Purchase, N.Y., had earnings of $595
million on revenue of $11.5 billion in 1987. It projects revenue of
about $13 billion this year.
   Analysts said they expect the General Cinema purchase to dilute
Pepsico's earnings by about 15 cents a share in 1989.
   The companies said the transaction is subject to the signing of a
definitive agreement, clearance of antitrust laws and closing prior
to the end of 1988.
</TEXT>
