<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was trading steadily against major
currencies in Europe today, with market players reluctant to be
active ahead of the release of U.S. unemployment figures.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   Foreign exchange dealers said they didn't expect much movement
ahead of the release of the U.S. unemployment figures for November.
Market forecasts anticipate the unemployment rate will be unchanged
from its October level of 5.3 percent.
   Non-farm payrolls, which are often seen as a more direct gauge
for economic activity, are expected to show a gain of 260,000.
   ``The market is only concentrated on the unemployment figures.
They may reopen a new chapter for the dollar,'' said one corporate
trader in Rome.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.8498 from $1.8535 late
Thursday.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.07 Japanese yen to a closing 121.64
yen. Later, in London, it dropped slightly to 121.63 yen.
   Other mid-morning dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.7331 West German marks, up from
1.7300; 1.4525 Swiss francs, up from 1.4498; 5.9205 French francs,
up from 5.9075; 1.9552 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9510; 1,281.75
Italian lire, up from 1,278.00; 1.1880 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1855.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $423.35 a troy ounce, up
from Thursday's late bid price of $423.25. Later, London's major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended gold price of $423.80.
   In Zurich, the metal fell to a bid of $423.15 from $424.90 bid
late Thursday.
   In Hong Kong, gold fell $1.07 a troy ounce to close at a bid
$424.45.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a bid price of $6.12 a troy
ounce from $6.15 bid late Thursday.
