<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FarmScene     12-02 0883</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,0920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deficit to `Intrude Heavily' on Farm Policy, Outgoing Ag Chief Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farm policymakers in the Bush administration
are going to find themselves sharply constrained by pressure to cut
the budget deficit, says outgoing Secretary of Agriculture Richard
E. Lyng.
   ``You cannot avoid having the problems of trade deficit and
fiscal deficit intrude heavily on agricultural policy in the new
administration,'' Lyng said Thursday at USDA's annual Agricultural
Outlook Conference.
   Lyng and two other panelists said as much as $3 billion may have
to be cut from farm programs in 1989 to meet targets under the
Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law.
   Farm programs of the government's Commodity Credit Corp.
currently cost about $13 billion a year, down from peak of $26
billion in fiscal 1986.
   The panelists suggested that Congress might pass an extension of
the farm law and postpone at least until 1991 any real overhaul of
the current five-year programs expiring in 1990.
   Lyng again said he will be leaving at the start of the new
administration. Numerous possible successors have been mentioned,
but thus far no word has come from President-elect Bush or his
transition team.
   Farm programs approved in 1985 under the pressure of a
large-scale rural crisis have proven highly popular, Lyng said.
   ``I don't think we would have any changes in farm programs if it
weren't for budget pressures,'' he said. But ``You've got $3 billion
to save in some shape or form and it's going to drive changes, I
think, in 1989.''
   Even so, there is no reason to think the Bush administration will
propose sweeping changes right away, said Lynn Daft, an agricultural
economist and former USDA official.
   ``You don't have to come forward with legislation right away,''
he said. He noted that farmers are not clamoring for any change. ``I
don't see any tractors across the street on the Mall,'' he said.
   ``If I were a new administration coming in, I'd say, why rush?''
he said.
   That only provides another reason for stopgap legislation, the
panelists said.
   ``Particularly when you've got eight members of the Senate
Agriculture Committee up for re-election'' in 1990, said William
Lesher, a consultant and former Lyng business partner also appearing
on the panel.
   ``My guess as the secretary says is that it's at least a 50
percent chance'' that stopgap legislation will be approved, he said.
   Lesher told the panel there are only three ways to reduce farm
program spending by $3 billion.
   He said one would be to lower target prices _ congressionally set
price levels used in calculating income-support payments. Another
would be to reduce the acreage base used in calculating payments, he
said, and a third would be to cut the amount of acreage planted.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has unveiled a 1989
program for rice farmers with a national average price-support level
of $6.50 for each 100 pounds.
   The support level represents an expected reduction from a
national average of $6.63 in 1988.
   Price support loans are paid by the government's Commodity Credit
Corp. to farmers who post their crops as collateral. Because
producers are free to forfeit the crops and keep the cash, the
system puts a floor under prices.
   Among program requirements that farmers must meet to qualify for
federal subsidies, Secretary of Agriculture Richard E. Lyng
announced a required acreage reduction of 25 percent. This
represents land that farmers cannot plant and is designed to prevent
surpluses.
   Lyng set the established target price at $10.80 for each 100
pounds, down from $11.15 this year.
   Target prices are used in calculating so-called deficiency
payments that the government provides as income supports to
participants in some programs.
   Other provisions of the rice program:
   _Whole kernel milled rice price support rates were set at $10.81
per hundredweight for long grain and $9.81 for medium and short
grain rice. The broken kernel rate for all rice classes is $5.41.
   _Producers who pledged 1989 crop rice as collateral for price
support loans will not be permitted to purchase marketing
certificates when repaying loans at the marketing loan repayment
rate.
   _The discretionary inventory reduction program will not be
implemented.
   _Farmers may sign up for the program between Dec. 19 and April 14.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Enrollments in colleges of agriculture at land
grant universities are up this year, reversing a decade-long
decline, the Agriculture Department says.
   ``This fall, undergraduate enrollments have taken a long awaited
upturn at many agricultural colleges,'' said a statement from J.
Patrick Jordan, administrator of USDA's cooperative state extension
service. ``At other schools, enrollments of agriculture majors have
begun to stabilize after years of fewer and fewer ag majors.''
   He said a USDA survey showed agriculture enrollment up 11 percent
in two years at Kansas State, 4 percent in the last year at Purdue,
16 percent at Penn State and 4 percent at Oregon State.
   Starting salaries for graduates also are on the rise, the
department said.
   It said campus placement officials reported starting salaries
ranging up to $30,000 for food science graduates. Purdue reported
salaries up to $30,000 for agricultural engineers, food science and
agricultural economics graduates.
   The average, however, was about $20,000 and those finding jobs in
urban areas tended to get more, the department said.
</TEXT>
