<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Summit     12-02 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Summit,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Leaders Open Two-Day Economic Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RHODES, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 12 EEC leaders opened a two-day summit
Friday to review progress toward creating a borderless,
single-market Europe by 1992.
   Officials said the leaders would seek to reassure the United
States and Japan, the EEC's main trading partners, that their
efforts to boost trade within the European Economic Community will
not be at the expense of imports.
   A draft statement to that effect, says that a single EEC market
will benefit also ``non community countries. 1992 Europe will not
close in on itself...will not be a fortress Europe but a partnership
Europe.''
   About 12 hours before the summit began, four bombs exploded in
Athens about 200 miles away, police said. No one was injured in the
blasts that caused minor damage to buildings, including an EEC
office. The Revolutionary Popular Struggle said it set off the
bombs. The left-wing group has claimed responsibility for bomb
attacks in the past.
   The EEC leaders, accompanied by their foreign ministers, began
their meeting with a luncheon hosted by Greek Premier Andreas
Papandreou, the summit's host.
   On Friday morning, the leaders held bilateral meetings. Britsh
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher met with West German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl and, officials said, they agreed it would be useful to
have a summit meeting of the leaders of the 16 NATO nations in
London in either May or June.
   The EEC summit is held at the Knights' palace, a 14th century
castle that is part of a medieval citadel overlooking the entrance
to a small harbor that the colossus of Rhodes was once said to have
straddled.
   The Greeks spent nearly $5 million renovating the massive
205-room castle which Italian dictator Benito Mussolini once planned
to use as his summer residence.
   The Greek premier arrived Thursday leading a 150-member
delegation.
   ``I feel optimistic about the summit. I think we can reach
significant decisions that will be good for the Community and good
for Greece,'' Papandreou said.
   The comment was apparently designed to remove fears Thatcher will
press her case that the EEC`s single-market project must not lead to
the creation of a central bank and a single currency.
   Britain's EEC partners, however, feel that is the road the
Community must take.
   Officials said the European leaders will have wide-ranging
political discussions.
   They are expected to discuss, among other things, the Middle East
and to issue a statement on East-West relations and the EEC's role
in world affairs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
