<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 2ndLd-Writethru   12-02 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0746</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unemployment Rate Rises To 5.4 Percent In November</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs on market reaction to numbers; picks up
5th graf pvs, On Thursday ...; will be led again with Commerce
Department reports on new home sales and factory orders, scheduled
for 10 a.m. EST release.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates jumped and stocks slipped today in reaction to a
government report that the economy created 463,000 jobs in November
and a record percentage of the American population was at work.
   The signs of economic growth were regarded as more significant
than a slight uptick in the civilian unemployment rate, which rose
to 5.4 percent from a 14-year low of 5.3 percent in October.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks
dipped 8.53 points to 2,093.35 after half an hour of trading.
   The dollar was little changed in active trading. Ordinarily the
dollar would rise in response to evidence of strong economic growth,
but there was little buying interest.
   ``The market has totally and unequivocally ignored whatever
positive news for the dollar there has been,'' said John McCarthy,
chief currency dealer for Amsterdam Rotterdam Bank in New York.
   The 0.1 percentage point increase from October's jobless rate was
due almost entirely to a 560,000 increase in the civilian labor
force _ the number of people either holding jobs or looking for
them, the Labor Department said.
   The labor force had remained essentially unchanged from August
through October and has grown by only 2 million people in the past
12 months, including the big gain in November, reflecting a tapering
off of the Baby Boom generation entering the job market.
   Despite the slight increase in the unemployment rate, the
government figures showed 116 million Americans holding jobs last
month, or 62.6 percent of the adult population age 16 or over. Both
are record highs, said Labor Statistics Commissioner Janet L.
Norwood.
   Strong employment gains raise fears that the economy will
overheat and prices will rise. That hurts the value of fixed-income
securities.
   The price of the Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond fell 1 3-16
point, or $11.88 per $1,000 face amount. Its yield, which rises when
the price falls, climbed to 9.13 percent from 9.02 percent late
Thursday.
   There were rumors that the Federal Reserve would raise its
discount rate to cool off the economy. Such a move would push up
short-term interest rates in general, making the dollar more
attractive to the world's investors.
   But the dollar was flat to slightly lower in hectic trading
today, at about 121.3 Japanese yen and 1.73 West German marks.
   On Thursday, the Commerce Department said its main economic
barometer indicated a possible slowing of the economy's expansion
during October. It said its Index of Leading Indicators edged up 0.1
percent after falling the previous month.
   Analysts cautioned against drawing any firm conclusions until the
index, used to forecast the economy's direction, established a
consistent pattern.
   The index has declined in five of the past 12 months. It dropped
a revised 0.3 percent in September, compared with the previous
estimate of minus 0.1 percent. It also fell in July and May, but
rose in June and August.
   When the economy is slowing, the Federal Reserve Board is less
likely to move interest rates higher.
   The financial markets all but disregarded the leading indicators
report, awaiting instead today's release of the November
unemployment figures. Activity on all markets was light as many
investors stayed on the sidelines.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, up
nearly 40 points over the past three sessions, fell 12.63 to close
at 2,101.88.
   The dollar was little changed in foreign exchange trading.
   The bond market reacted positively to the leading indicators,
with the Treasury's key 30-year issue rising about $5 for every
$1,000 in face amount. In a separate report Thursday, the Commerce
Department said construction activity rose 0.9 percent in October to
a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $409.2 billion, the fourth
consecutive monthly increase.
   Strength was in most categories, but half the gain came in
single-family homes, the department said.
   In other economic news, the nation's largest general retailers
reported their sales continued at a sluggish pace in November, but
an end-of-the-month surge was a positive sign for the Christmas
shopping season.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
