<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0348</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell in early trading today after
Wall Street was disappointed by better-than-expected employment
figures.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was down 8.53 to
2,093.35 as of 10 a.m. EST.
   Declining issues were ahead of advancers by a margin of 3-to-1,
with 745 issues falling, 247 rising and 457 unchanged in New York
Stock Exchange trading.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed stocks was down 0.49
to 152.88 On the American Stock Exchange, the market value index
slipped 0.64 to 294.61.
   Volume on the Big Board came to a light 18.12 million shares
after the first 30 minutes of trading.
   The Labor Department's eagerly awaited report on November
employment disappointed traders because of an increase of 463,000
new jobs _ an indication that the economy remains robust.
   Stock prices declined on the news because of the likelihood that
the Federal Reserve would move interest rates higher to cool the
economy down and keep a lid on inflation.
   ``With employment soaring and capacity so full, the Fed's going
to have to lean against the economy and raise the discount rate,''
said Larry Wachtel, a market analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   In its report, the Labor Department also said the unemployment
rate rose to 5.4 percent from October's 5.3 percent.
   The most-actively traded issue on the NYSE today was RJR Nabisco,
which fell { to 91\.
   Other decliners included AT&T, down [ at 29\, and General
Electric, off \ at 43}.
   Mining stocks were among the gainers, as gold is a hedge against
inflation. ASA rose [ to 38~, and Hecla Mining rose [ to 13}.
   On Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial average lost 12.63 to close
at 2,101.88.
   Declining issues outnumbered gainers by about 8-to-7 in
nationwide trading of NYSE-listed stocks, with 805 issues up, 680
down and 486 unchanged.
   NYSE volume came to 129.38 million shares, down from 157.81
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
