<2ND_LINE>PM-American-Radar,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Airlines Signs Contract for Radar Systems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bendix-King has signed an agreement
to provide federally required collision avoidance radar systems for
American Airlines.
   The multi-year agreement announced Thursday by the companies is
valued at $100 million. It calls for Bendix-King to provide the
systems for 600 planes.
   Fort Worth-based American plans to spend an estimated $140
million for the equipment, including installation, according to
American spokesman Jim Brown.
   Installation is expected to start late next year and be completed
by the end of 1991 to meet a federal deadline for adding the
systems, Brown said.
   The Bendix-King system lets commercial and corporate aircraft
communicate automatically with each other, pinpointing location,
altitude and direction.
   When another plane comes within five miles, the system's monitor
will highlight its position, direction, altitude and ascent or
descent. If the system determines that the plane is on a collision
course, it will instruct the pilot _ both by synthesized voice and
an on-screen graphic _ to descend, climb or hold present course.
</TEXT>
