   ``Things are starting to steady up a bit,'' Mao said about 20
minutes after the opening. ``It might be that we just ran through a
liquidation phase and now we'll come back.''
   In early trading, wheat was 1{ cents lower to } cent higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.15} a bushel; corn was }
cent to 1{ cents lower with December at $2.56 a bushel; oats were }
cent lower to 1 cent higher with December at $1.90{ a bushel;
soybeans were { cent to 4 cents lower with January at $7.54{ a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .67 cent lower with December at
72.12 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to .40 cent lower
with January at 82.90 cents a pound; live hogs were unchanged to .33
cent lower with December at 40.30 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were unchanged to .40 cent lower with February at 44.67 cents a
