<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices declined on Wall Street today as
better-than-expected employment figures heightened trader concerns
about rising interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was down 11.73 to
2,090.15 as of noon EST.
   Declining issues were ahead of advancers by a margin of about
2-to-1, with 843 issues falling, 399 rising and 531 unchanged in New
York Stock Exchange trading.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed stocks was down 0.65
to 152.72 On the American Stock Exchange, the market value index
slipped 1.00 to 294.25.
   Volume on the Big Board came to a light 56.74 million shares by
midday.
   The Labor Department's eagerly awaited report on November
employment disappointed traders because of an increase of 463,000
new jobs _ an indication that the economy remains robust.
   Bond prices tumbled on the news and stock prices followed suit
because of the likelihood that the Federal Reserve would move
interest rates higher to cool the economy down and keep a lid on
inflation.
   ``With employment soaring and capacity so full, the Fed's going
to have to lean against the economy and raise the discount rate,''
said Larry Wachtel, a market analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   In its report, the Labor Department also said the unemployment
rate rose to 5.4 percent from October's 5.3 percent.
   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond skidded about $13 per
$1,000 in face value on the employment data because of the prospect
of higher interest rates. The bond's yield surged to 9.14 percent
from late Thursday's 9.02 percent.
   Analysts said Wall Street was keeping a close eye on interest
rate movements in the credit markets.
   ``We seem to be trading off bonds,'' said Peter Vandenberg, a
stock market analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The most-actively traded issue on the NYSE today was RJR Nabisco,
which slipped | to 91[.
   Other decliners included AT&T, down ] at 29, Exxon, which slipped
] to 42|, and General Electric, off \ at 43}.
   Mining stocks were among the gainers, as gold is a hedge against
inflation. ASA rose \ to 39, and Hecla Mining was up \ to 13~.
