<HEAD>Cincy Milacron to Sell Subsidiary to Japanese Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cincinnati Milacron Inc. announced Friday it
plans to sell its semiconductor materials subsidiary to a Japanese
company which manufactures components for the semiconductor industry.
   Cincinnati Milacron, a Cincinnati-based manufacturer, declined to
disclose the price that Osaka Titanium Co. Ltd. will pay for the
subsidiary, Cincinnati Milacron Semiconductor Materials Inc.
   Milacron officials said they understand that Osaka Titanium plans
to continue manufacturing of semiconductor materials at Milacron's
plant in the southwestern Ohio town of Maineville. Milacron
officials said in February that they were seeking a buyer for the
semiconductor subsidiary.
   Cincinnati Milacron said another Japanese company, Sumitomo Metal
Industries Ltd., will hold an indirect minority interest in the
acquiring company.
   Osaka Titanium produces titanium sponge and silicon wafers for
the semiconductor industry. Sumitomo Metal Industries produces iron
and steel.
   Cincinnati Milacron had sales of $828 million in 1987. The
company's products also include industrial robots, plastics
machinery and machine tools.
