<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1308EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Unemployment 3rdLd-Writethru   12-02 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Unemployment, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0772</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Civilian Unemployment Edged Up in November to 5.4 Percent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts graf 5, At the White House, with comment; Also moved
on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's civilian unemployment rate in
November edged upward from a 14-year low to 5.4 percent despite an
increase of 463,000 new jobs and a record percentage of the American
population at work, the government said today.
   The 0.1 percentage point increase from October's jobless rate of
5.3 percent was due almost entirely to a 560,000 increase in the
civilian labor force _ the number of people either holding jobs or
looking for them, the Labor Department said.
   The labor force had remained essentially unchanged from August
through October and has grown by only 2 million people in the past
12 months, including the big gain in November, reflecting a tapering
off of the Baby Boom generation entering the job market.
   Despite the slight increase in the unemployment rate, the
government figures showed 116 million Americans holding jobs last
month, or 62.6 percent of the adult population age 16 or over. Both
are record highs, said Labor Statistics Commissioner Janet L.
Norwood.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater attributed the
rise to ``a large increase in the labor force'' and noted that the
total number of employed reached an all-time high. ``There were more
people looking for work,'' he said.
   The number of factory jobs climbed by 71,000 in November on top
of a four-year record-high 99,000 new assembly line workers in
October following a slight decline in the late summer.
   ``Over the past year, the number of factory jobs has risen by
425,000,'' Norwood said in prepared testimony before the Joint
Economic Committee of Congress. `This growth has been concentrated
in a limited number of industries, with machinery alone counting for
more than a quarter of the gain.''
   Meanwhile, factory workers continued to average four hours of
overtime a week last month, indicating that the manufacturing sector
is continuning to boom and there is no slowdown in the rate of
economic growth.
   Many economists are concerned that inflation will continue
increasing unless the growth rate is slowed, but there was no
indication that it did in November, acording to the job figures, the
first economic indicator of the month.
   Construction employment increased by 55,000 over the month,
reflecting an upturn in housing starts, after sluggish activity from
July through October.
   The November job figures officially mark the sixth birthday of
the current economic expansion, the longest in the nation's history.
But the pattern of growth has not been consistent throughout.
   Factory jobs, for example, rose by 1.4 million in the first two
years of recovery following a loss of nearly 2 million jobs in the
1981-82 recession. But in 1985 and 1986, they declined by 600,000
before rebounding by 850,000 over the past two years.
   `Not unexpectedly, changes in the unemployment rate for adult men
have tracked closely with the factory job swings,'' said Norwood.
`It fell from 10 percent to 6.2 percent during the initial rebound,
was unchanged in the middle years, and dropped from 6.2 percent to
4.8 percent in the past two years.''
   The pattern of female joblessness, meanwhile, has shown a more
consistent, gradual decline. It, too, was 4.8 percent last month.
   The service side of the economy added 345,000 new jobs last
month, including 40,000 in transportation, reflecting an improvement
in the health of the airline industry.
   Retail trade employment climbed by 19,000 despite a decrease of
2,000 workers in department stores. Department store employment has
now been falling for five months in a row, an indication to some
economists that consumer spending is slowing and that exports of
U.S. manufactred products abroad are propelling the nation's
continued growth.
   Health service jobs rose by 56,000 last month while employment in
business services such as data processing climbed by 31,000 after
several months of sluggish activity.
   Meanwhile, average hourly earnings were unchanged at $9.45 in
November after rising by a nickel in October, setting off fears of a
wage-push inflation then.
   An alternate employment rate that includes the 1.7 million
members of the Armed Forces stationed in the country also rose last
month, from 5.2 percent to 5.3 percent.
   Unemployment rates for various population groups showed little or
no improvement. They climbed from 11 percent to 11.2 percent for
blacks, from 7.7 percent to 8.1 percent for Hispanics and from 26.5
percent to 30.4 percent for black teen-agers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881202-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1403EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv05   12-02 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 05,0664</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Monday Dec. 5</NOTE>
<HEAD>What A Deal!</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix cycle designator.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In their latest and most likely final offer, the
management of RJR Nabisco Inc. offered shareholders $8 billion more
for their shares than in their first offer.
   What is $8 billion?
   Among other things, it is the asset value of a company the size
of Minnesota Mining & Manufacturing Co., including about 180 plants
and 370 sales offices and distribution centers in 49 countries.
   Or it is the assets of Georgia-Pacific Corp., which owns or has
cutting rights to 5.6 million acres of North American timberlands _
plus Morton Thiokol Inc., the aerospace contractor, and a few
hundred million dollars in change.
   Had shareholders accepted the first offer, which was publicized
as being in their interest, they would have, so to speak, left that
much on the table.
   It is because of such mind-boggling considerations as these that
aspects of the RJR Nabisco sale will be debated well into the next
century, and perhaps as long as business schools exist.
   Did shareholders get a fair deal? It would seem so, since the
stock leaped in a few weeks from $55 a share to more than $90. But
even after such good fortune, some shareholders might not be as
happy as you might think.
   A good many RJR Nabisco shareholders were long-term investors
with an eye on the steady dividends of 5 percent or so a year, which
they had expected to continue well into the future.
   These investors were not traders or sellers. RJR Nabisco was, to
them, a source of income. Suddenly, they have capital gains taxes to
pay which, when combined with state taxes, could approach 40 percent.
   What does the precipitous sale of an established company mean to
holders of bonds? Big losses. Bonds purchased when the company's
debt position was strong have, inevitably, lost value as the company
becomes burdened with debt.
   The questions drive at the very meaning of a company.
   Is a corporation a dynamic, ever-changing institution whose value
_ to its immediate owners or to society at large _ lies in its
unique ability to produce products and services?
   Or is it to be viewed as a static entity, like a consumer product
on a shelf, to be sold, and in the selling lose all its future value
as a creator of change, a payer of dividends, an employer, a
taxpayer, a producer?
   How is the RJR Nabisco management to be viewed, or in fact the
management of any company that promises to serve the shareholders,
creditors, employees and customers, but which plots to take the
company for its own portfolio?
   The meaning of ``insider trading,'' a term used commonly to
describe those outsiders who gain access to inside information and
use it for their own financial gain, might have to be reconsidered.
   Consider that prior to making their announcements, buyout
managements use privileged information to construct their offer.
They allow investors to buy bonds, knowing that those bonds will
fall in value on their announcement.
   Is it proper for management to arrange for the continuance of
their salaries, plus benefits, bonuses and lucrative pensions should
they fail in their takeover attempt and instead fall prey to a
hostile offer?
   Is an insider takeover and dismantling a proper end for a
thriving company built on the savings, sacrifices and ingenuity of
entrepreneurs, the millions of man-hours of labor, the years of
risks, the hard times conquered?
   In comparison, what sacrifices, ingenuity, labor, risks and hard
times are incurred by a management that benefits from its failure,
i.e. that puts the company on the block because it thinks it might
be better dead than alive?
   The debate is only beginning.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Mon Dec. 05</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881202-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1323EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-IBM-Fujitsu     12-02 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-IBM-Fujitsu,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arbitrators Say IBM-Fujitsu Deal Fair And Balanced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONIKA JAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The recent ruling ordering a Japanese computer
company to pay International Business Machines Corp. for use of the
software information running its computers was fair and should
satisfy concerns over protecting intellectual property rights,
American arbitrators said Friday.
   In a landmark case, two arbitrators assigned by the American
Arbitration Association Tuesday ordered Japan's largest computer
firm, Fujitsu Ltd., to pay IBM $237 million and tens of millions of
dollars each year beginning in 1989 under a complex payout plan for
special access to IBM's mainframe computer software.
   Including past payments, Fujitsu could pay IBM more than $1
billion by the end of the century.
   The decision followed years of wrangling between the world's
biggest computer company and its main Japanese rival over what IBM
claimed was Fujitsu's infringement on its intellectual property
rights.
   Fujitsu competes with IBM in the mainframe computer business with
a line of machines and accompanying base-layer software that are
supposed to be able to run the same programs as the IBM mainframes.
   Exploiting often murky copyright laws, Japan has been accused in
the past of altering imported technology to suit its own
requirements. The ruling by the arbitration association is expected
to make Japanese industry more cautious.
   ``The days when ideas were free are now over,'' said an editorial
Thursday in the Asahi Evening News.
   ``By tradition, Japanese industry has relied on Western
technologies for growth, freely `borrowing' them and adapting them
cleverly to its own needs.''
   ``But this won't be acceptable in the future,'' the editorial
said. ``The AAA ruling on the IBM-Fujitsu dispute will lend impetus
to the mounting global trend toward demanding monetary payment for
intellectual property.''
   Mnookin, a law professor at Stanford Law School, said IBM had
invested billions of dollars in its operating systems software.
While ``the precise scope of copyright protection is not entirely
clear, what is clear is that this investment in its property is
worthy of ... protection,'' he said.
   He said the ruling was ``fair and balanced'' and one in which
both parties were made substantially better off.
   ``Any concerns that customers may have had because of
uncertainties about intellectual property rights with respect to
compatible operating system software have now been put to rest,''
Jones said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
