<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1332EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Chrysler-Kenosha     12-02 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Chrysler-Kenosha,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>About 2,200 Chrysler workers to continue to receive pay after
production ends</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,200 of the most senior Chrysler
Corp. workers in Kenosha will continue to receive full pay and
benefits after the Dec. 23 end of production in the city until a
company-funded, $20 million job bank is depleted, a union official
says.
   United Auto Workers Local 72 Shop Committee Chairman Rudy Kuzel
said Thursday the job bank was provided in the plant closing
agreement negotiated with Chrysler.
   Kuzel estimated it will take the 2,200 employees about eight to
nine weeks, or until about March, to deplete the $20 million.
   After the money is gone, the workers can turn to state-sponsored
unemployment compensation benefits and company-funded Supplemental
Unemployment Benefits.
   The job bank was formed as compensation for the transfer of
L-body Dodge Omni and Plymouth Horizon model production from Kenosha
to Chrysler's Jefferson Avenue plant in Detroit.
   ``But the job bank is not just for those working on L-body,''
Kuzel said.
   The contract said the 2,200 most senior employees could be
transferred to non-traditional work once the L-body line is moved.
But Kuzel said he doubts enough work will remain in Kenosha for all
of them to actually be on the job.
   Regardless of whether they are working or not, they will earn
full pay and benefits, he said.
   The Wisconsin Job Service has said that most Chrysler Corp.
employees losing their jobs as a result of the plant closing will be
eligible for $200 weekly unemployment benefits for 26 weeks. The
union workers are to also receive SUB benefits of $100 per week for
24 weeks.
   Chrysler has said the ending of auto production in Kenosha will
put about 5,300 people out of work. About 1,200 people are to
continue working at the automaker's engine operation in Kenosha.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
