<DOCNO> AP881202-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1359EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-MackTrucks     12-02 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Mack Trucks,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mack Trucks Announces New Truck Line</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mack Trucks Inc. has unveiled a new truck
with a larger cab and sleeping space that is aimed at the market of
owner-operators.
   Mack Chairman John C. Curcio showed off the new truck Thursday
predicting it would boost company profit and revenue.
   If so, Mack would have consecutive profitable years for the first
time since 1978-79, according to Curcio.
   Curcio, speaking at Mack headquarters here, said the CH600 truck
would be produced at Mack's new factory in Winnsboro, S.C. The new
factory replaced an aging plant in Allentown.
   ``What you are seeing today is the first truly all-new truck of
the 1990s,'' the chairman said.
   He said the truck represented a five-year commitment by Mack, $60
million in design and development, plus millions of miles in testing.
   ``We see the results of shortcutting this process far too often
in today's super-competitive truck industry,'' Curcio said. ``We
resisted the temptation to rush to the market with a rehashed
version of the same old thing, or to rush a less-than-fully
developed and tested vehicle to market, as some other manufacturers
have done.''
   The innovations are expected to increase Mack's market share by 2
to 3 percentage points by 1991 from its current share of about 15
percent, said Paul Ritter, senior vice president of sales for the
company.
   After operating in red ink from 1982 through 1986, Mack Trucks
earned $4.09 million in 1987. The company has said it expects to
move further into the black this year.
   Through the first nine months of 1988, Mack reported earnings of
$18 million on sales of $1.6 billion, compared to a $15 million
profit on sales of $1.4 billion during the same period in 1987.
   The truck includes a new frame and chassis, and aerodynamic
efficiency was a key consideration in its design, Curcio said. Among
aspects designed to smooth air flow around the truck are a two-piece
windshield sloped 20 degrees and rounded and contoured lamps, the
company said.
   The CH600 will be no more expensive than Mack's former
conventional ``R'' truck _ averaging about $60,000.
   The CH600 _ and the E-7 engine to be introduced for the truck in
July or August _ are part of Mack's $500 million capital expenditure
program begun by Curcio in 1983.
   Part of Curcio's program was the replacement of the company's
antiquated 5C assembly plant in Allentown with one of the industry's
most modern assembly plants. Production of the new truck is to begin
Jan. 1.
   Last year, Mack introduced its CM400, its down-sized ``Baby 8''
intercity vehicle, and began producing it in its Macungie assembly
plant. The company also is spending $100 million to modernize its
power-train division in Hagerstown, Md., for production of the new
E-7 engine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
