<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1433EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     12-02 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0414</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices declined but then bounced back from their
lows on Wall Street today after the Labor Department released
better-than-expected employment figures for November.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was down 6.93 to
2,094.95 as of 2 p.m. EST. In earlier trading, the average was down
about 17 points.
   Declining issues were ahead of advancers by a margin of about
8-to-5, with 825 issues falling, 505 rising and 547 unchanged in New
York Stock Exchange trading.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed stocks was down 0.35
to 153.02 On the American Stock Exchange, the market value index
slipped 0.35 to 294.90.
   Volume on the Big Board came to a light 87.71 million shares with
two hours of trading left.
   The Labor Department's eagerly awaited report on November
employment disappointed traders because of an increase of 463,000
new jobs _ an indication that the economy remains robust.
   Bond prices tumbled on the news and stock prices followed suit
because of the likelihood that the Federal Reserve would move
interest rates higher to cool the economy down and keep a lid on
inflation.
   ``With employment soaring and capacity so full, the Fed's going
to have to lean against the economy and raise the discount rate,''
said Larry Wachtel, a market analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   But stocks recouped some of their losses in afternoon trading.
   Michael Metz, an analyst with Oppenheimer & Co., said ``A lot of
investors are looking for an entry into the market.''
   He said some traders believed Wall Street's reaction to the Labor
Department figures was a temporary phenomenon, and the fact they
were buying stocks showed how resilient the market was.
   In its report, the Labor Department also said the unemployment
rate rose to 5.4 percent from October's 5.3 percent.
   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond skidded about $13 per
$1,000 in face value on the employment data because of the prospect
of higher interest rates. The bond's yield surged to 9.14 percent
from late Thursday's 9.02 percent.
   The most-actively traded issue on the NYSE today was RJR Nabisco,
which slipped ~ to 90~.
   Other decliners included AT&T, down { at 28~, and Exxon, which
slipped { to 42{.
   Technology stocks were among the gainers. IBM picked up 1[ to
119] and Hewlett Packard was up 1 at 50.
</TEXT>
