<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     12-02 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar And Gold Varied In Europe</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar turned mixed against the major
European currencies on Friday. Gold prices also varied.
   The news that non-farm payrolls in the United States rose by
463,000 in November, exceeding expectations by some 200,000, helped
the dollar early in the day.
   But London dealers said the U.S. currency couldn't hold most of
the rise because of sales of dollars in Tokyo, a large, unidentified
order to buy sterling, and some profit-taking.
   News that the U.S. unemployment rate in October was revised
upward to 5.4 percent from 5.3 percent also hurt the dollar.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8597 late Friday, more
expensive for buyers than Thursday's late $1.8535.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with Thursday's late
rates: 1.7315 West German marks, up from 1.7300; 1.4598 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4498; 5.9200 French francs, up from 5.9075; 1.9490
Dutch guilders, down from 1.9510; 1,279.50 Italian lire, up from
1,278.00; and 1.1869 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1855.
   Earlier in Tokyo the dollar closed at 121.64 Japanese yen, up
from 121.57. In London late Friday the dollar traded lower at 121.35
yen.
   Gold closed in London at a bid $425.50 a troy ounce, up from
$423.25. The Zurich closing bid price was $424.30 an ounce, down
from $424.90.
   Gold closed in Hong Kong at $424.45 an ounce, down from $425.52.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $6.13 a troy ounce, down
from $6.15.
</TEXT>
