<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   12-02 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Surge on South American Concern</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed sharply higher
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade on reduced chances for a wet
weekend in the South American soybean belt and strong gains in the
soybean oil market.
   Grain futures finished mostly higher.
   Concerns about the unusually dry weather in Brazil and Argentina,
the world's second- and fourth-largest soybean producers, have
become the dominant factor in the U.S. soybean futures market since
planting began in those countries earlier this fall.
   Forecasts for a rainy weekend in Brazil had prompted active
selling of futures on Thursday but Friday's forecasts indicated
chances for rain were diminishing, and that sparked a rally,
analysts said.
   ``We ended up with a little bit of emotional action in the last
hour of trading _ we were up and down here,'' said Jerry Gidel, an
analyst in Chicago with the G.H. Miller division of LIT America Inc.
   Rumors that Brazil was considering importing soybean oil from
Argentina, either for its own needs or to export, sent soybean oil
futures prices up sharply and added support to the soybean market,
Gidel said.
   At the close of trading, wheat was 1{ cents lower to 3 cents
higher with the contract for delivery in December at $4.19 a bushel;
corn was 1\ cents lower to 1\ cents higher with December at $2.58{ a
bushel; oats were 3{ cents to 6 cents higher with December at $1.94{
a bushel; soybeans were 8 cents to 11 cents higher with January at
$7.69 a bushel.
</TEXT>
