<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881202-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 2153EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv03-04   12-02 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 03-04,0645</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 3-4</NOTE>
<HEAD>KKR Discloses Details of RJR Financing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. unveiled on Friday
the financing plan for its record $24.53 billion purchase of RJR
Nabisco Inc. that includes a complex assortment of bank loans, junk
bonds and some cash from its own pocket.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, the
powerful Wall Street buyout firm illustrated the techniques it
typically uses in leveraged buyouts, only on a far grander scale.
   The LBO concept is quite simple: After making a small
downpayment, a firm and its investors borrow the rest of the
purchase and pay off that debt with funds generated by a target
company's profits or asset sales. In effect, the business itself is
used as collateral.
   The borrowing process, though, can get confusing.
   ``A lot of the financing is just plain vanilla. That's not the
case here,'' said Robert Waill, a high-yield bond specialist with
L.F. Rothschild Holdings Inc.
   The RJR buyout will require more than $20 billion in loans to
finance the cash portion of the $109-a-share offer accepted
Wednesday by a special RJR directors committee. Kohlberg's offer was
selected over a $25.2 billion bid from a group led by F. Ross
Johnson, RJR's chief executive.
   Besides getting $81 in cash for each of their shares, RJR
stockholders will receive a total $4 billion in preferred stock and
$2.3 bilion in convertible bonds.
   Kohlberg said in its SEC filing that four banks _ Bankers Trust,
Chase Manhattan, Citibank and Manufacturers Hanover Trust _ will
lend $2.7 billion themselves and assemble a syndicate of other banks
to lend an additional $14 billion.
   Kohlberg's two main Wall Street financial backers, Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. and Merrill Lynch & Co., will provide $5 billion in
short-term ``bridge loans'' that will be repaid by selling
high-yield, high-risk ``junk bonds,'' according to the SEC filing
and a spokeswoman for Kohlberg.
   Another $5 billion of existing RJR debt also could become
downgraded to junk bonds in the processs since the acquistion will
more than quadruple the company's existing debt to $22.3 billion.
   The buyout also will make RJR the largest single junk bond
issuer, analysts said. Union Carbide Corp. now holds that
distinction, with $4.2 billion.
   ``One major difference is that Union Carbide didn't issue them
all at once,'' said Kenneth Urbaszewski, who manages $4 billion in
junk bonds at Kemper Financial Services in Chicago.
   But Urbaszewski believes the high-yield market can absorb the
deluge of expected RJR debt, as long as those issues are priced
right.
   ``There's plenty of cash out there now,'' he said.
   Urbaszewski noted that despite the huge resulting debt load,
RJR's ratio of debt to equity would be only 3-to-1, which is
considered low for a leveraged buyout. By contrast, Kohlberg's 1986
buyout of supermarket giant Safeway Stores Inc. for $4.2 billion
left the acquired company with a debt-to-equity ratio of 10-to-1.
   The higher the debt load the harder it is for a company to pay
off its loans.
   For its part, Kohlberg is putting up $1.5 billion in cash for the
RJR acquisition, most of which will come from a $5 billion pool of
capital invested by institutional investors. Kohlberg also is
lending $500 million for the acquisition, the filing said.
   A Kohlberg spokeswoman said she did not know exactly how much of
the $1.5 billion in cash was coming from the buyout firm itself.
However, the Washington Post reported Friday that Kohlberg planned
to put only slightly more than $15 million of its own money into the
purchase.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Dec. 3-4</NOTE>
</DOC>
