<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-02 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precious Metals Surge On Jobless Data, Argentina</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices of precious metals futures surged Friday on the Chicago
Board of Trade amid renewed inflation fears and jitters over a
military insurrection in Argentina, analysts said.
   On other markets, copper and cattle futures fell sharply; pork
futures were mixed; grains and soybeans were higher; energy futures
were mixed; and stock-index futures advanced.
   Analysts counted Friday's unemployment report as one bullish
factor in the precious-metals markets. The 5.4 percent November
jobless rate was near expectations but the increase of 463,000 new
jobs was much higher than the markets had anticipated, and many saw
it as a sign that wages and inflation may rise.
   ``If you're looking at precious metals as an inflation hedge, the
unemployment numbers were quite positive,'' said Jack Barbanel,
director of futures trading with Gruntal & Co., a New York brokerage
firm.
   Analysts also agreed that the dollar's weakness, following a
strong start, helped fuel the precious-metals rally.
   News reports of a mutinous clash between loyal and rebel military
factions near Buenos Aires, Argentina, may also have sparked some
buying among those who favor gold as a haven during turbulent times,
said Scott Hinton, an analyst with Elders Futures Inc. in New York.
   The rally accelerated when gold futures cracked a key technical
resistance point at around $432 on the contract for February
delivery.
   ``That really set the market off,'' Hinton said. ``You're getting
into an area where a lot of people are saying, `This downtrend is
over, it's time to get out of long-term short (or sell) positions.'''
   Gold settled $7.80 to $9.90 higher with the active February
contract at $436.70 an ounce and spot December at $431.70; silver
was 9 cents to 10.2 cents higher with active March at $6.335 a troy
ounce and spot December at $6.19. Platinum was $7.50 to $15 higher
with January at $615.90 a troy ounce.
   Copper futures sold off sharply in afternoon trading on the
Commodity Exchange on profit-taking ahead of the weekend and
uncertainty over the labor situation in Peru, where mineworkers have
been on strike for more than six weeks, analysts said.
   Copper settled .30 cent to 3.8 cents lower with December at
$1.502 a pound.
   Cattle futures prices plummeted on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange on mostly technical selling triggered when the price for
December delivery of live cattle slipped below 72 cents a pound.
   ``The market's kicking its foot in the dirt because it's kind of
disappointed it hasn't gone above 75 cents yet,'' said Jerry Gidel,
an analyst in Chicago with the G.H. Miller division of LIT America
Inc.
   Live cattle settled .52 cent to 1.42 cents lower with December at
71.50 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .45 cent to .83 cent lower
with January at 82.32 cents a pound; live hogs were .48 cent lower
to .35 cent higher with December at 40.35 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .30 cent to .43 cent higher with February at 45.37
cents a pound.
   Soybean futures prices settled sharply higher on the Chicago
Board of Trade on reduced chances for a wet weekend in the South
American soybean belt and strong gains in the soybean oil market.
Grain futures finished mostly higher.
   Concerns about the unusually dry weather in Brazil and Argentina,
the world's second- and fourth-largest soybean producers, have
become the dominant factor in the U.S. soybean futures market since
planting began in those countries earlier this fall.
   Forecasts for a rainy weekend in Brazil had prompted active
selling of futures on Thursday but Friday's forecasts indicated
chances for rain were diminishing, and that sparked a rally,
analysts said.
   Wheat settled 1 cent lower to 3 cents higher with December at
$4.19 a bushel; corn was 1\ cents lower to 1{ cents higher with
December at $2.58} a bushel; oats were 3 cents to 5{ cents higher
with December at $1.94\ a bushel; soybeans were 8 cents to 10} cents
higher with January at $7.68} a bushel.
   Crude oil prices rose while gasoline and heating oil futures
finished mostly lower in light trading on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude settled 3 cents to 4 cents higher
with January at $15.64 a barrel; heating oil was .22 cent lower to
.08 cent higher with January at 48.96 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .20 cent to .45 cent lower with January at 45.57 cents
a gallon.
   Stock-index futures retreated slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 settled .70 point lower at 272.50. Each point is worth
$500.
</TEXT>
