<HEAD>Universal Foods Chairman Says He'll Fight Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Universal Foods Corp. Chairman Jack Murray says
he will ask his company's board of directors to fight a $520 million
takeover bid from a Massachusetts company.
   The cash tender offer, launched Thursday by Amanda Acquisition
Corp., a subsidiary of High Voltage Engineering Corp., amounted to
$30.50 a share for the 96 percent of Universal stock it does not own.
   Murray said Friday the company is not for sale, although
officials of High Voltage said earlier they had no plans to move the
Milwaukee-based food processing company.
   ``We have absolutely no intention of moving the company out of
Milwaukee or changing the senior management,'' said Clifford Press,
deputy chairman of High Voltage Engineering, based in Burlington,
Mass.
   Universal had net income last year of $24.8 million, or $2.10 a
share, on revenue of $711.5 million. High Voltage had sales of about
$112 million last year.
   Press said the offer would be financed by $340 million from Chase
Manhattan Bank and the remainder from Hyde Park Parners, a company
he owns with Laurence Levy.
   Levy dismissed Murray's objections, saying: ``With all due
respect, it is not up to senior management to elect whether the
company's for sale. It's up to the shareholders.''
