<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Pepperell-Farley     12-02 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pepperell-Farley,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farley Calls for Special Meeting of Pepperell Shareholders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farley Inc. said Friday it would ask shareholders
of textile giant West Point-Pepperell Inc. to hold a special meeting
to consider Farley's $1.4 billion tender offer to acquire Pepperell.
   Spokesman David Kronfeld of West Point, Ga.-based Pepperell said
the company would have no comment on Farley's request.
   Farley, Chicago-based owner of Fruit of the Loom underwear and
other companies, extended its offer Thursday, saying it had garnered
nearly 50 percent of Pepperell's stock. The offer, which was to
expire at midnight Wednesday, was extended by one week to midnight
EST Dec. 7.
   Farley said today that Pepperell shareholders of record as of
Monday are entitled to call for a special meeting. Under Georgia
law, the company said, Pepperell management must call such a meeting
if shareholders of record of 25 percent of outstanding shares
support it.
   ``Our intention has always been to conduct friendy negotiations
on a mutually acceptable business combination, but Pepperell
management refuses to talk to us and has impeded shareholders from
even considering our offer,'' said chairman William Farley in a
statement.
   ``We have no choice but to seek a special meeting where
shareholders can decide for themselves whether our $48-per-share
cash tender offer should succeed,'' he said. ``Shareholders have
that right.''
   Farley officials said Thursday a preliminary count showed that
about 11.4 million shares of Pepperell's common stock had been
tendered by shareholders as of the close of business Wednesday. With
the shares Farley already owns, that would give the company about 49
percent of Pepperell's stock.
   Farley officials have declined to say how much of the Georgia
company's stock they hope to acquire.
   An appeals court has scheduled a hearing the week of Jan. 9 to
determine the fate of Pepperell's ``poison pill'' shareholder rights
plan, designed to thwart hostile takeovers. Farley's offer is
contingent on getting the plan overturned.
   Farley also has gone to court to challenge the constitutionality
of Georgia's anti-takeover law, but no hearing date has been set on
that issue.
</TEXT>
