<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Pillsbury     12-02 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pillsbury,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury's Sales Called No Surprise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZANNE MALICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co., the object of a $5.23 billion
hostile takeover bid, announced Friday it has agreed to sell its
Grain Merchandising Division, a chain of restaurants and a food
division.
   Pillsbury spokesman Larry Haeg denied that the sales, terms of
which were not disclosed, were made in reaction to the takeover
attempt.
   ``It is consistent with the restructuring effort that was
underway for quite some time to focus in on our core businesses,''
said Haeg, who added that plans to sell the Grain Merchandising
Division were announced July 25.
   Grand Metropolitan PLC's takeover efforts first came to light in
early October, he noted.
   Grand Met, a British liquor and gambling conglomerate, launched
its $60-a-share, all-cash tender offer for Pillsbury on Oct. 4.
Grand Met's fifth offer was set to expire at midnight EST Friday
unless extended again.
   Haeg declined to comment on Pillsbury's plans Friday. ``As a
matter of policy, we have never responded to those offers,'' he said.
   Grand Met spokesman Walter Montgomery refused to comment on what
Grand Met planned to do once the offer expired. He also wouldn't say
if Grand Met had heard from Pillsbury.
   Pillsbury sold its Grain Merchandising Division to ConAgra Inc.,
a diversified food company based in Omaha, Neb., with annual sales
of $9.5 billion.
   The Pillsbury division consists of 50 grain facilities primarily
in the Upper Midwest and about 200 river barges that are owned or
leased by Pillsbury, Haeg said.
   ConAgra spokeswoman Lynn Phares said the company ``fully expects
to hire a large percentage of those employees.'' Haeg said about 750
people are currently employed at the Grain Merchandising Division.
   The sale should be completed by the end of January, said Phares,
vice president of public relations at ConAgra.
   Haeg said it was not known how much the division was worth, but
said it was part of the company's industrial foods division, which
had sales of $416 million last year.
   The Minneapolis-based food and restaurant giant also said it was
selling Bay Street, a chain of 12 seafood restaurants based in
Dallas. The chain was sold to Bay Street Restaurant Inc., a
management group led by Bay Street General Manager Alan R. Palmieri
and Bill Bouffard, president of Restaurant Capital Corp., an
investment group, Pillsbury said in a statement.
   Also sold was Ashford Creameries, a division of Fiesta Foods Ltd.
of the United Kingdom, marketer of frozen desserts and ice cream. It
was sold to London-based Hillsdown Holdings PLC.
</TEXT>
