<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1937EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-RKO-Disney     12-02 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-RKO-Disney,0689</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disney Purchase of L.A. TV Station from RKO Completed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RKO General Inc. on Friday completed the
$320 million sale of Los Angeles television station KHJ to The Walt
Disney Co., marking a milestone toward ending a 23-year dispute
between RKO and federal regulators.
   Of the purchase price, $103 million, or 32 percent, goes to a
broadcast company that challenged the fitness of RKO and its parent,
GenCorp, to hold a broadcaster's license. GenCorp, based in
Fairlawn, Ohio, gets $217 million, the companies said.
   The payment to the challenger, Fidelity Television Inc., was
ordered by the Federal Communications Commission as part of a
settlement of license challenges based on allegations of improper
billings and other FCC rule violations by RKO.
   The commission stripped RKO of one television license in 1980,
and, in effect, is forcing the company to sell KHJ and its 13 other
radio and TV stations on unfavorable terms.
   Sale of KHJ, the biggest of RKO's stations and the starting point
of the dispute, is intended to serve as a model for disposal of the
rest of the stations.
   ``This signals a watershed event for us,'' said GenCorp spokesman
Rip Tilden. ``We're out of operation of KHJ-TV ... We're getting out
of the broadcast business.''
   The sale was completed a day after KHJ's broadcast license came
up for renewal and was awarded to Los Angeles-based Fidelity. The
sale agreement calls for Disney to run the station and for Fidelity
to eventually transfer the license to Disney.
   The sale was set up by a settlement among RKO, various
competitors and the FCC that was approved by the commission in July.
The arrangement, which FCC records indicate was intended to both
punish RKO and bring the dispute to a speedy end, calls for sale of
the company's remaining properties _ a TV station and nine radio
stations _ on similar terms.
   RKO's trouble with the FCC began in 1965, when Fidelity
challenged its fitness to hold a license for KHJ. In that complaint
and in other challenges ultimately filed to all RKO's licenses, the
company's business practices and the corporate character of its
parent, then known as General Tire & Rubber Co., were called into
question.
   In a 1980 ruling that stripped RKO of its license to run WNAC-TV
in Boston, the commission found that GenCorp, RKO and the various
stations had engaged in improper billing, submission of false
financial statements and demonstrated lack of concern for FCC rules
and federal laws.
   In weighing the challenges, the commission also considered
evidence General Tire had engaged in ``schemes which defrauded
partially owned affiliate companies of millions of dollars,'' made
improper political contributions and bribed foreign officials to
further its business interests, according to FCC records.
   GenCorp spokesman Tilden noted the company hasn't acknowledged
any violations of FCC rules. He said the decision to sell all the
stations and eliminate RKO is in keeping with a GenCorp business
strategy of focusing on its main industrial operations, which
include making aerospace and automotive components and plastic
products.
   ``We feel we are perfectly fit to operate a broadcast station,''
Tilden said.
   One of the unusual aspects of the settlement is the FCC's
allowing Disney _ which wasn't a part of the license challenges _ to
enter as a ``white knight'' to buy KHJ.
   ``We've always taken a position with the commission that we
thought Disney would be a nice opportunity to get someone in there
to resolve what has been a messy situation for 20 years,'' said Neil
McCarthy, the Disney vice president who arranged the deal.
   Sale agreements similar to the KHJ deal have been approved for
RKO's WHBQ-AM in Memphis, Tenn.; WGMS-AM in Bethesda, Md.; WGMS-FM
in Washington, D.C., and WRKO-AM and WROR-FM in Boston.
   The company is seeking buyers for WOR-AM and WRKS-FM in New York
City; KRTH-AM and KRTH-FM in Los Angeles; KFRC-AM in San Francisco;,
WAXY-FM in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.; WFYR-FM in Chicago; and WHBQ-TV in
Memphis.
</TEXT>
