<1ST_LINE>d f PM-OilPrices     12-02 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures closed the week on a high note as
investors remained optimistic that OPEC would stick to its latest
production agreement.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange Friday, the January contract
for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil,
settled 3 cents higher at $15.64 after trading as high as $15.74.
Other contract months also advanced slightly.
   Refined petroleum products traded on the exchange were mostly
lower in what analysts said were technical factors.
   The January contract for unleaded gasoline declined 0.41 cent to
settle at 45.57 cents a gallon, while other contract months also
fell. January heating oil closed down 0.22 cent at 48.96 cents a
gallon, while other contract months finished mixed.
   Analysts said the optimism begun after last Monday's decision by
OPEC to drastically reduce production managed to carry through the
week despite skepticism that the agreement would last.
   ``Two weeks ago you couldn't find a bull; now you can't find a
bear,'' said Jim Fiedler, vice president in charge of energy
brokering for E.D.&F. Man International Futures Inc.
   The 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
agreed Monday to reduce its volume by about 4 million barrels a day
to 18.5 million barrels. The cartel also agreed to maintain its old
benchmark price of $18 a barrel.
   Immediately after the announcement, oil prices surged to $15.80 a
barrel, its high for the week, leveled off on Tuesday, then climbed
the rest of the week but failed to reach Monday's highs.
   Statements of support for the agreement from various OPEC
representatives during the week helped keep prices strong, analysts
said. In addition, prices were supported by talk that non-OPEC
producing nations were considering the possibility of reducing their
output to help soak up the current world oil glut and ensure the
success of the accord.
   Analysts and brokers remained mixed in their assessment of where
prices would head in coming weeks.
   Mike Hiley, a broker for Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., saidthe
market is unlikely to make further headway until it receives
confirmation of whether OPEC will stick to its agreement. Until
then, he believes prices will drift in the $15 range of this week.
   ``OPEC has milked the agreement for all it's worth and now the
market is waiting until January to what's going to happen,'' Hiley
said.
   The OPEC accord is scheduled to take effect Jan. 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
