<DOCNO> AP881202-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 1948EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Zenith-Brookhurst     12-02 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zenith-Brookhurst,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brookhurst Bows Out Of Zenith Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dissident group of shareholders ended an attempt
to gain control of Zenith Electronics Corp. Friday, saying it was
satisfied the company was taking steps to improve the value of its
shares.
   The announcement ends the takeover battle that was launched Oct.
12 by Brookhurst Partners of New York, owner of 6.1 percent of
Zenith's stock.
   ``The continuing efforts of Zenith's management and board have
persuaded the company's shareholders that Zenith is pursuing
programs that will maximize shareholder value,'' said Herbert B.
Abelow, a leader of Brookhurst Partners.
   Zenith President Jerry K. Pearlman said his company would
continue discussions with other companies to find ways to bolster
the stock. The company has in the past said it might consider joint
ventures or the sale of some of its operations.
   ``We appreciate the keen interest our shareholders have shown in
the future of Zenith,'' Pearlman said in a statement.
   In their joint statement, Brookhurst and Zenith said they had
agreed to terminate all lawsuits they had pending against each other.
   Brookhurst, headed by stock-market speculators Abelow and
Nicholas Ihasz, had asked Zenith shareholders to support a plan to
seize control of the company's board and, in turn, sell Zenith's
ailing consumer-electronics division.
   Brookhurst had said that if it couldn't find a buyer for the
electronics unit, it would attempt to sell the entire company, which
is the last major U.S. manufacturer of television sets.
   Zenith, based in the Chicago suburb of Glenview, also makes
personal computers.
   Brookhurst's plan called for reducing the size of Zenith's board
from 10 directors to six and replacing some directors with its own
candidates.
   Brookhurst has cited Zenith's dismal earnings in recent years as
the reason for the unusual takeover bid.
   Zenith has posted multimillion-dollar losses in each of the past
three years but the company reported a $3 million profit for the
third quarter of 1988. It expects to show a pre-tax profit at the
end of this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
